          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No NFS mounts were found in '/etc/fstab'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep nfs /etc/fstab | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nChecking for NFS mounts in '/etc/fstab':\n\ud83d\udd36 No NFS mounts were found in '/etc/fstab'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1da501f5-063c-4d31-9ef4-e86c54d3efb0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-274877",
          "group_id_src": "V-274877",
          "rule_id": "SV-274877r1155381",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-274877r1155381_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030655",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must audit any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to audit the execution of any system call made by cron as root or as any privileged user.\n\nAdd or update the following file system rules to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n-w /etc/cron.d/ -p wa -k cronjobs\n-w /var/spool/cron/ -p wa -k cronjobs\n\nTo load the rules to the kernel immediately, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo augenrules --load",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must audit any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Any script or executable called by cron as root or by any privileged user must be owned by that user, must have the permissions set to 755 or more restrictive, and have no extended rights that allow a nonprivileged user to modify the script or executable.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 is configured to audit the execution of any system call made by cron as root or as any privileged user.\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /etc/cron.d\n-w /etc/cron.d -p wa -k cronjobs\n\n$ sudo auditctl -l | grep /var/spool/cron\n-w /var/spool/cron -p wa -k cronjobs\n\nIf either of these commands do not return the expected output, or the lines are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-274877"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000172"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-274877",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following audit lines are missing for the events '/etc/cron.d':\n-w /etc/cron.d -p wa -k cronjobs\nThe following audit lines are missing for the events '/var/spool/cron':\n-w /var/spool/cron -p wa -k cronjobs",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/cron.d\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /var/spool/cron\n\nChecking that the OS is configured to audit the execution of the '/etc/cron.d' events:\n\u274c Missing: -w /etc/cron.d -p wa -k cronjobs\n\n\nChecking that the OS is configured to audit the execution of the '/var/spool/cron' events:\n\u274c Missing: -w /var/spool/cron -p wa -k cronjobs\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1dab0167-30a2-4f7a-9ba9-7ac114d805c4",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230343",
          "group_id_src": "V-230343",
          "rule_id": "SV-230343r1017155",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230343r1017155_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020021",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/Modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\naudit",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Note: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.2 or newer, if the system is RHEL version 8.0 or 8.1, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur:\n\n$ sudo grep audit /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\naudit\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is not set, is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230343"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230343",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'audit' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -E '^[[:space:]]*audit' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nChecking the version of RHEL:\n\ud83d\udd0d The RHEL version is '8.10'. \nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file is configured to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur:\n\u274c The 'audit' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1e82c11f-24dd-417f-b217-af840fb51d74",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230304",
          "group_id_src": "V-230304",
          "rule_id": "SV-230304r1017114",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230304r1017114_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010610",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system not to execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"noexec\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"noexec\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230304"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230304",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No removable media found",
          "finding_details": "#fstab_file=\"/etc/fstab\"\nremovable_media_found=false\n\nwhile read -r line; do\n    line=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/^[[:space:]]*//' -e 's/[[:space:]]*$//')\n    if [[ -n \"$line\" && ! \"$line\" =~ ^# ]]; then\n        fields=($line)\n        mount_point=${fields[1]}\n\n        # Check if the mount point is a removable media\n        transport=$(lsblk --output TRAN -n \"$mount_point\" 2>/dev/null)\n        if [[ -n \"$transport\" && \"$transport\" != \"loop\" ]]; then\n            echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n            echo \"Removable media found: $mount_point\"\n            echo \"$line\"\n            removable_media_found=true\n        fi\n    fi\ndone < \"$fstab_file\"\n\nif [[ \"$removable_media_found\" == false ]]; then\n    echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n    echo \"No removable media found\"\nfi\n\nChecking for 'noexec' option mounted removable media:\n\u2705 No removable media found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1ee9b921-33b5-4dc7-90ec-9284047980f5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230294",
          "group_id_src": "V-230294",
          "rule_id": "SV-230294r1017105",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230294r1017105_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010542",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must use a separate file system for the system audit data path.",
          "fix_text": "Migrate the system audit data path onto a separate file system.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must use a separate file system for the system audit data path.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.",
          "check_content": "Verify that a separate file system/partition has been created for the system audit data path with the following command:\n\nNote: /var/log/audit is used as the example as it is a common location.\n\n$ sudo grep /var/log/audit /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=3645951a /var/log/audit xfs defaults 1 2\n\nIf an entry for \"/var/log/audit\" does not exist, ask the System Administrator if the system audit logs are being written to a different file system/partition on the system, then grep for that file system/partition.\n\nIf a separate file system/partition does not exist for the system audit data path, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230294"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230294",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No entry for the system audit data path('/var/log/audit') was found in '/etc/fstab'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep '^log_file' /etc/audit/auditd.conf 2>/dev/null | cut -d\"=\" -f2 | xargs -I AUDDIR dirname AUDDIR\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep '^log_file' /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d\"=\" -f2 | xargs -I AUDDIR dirname AUDDIR | xargs -I SEARCHDIR grep SEARCHDIR /etc/fstab\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab\n\nDetermining the system audit data path from '/etc/audit/audit.d.conf':\n\ud83d\udd0d /var/log/audit\n\nChecking '/etc/fstab' for an entry for '/var/log/audit':\n\u274c No entry for the system audit data path('/var/log/audit') was found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1ef9b24c-f6b5-4417-91df-c776f8e378e3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244554",
          "group_id_src": "V-244554",
          "rule_id": "SV-244554r1017354",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244554r1017354_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040286",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter Just-in-time compiler.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to enable hardening for the BPF JIT compiler by adding the following line to a file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d\" directory:\n\nnet.core.bpf_jit_harden = 2\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter Just-in-time compiler.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nEnabling hardening for the Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF) Just-in-time (JIT) compiler aids in mitigating JIT spraying attacks. Setting the value to \"2\" enables JIT hardening for all users.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 enables hardening for the BPF JIT with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.core.bpf_jit_harden\n\nnet.core.bpf_jit_harden = 2\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"2\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.core.bpf_jit_harden /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.core.bpf_jit_harden = 2\n\nIf \"net.core.bpf_jit_harden\" is not set to \"2\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244554"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244554",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.core.bpf_jit_harden' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.core.bpf_jit_harden' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.core.bpf_jit_harden 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.core.bpf_jit_harden' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.core.bpf_jit_harden' variable:\n\u274c net.core.bpf_jit_harden = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.core.bpf_jit_harden' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.core.bpf_jit_harden' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1f147984-1de5-4146-aa01-dc673606d33c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230534",
          "group_id_src": "V-230534",
          "rule_id": "SV-230534r1017296",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230534r1017296_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040200",
          "rule_title": "The root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to the RHEL 8 system.",
          "fix_text": "Change the UID of any account on the system, other than root, that has a UID of \"0\".\n\nIf the account is associated with system commands or applications, the UID should be changed to one greater than \"0\" but less than \"1000\". Otherwise, assign a UID of greater than \"1000\" that has not already been assigned.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The root account must be the only account having unrestricted access to the RHEL 8 system.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If an account other than root also has a User Identifier (UID) of \"0\", it has root authority, giving that account unrestricted access to the entire operating system. Multiple accounts with a UID of \"0\" afford an opportunity for potential intruders to guess a password for a privileged account.",
          "check_content": "Check the system for duplicate UID \"0\" assignments with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd\n\nIf any accounts other than root have a UID of \"0\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230534"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230534",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No accounts other than 'root' have a UID of '0'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nawk -F: '$3 == 0 {print $1}' /etc/passwd | grep -v 'root'\n\nChecking the system for duplicate UID '0' assignments:\n\u2705 No accounts other than 'root' have a UID of '0'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "1f7ac491-772a-410a-b712-91007473c3fc",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230375",
          "group_id_src": "V-230375",
          "rule_id": "SV-230375r1017187",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230375r1017187_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020280",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 passwords must contain at least one special character.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used by setting the \"ocredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to /etc/security/pwquality.conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nocredit = -1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 passwords must contain at least one special character.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Note that to require special characters without degrading the \"minlen\" value, the credit value must be expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".",
          "check_content": "Verify the value for \"ocredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:ocredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"ocredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
