          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230375",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000266-GPOS-00101",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'ocredit' setting is commented out in '/etc/security/pwquality.conf'.\nAll 'ocredit' settings are commented out in all 'pwquality.conf' files in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -r ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'ocredit':\n\u274c /etc/security/pwquality.conf:# ocredit = 0\n\u274c All 'ocredit' settings are commented out in all 'pwquality.conf' files in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2045f208-7e11-48e4-a7d4-58617a6ecb86",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230385",
          "group_id_src": "V-230385",
          "rule_id": "SV-230385r1017194",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230385r1017194_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020353",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must define default permissions for logon and non-logon shells.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the lines for the \"UMASK\" parameter in the \"/etc/bashrc\", \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" and \"/etc/profile\"files to \"077\":\n\nUMASK 077",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must define default permissions for logon and non-logon shells.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the umask default for installed shells is \"077\".\n\nCheck for the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter in the \"/etc/bashrc\", \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" and \"/etc/profile\" files with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter is set to \"000\" in the \"/etc/bashrc\" the \"/etc/csh.cshrc\" or the \"/etc/profile\" files, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n# grep -i umask /etc/bashrc /etc/csh.cshrc /etc/profile\n\n/etc/bashrc:          umask 077\n/etc/bashrc:          umask 077\n/etc/csh.cshrc:      umask 077\n/etc/csh.cshrc:      umask 077\n/etc/profile:      umask 077\n/etc/profile:      umask 077\n\nIf the value for the \"UMASK\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"UMASK\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230385"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230385",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "A 'UMASK' parameter is set to '002' in '/etc/bashrc'\nA 'UMASK' parameter is set to '022' in '/etc/bashrc'\nA 'UMASK' parameter is set to '002' in '/etc/csh.cshrc'\nA 'UMASK' parameter is set to '022' in '/etc/csh.cshrc'\nA 'UMASK' parameter is set to '002' in '/etc/profile'\nA 'UMASK' parameter is set to '022' in '/etc/profile'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i umask /etc/bashrc | grep -Ev \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i umask /etc/csh.cshrc | grep -v \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i umask /etc/profile | grep -v \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\n\nChecking the 'UMASK' parameter in '/etc/bashrc':\n\u274c umask 002\n\u274c umask 022\n\nChecking the 'UMASK' parameter in '/etc/csh.cshrc':\n\u274c umask 002\n\u274c umask 022\n\nChecking the 'UMASK' parameter in '/etc/profile':\n\u274c umask 002\n\u274c umask 022\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "20afebbb-6537-4d6c-8e50-f0ffa3a7fd14",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230318",
          "group_id_src": "V-230318",
          "rule_id": "SV-230318r1155352",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230318r1155352_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010700",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 world-writable directories must be owned by root, sys, bin, or an application user.",
          "fix_text": "Configure all RHEL 8 public directories to be owned by root or a system account to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.\n\nUse the following command template to set ownership of public directories to root or a system account:\n\n$ sudo chown [root or system account] [Public Directory]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 world-writable directories must be owned by root, sys, bin, or an application user.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If a world-writable directory is not owned by root, sys, bin, or an application User Identifier (UID), unauthorized users may be able to modify files created by others.\n\nThe only authorized public directories are those temporary directories supplied with the system or those designed to be temporary file repositories. The setting is normally reserved for directories used by the system and by users for temporary file storage, (e.g., /tmp), and for directories requiring global read/write access.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 world writable directories are owned by root, a system account, or an application account with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -xdev -type d -perm -0002 -uid +999 -exec stat -c \"%U, %u, %A, %n\" {} \\; 2>/dev/null\n\nIf there is output that indicates world-writable directories are owned by any account other than root or an approved system account, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230318"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230318",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "There are no world-writable directories that are not owned by a system account",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndf --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | xargs -I PART find PART -xdev -type d -perm -0002  -uid +999 -print 2>/dev/null |xargs -I FILENAME stat -c \"%U %n\" FILENAME\n\nChecking for world-writable directories that are not owned by a system account:\n\u2705 There are no world-writable directories that are not owned by a system account\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "20b9eb8b-cf02-4131-9609-0f98c8065b23",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230481",
          "group_id_src": "V-230481",
          "rule_id": "SV-230481r958754",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230481r958754_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030710",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must encrypt the transfer of audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to encrypt off-loaded audit records by setting the following options in \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/[customfile].conf\":\n\n$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls\n$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must encrypt the transfer of audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 8 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\".  \"rsyslogd\" is a system utility providing support for message logging.  Support for both internet and UNIX domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging.  Couple this utility with \"gnutls\" (which is a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols), and you have a method to securely encrypt and off-load auditing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system encrypts audit records off-loaded onto a different system or media from the system being audited with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep -i '$DefaultNetstreamDriver' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls\n\nIf the value of the \"$DefaultNetstreamDriver\" option is not set to \"gtls\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\n$ sudo grep -i '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:$ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1\n\nIf the value of the \"$ActionSendStreamDriverMode\" option is not set to \"1\" or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf neither of the definitions above are set, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being off-loaded to another system or media is encrypted, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230481"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001851"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230481",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' setting was not found in '/etc/rsyslog.conf' or any '.conf' file in '/etc/rsyslog.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i '$DefaultNetstreamDriver' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the '$DefaultNetstreamDriver' setting:\n\u274c The '$DefaultNetstreamDriver' setting was not found\n\nChecking for the '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' setting:\n\u274c The '$ActionSendStreamDriverMode' setting was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "211c0e93-586a-4966-9bc0-e9e285dcbc50",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230511",
          "group_id_src": "V-230511",
          "rule_id": "SV-230511r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230511r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040123",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /tmp with the nodev option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /tmp is mounted with the \"nodev\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-tmp /tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /tmp with the nodev option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/tmp\" is mounted with the \"nodev\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-tmp on /tmp type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"nodev\" option is configured for /tmp:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-tmp /tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"nodev\" option is missing, or if /tmp is mounted without the \"nodev\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230511"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230511",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n'/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /tmp\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /tmp\n\nChecking if '/tmp' is mounted with 'nodev' option:\n\u274c '/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'nodev' is configured for '/tmp':\n\u274c '/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2133d330-a4f9-486f-8710-39d978cfed2d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-257258",
          "group_id_src": "V-257258",
          "rule_id": "SV-257258r1069328",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-257258r1069328_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020035",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8.7 and higher must terminate idle user sessions.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to log out idle sessions after 10 minutes by editing the /etc/systemd/logind.conf file with the following line:\n\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\n\nThe \"logind\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"logind\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart systemd-logind",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8.7 and higher must terminate idle user sessions.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Terminating an idle session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended.",
          "check_content": "Note: This requirement applies to RHEL versions 8.7 and higher. If the system is not RHEL version 8.7 or newer, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nNote: For cloud hosted systems where \"ClientAliveInterval\" (V-244525) is configured, this setting is not applicable.\n\nVerify that RHEL 8 logs out sessions that are idle for 10 minutes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i ^StopIdleSessionSec /etc/systemd/logind.conf\n\nStopIdleSessionSec=600\n\nIf \"StopIdleSessionSec\" is not configured to \"600\" seconds, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-257258"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001133"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-257258",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'StopIdleSessionSec' setting does not exist in '/etc/systemd/logind.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Ei '^[[:space:]]*StopIdleSessionSec' /etc/systemd/logind.conf\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\ud83d\udd0d Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\nThe version of Red Hat is '8.10'\n\nChecking the 'StopIdleSessionSec' setting in '/etc/systemd/logind.conf':\n\u274c The 'StopIdleSessionSec' setting does not exist in '/etc/systemd/logind.conf'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "22742bc4-84d5-4454-bf5c-fa0b0ae7ad7a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230360",
          "group_id_src": "V-230360",
          "rule_id": "SV-230360r1017172",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230360r1017172_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020140",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to require the change of the number of repeating characters of the same character class when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxclassrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxclassrepeat = 4\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must require the maximum number of repeating characters of the same character class be limited to four when passwords are changed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. The \"maxclassrepeat\" option sets the maximum number of allowed same consecutive characters in the same class in the new password.",
          "check_content": "Check for the value of the \"maxclassrepeat\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r maxclassrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:maxclassrepeat = 4\n\nIf the value of \"maxclassrepeat\" is set to \"0\", more than \"4\" or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230360"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000195"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230360",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'maxclassrepeat' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*maxclassrepeat' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'maxclassrepeat':\n\u274c The 'maxclassrepeat' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2299e775-b58d-44f0-a736-be8b41f955c5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230546",
          "group_id_src": "V-230546",
          "rule_id": "SV-230546r1155413",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230546r1155413_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040282",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict usage of ptrace to descendant  processes.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to restrict usage of ptrace to descendant processes by adding the following line in a dropfile, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d\" directory with the following commands:\n\nCreate the dropfile if it doesn't already exist:\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-ptrace-restrict.conf\n\nAdd the following line to the file:\nkernel.yama.ptrace_scope = 1\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict usage of ptrace to descendant  processes.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore, may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 restricts usage of ptrace to descendant processes with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl kernel.yama.ptrace_scope\n\nkernel.yama.ptrace_scope = 1\n\nIf \"kernel.yama.ptrace_scope\" is not set to \"1\", is missing, or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230546"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230546",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'kernel.yama.ptrace_scope' variable is set to '0' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '1'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.yama.ptrace_scope 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'kernel.yama.ptrace_scope' variable:\n\u274c kernel.yama.ptrace_scope = 0\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "22d70578-b600-4fba-8ed0-d34cc3482022",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230357",
          "group_id_src": "V-230357",
          "rule_id": "SV-230357r1017169",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230357r1017169_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020110",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used by setting the \"ucredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to /etc/security/pwquality.conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nucredit = -1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes pwquality as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Note that in order to require uppercase characters, without degrading the \"minlen\" value, the credit value must be expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".",
          "check_content": "Verify the value for \"ucredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r ucredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:ucredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"ucredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230357"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000192",
            "CCI-004066"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230357",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000069-GPOS-00037",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'ucredit' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*ucredit' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'ucredit':\n\u274c The 'ucredit' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "242cd06c-70c7-4d9a-9bd2-8e407bf83e8b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230330",
          "group_id_src": "V-230330",
          "rule_id": "SV-230330r1069305",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230330r1069305_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010830",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to allow the SSH daemon to not allow unattended or automatic logon to the system.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file:\n\nPermitUserEnvironment no\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow users to override SSH environment variables.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "SSH environment options potentially allow users to bypass access restriction in some configurations.",
          "check_content": "Verify that unattended or automatic logon via ssh is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permituserenvironment'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:PermitUserEnvironment no\n\nIf \"PermitUserEnvironment\" is set to \"yes\", is missing completely, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230330"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230330",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'PermitUserEnvironment' keyword is set to 'no' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'PermitUserEnvironment' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 permituserenvironment no\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "243f778f-df32-4a69-b6bd-b2bda33ad279",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230288",
          "group_id_src": "V-230288",
          "rule_id": "SV-230288r1069301",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230288r1069301_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010500",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files.",
          "fix_text": "Configure SSH to perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files. Uncomment the \"StrictModes\" keyword in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" and set the value to \"yes\":\n\nStrictModes yes\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must perform strict mode checking of home directory configuration files.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If other users have access to modify user-specific SSH configuration files, they may be able to log on to the system as another user.",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH daemon performs strict mode checking of home directory configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*strictmodes'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:StrictModes yes\n\nIf \"StrictModes\" is set to \"no\", is missing, or the returned line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230288"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230288",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'StrictModes' keyword is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'StrictModes' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 strictmodes yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "24436638-edab-4c6f-985b-69ff03c866e5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230286",
          "group_id_src": "V-230286",
          "rule_id": "SV-230286r1017097",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230286r1017097_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010480",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH public host key files must have mode 0644 or less permissive.",
          "fix_text": "Change the mode of public host key files under \"/etc/ssh\" to \"0644\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0644 /etc/ssh/*key.pub\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH public host key files must have mode 0644 or less permissive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If a public host key file is modified by an unauthorized user, the SSH service may be compromised.",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH public host key files have mode \"0644\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -l /etc/ssh/*.pub\n\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 618 Nov 28 06:43 ssh_host_dsa_key.pub\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 347 Nov 28 06:43 ssh_host_key.pub\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 238 Nov 28 06:43 ssh_host_rsa_key.pub\n\nIf any key.pub file has a mode more permissive than \"0644\", this is a finding.\n\nNote: SSH public key files may be found in other directories on the system depending on the installation.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230286"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230286",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All public host key files have permissions of '644' or less permissive",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nstat -c \"%a:%n\" /etc/ssh/*.pub\n\nChecking permissions of public host key files:\n\u2705 644:/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key.pub\n\u2705 644:/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key.pub\n\u2705 644:/etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key.pub\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "25b8fe63-70c1-402d-aebb-08b7dc34387f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230305",
          "group_id_src": "V-230305",
          "rule_id": "SV-230305r1017115",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230305r1017115_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010620",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230305"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230305",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No removable media found",
          "finding_details": "#fstab_file=\"/etc/fstab\"\nremovable_media_found=false\n\nwhile read -r line; do\n    line=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/^[[:space:]]*//' -e 's/[[:space:]]*$//')\n    if [[ -n \"$line\" && ! \"$line\" =~ ^# ]]; then\n        fields=($line)\n        mount_point=${fields[1]}\n\n        # Check if the mount point is a removable media\n        transport=$(lsblk --output TRAN -n \"$mount_point\" 2>/dev/null)\n        if [[ -n \"$transport\" && \"$transport\" != \"loop\" ]]; then\n            echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n            echo \"Removable media found: $mount_point\"\n            echo \"$line\"\n            removable_media_found=true\n        fi\n    fi\ndone < \"$fstab_file\"\n\nif [[ \"$removable_media_found\" == false ]]; then\n    echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n    echo \"No removable media found\"\nfi\n\nChecking for 'nosuid' option mounted removable media:\n\u2705 No removable media found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "268fb089-6a4c-496c-bbad-c765111b7d1c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230285",
          "group_id_src": "V-230285",
          "rule_id": "SV-230285r1017096",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230285r1017096_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010471",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable the hardware random number generator entropy gatherer service.",
          "fix_text": "Start the rngd service and enable the rngd service with the following commands:\n\n     $ sudo systemctl start rngd.service\n\n     $ sudo systemctl enable rngd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable the hardware random number generator entropy gatherer service.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The most important characteristic of a random number generator is its randomness, namely its ability to deliver random numbers that are impossible to predict. Entropy in computer security is associated with the unpredictability of a source of randomness.  The random source with high entropy tends to achieve a uniform distribution of random values. Random number generators are one of the most important building blocks of cryptosystems.\n\nThe rngd service feeds random data from hardware device to kernel random device. Quality (nonpredictable) random number generation is important for several security functions (i.e., ciphers).",
          "check_content": "Note: For RHEL versions 8.4 and above running with kernel FIPS mode enabled as specified by RHEL-08-010020, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck that  RHEL 8 has enabled the hardware random number generator entropy gatherer service.\n\nVerify the rngd service is enabled and active with the following commands:\n\n     $ sudo systemctl is-enabled rngd\n     enabled\n\n     $ sudo systemctl is-active rngd\n     active\n\nIf the service is not \"enabled\" and \"active\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230285"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230285",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'rngd' service is set to 'Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)', but should be set to 'enabled'\nThe 'rngd' service is set to 'Installation of FIPS modules is not completed.\nFIPS mode is disabled.', but should be set to 'active'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nfips-mode-setup --check\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrub2-editenv list | grep kernelopts | grep fips\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsystemctl is-enabled rngd\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsystemctl is-active rngd\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\ud83d\udd0d The Red Hat version is '8.10'\n\nChecking if FIPS mode is 'enabled':\n\ud83d\udd0d FIPS mode is not 'enabled'\n\nChecking if 'kernel boot parameter' is configured to use FIPS:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'kernel boot parameter' is not configure for FIPS mode\n\nChecking if FIPS mode is 'active'\n\ud83d\udd0d FIPS mode is not active\n\nChecking if the 'rngd' server is 'enabled':\n\u274c The 'rngd' service is set to 'Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)'\n\nChecking if the 'rngd' server is 'active':\n\u274c The 'rngd' service is set to 'Installation of FIPS modules is not completed.\nFIPS mode is disabled.'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "27445897-e3a9-4549-bae3-6742ad55dc63",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230540",
          "group_id_src": "V-230540",
          "rule_id": "SV-230540r1017302",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230540r1017302_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040260",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not allow IPv6 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not enable IPv6 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 is not performing IPv6 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck that IPv6 forwarding is disabled using the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf the IPv6 forwarding value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230540"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230540",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding' setting.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl -a 2>/dev/null | grep 'net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if IPv6 is disabled on the system:\n\ud83d\udd0d IPv6 is not disabled\n\nChecking the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding' setting using 'sysctl':\n\u2705 net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nChecking for the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding' setting in configuration files:\n\u274c No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding' setting\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2804270e-c56f-42e2-a7e3-7723ec241b87",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230553",
          "group_id_src": "V-230553",
          "rule_id": "SV-230553r1017315",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230553r1017315_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040320",
          "rule_title": "The graphical display manager must not be installed on RHEL 8 unless approved.",
          "fix_text": "Document the requirement for a graphical user interface with the ISSO or reinstall the operating system without the graphical user interface. If reinstallation is not feasible, then continue with the following procedure:\n\nOpen an SSH session and enter the following commands:\n\n$ sudo yum remove xorg-x11-server-Xorg xorg-x11-server-common xorg-x11-server-utils xorg-x11-server-Xwayland\n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The graphical display manager must not be installed on RHEL 8 unless approved.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Internet services that are not required for system or application processes must not be active to decrease the attack surface of the system. Graphical display managers have a long history of security vulnerabilities and must not be used, unless approved and documented.",
          "check_content": "Verify that a graphical user interface is not installed:\n\n$ rpm -qa | grep xorg | grep server\n\nAsk the System Administrator if use of a graphical user interface is an operational requirement.\n\nIf the use of a graphical user interface on the system is not documented with the ISSO, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230553"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230553",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "A graphical user interface is installed, ask the SA if this is an operational requirement.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nrpm -qa | grep xorg | grep server\n\nChecking if a graphical user interface is installed:\n\ud83d\udd36 A graphical user interface is installed, ask the SA if this is an operational requirement.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "29360f26-2d4a-4687-b90c-bc40449712a1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230400",
          "group_id_src": "V-230400",
          "rule_id": "SV-230400r1017206",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230400r1017206_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030110",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must be group-owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log to be protected from unauthorized read access by setting the correct group-owner as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [audit_log_directory]\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_directory]\" with the correct audit log directory path, by default this location is usually \"/var/log/audit\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must be group-owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit RHEL 8 activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit log directory is group-owned by \"root\" to prevent unauthorized read access.\n\nDetermine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nDetermine the group owner of the audit log directory by using the output of the above command (ex: \"/var/log/audit/\"). Run the following command with the correct audit log directory path:\n\n$ sudo ls -ld /var/log/audit\n\ndrw------- 2 root root 23 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit log directory is not group-owned by \"root\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230400"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230400",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The group owner of '/var/log/audit' is 'root'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndirname /var/log/audit/audit.log | xargs -I DIR stat -c \"%G\" DIR \necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR | xargs stat -c \"%G\"\n\nDetermining the audit log directory:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log Directory: /var/log/audit\n\nChecking the group owner of '/var/log/audit':\n\u2705 Group Owner = root\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "293fc063-9d26-485a-8389-23c9326a3bd5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230291",
          "group_id_src": "V-230291",
          "rule_id": "SV-230291r1069303",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230291r1069303_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010521",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must not allow Kerberos authentication, except to fulfill documented and validated mission requirements.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the SSH daemon to not allow Kerberos authentication.\n\nAdd the following line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\", or uncomment the line and set the value to \"no\":\n\nKerberosAuthentication no\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must not allow Kerberos authentication, except to fulfill documented and validated mission requirements.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Configuring these settings for the SSH daemon provides additional assurance that remote logon via SSH will not use unused methods of authentication, even in the event of misconfiguration elsewhere.",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH daemon does not allow Kerberos authentication with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*kerberosauthentication'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:KerberosAuthentication no\n\nIf the value is returned as \"yes\", the returned line is commented out, no output is returned, or has not been documented with the information system security officer (ISSO), this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230291"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230291",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'KerberosAuthentication' keyword is set to 'no' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'KerberosAuthentication' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 kerberosauthentication no\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2a180d39-dd54-4e5a-93e6-553ec721dd93",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230333",
          "group_id_src": "V-230333",
          "rule_id": "SV-230333r1017145",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230333r1017145_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020011",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/Modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\ndeny = 3",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Note: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.2 or newer, if the system is RHEL version 8.0 or 8.1, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to lock an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts:\n\n$ sudo grep 'deny =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\ndeny = 3\n\nIf the \"deny\" option is not set to \"3\" or less (but not \"0\"), is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230333"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230333",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All 'deny' option entries are commented out in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep 'deny =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nChecking the version of RHEL:\n\ud83d\udd0d The RHEL version is '8.10'. \nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file is configured to lock an account after 3 unsuccessful logon attempts:\n\u274c # deny = 3\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2aad0efc-232f-448d-b34f-d8b3f94c08c5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244541",
          "group_id_src": "V-244541",
          "rule_id": "SV-244541r1017347",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244541r1017347_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020332",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow blank or null passwords in the password-auth file.",
          "fix_text": "Remove any instances of the \"nullok\" option in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nNote: Manual changes to the listed file may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow blank or null passwords in the password-auth file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.",
          "check_content": "To verify that null passwords cannot be used, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nIf output is produced, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244541"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244541",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'nullok' option was found on '2' lines in '/etc/pam.d/password-auth'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nChecking that null passwords cannont be used:\n\u274c auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\n\u274c password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2b1b9231-d2e1-4f67-9fb1-0af97d348a03",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230418",
          "group_id_src": "V-230418",
          "rule_id": "SV-230418r1017220",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230418r1017220_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030250",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chage command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"chage\" command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-chage\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chage command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"chage\" command is used to change or view user password expiry information.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"chage\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w chage /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chage -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-chage\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230418"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230418",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for 'chage' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for 'chage' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w chage /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w chage\n\nChecking for 'chage' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for 'chage' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the 'chage' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for 'chage' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2b441e32-f665-439e-9ec0-a152a063c751",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244522",
          "group_id_src": "V-244522",
          "rule_id": "SV-244522r1137691",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244522r1137691_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010149",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 operating systems booted with a BIOS must require  a unique superusers name upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system to have a unique name for the grub superusers account.\n\nEdit the /etc/grub.d/01_users file and add or modify the following lines:\n\nset superusers=\"[someuniquestringhere]\"\nexport superusers\npassword_pbkdf2 [someuniquestringhere] ${GRUB2_PASSWORD}\n\nGenerate a new grub.cfg file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 operating systems booted with a BIOS must require  a unique superusers name upon booting into single-user and maintenance modes.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If the system does not require valid authentication before it boots into single-user or maintenance mode, anyone who invokes single-user or maintenance mode is granted privileged access to all files on the system. GRUB 2 is the default boot loader for RHEL 8 and is designed to require a password to boot into single-user mode or make modifications to the boot menu.\n\nThe GRUB 2 superuser account is an account of last resort. Establishing a unique username for this account hardens the boot loader against brute force attacks. Due to the nature of the superuser account database being distinct from the OS account database, this allows the use of a username that is not among those within the OS account database. Examples of non-unique superusers names are root, superuser, unlock, etc.",
          "check_content": "For systems that use UEFI, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that a unique name is set as the \"superusers\" account:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw \"superusers\" /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\nset superusers=\"[someuniquestringhere]\"\nexport superusers\n\nIf \"superusers\" is identical to any OS account name or is missing a name, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244522"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000213"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244522",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000080-GPOS-00048",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'superusers' setting is set to 'root' and exists in '/etc/passwd'.\n    set superusers=\"root\"",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nls /sys/firmware/efi\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/passwd | cut -d: -f1\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n grep -iw \"superusers=\" /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n\nChecking if the systems uses UEFI:\n\ud83d\udd0d This system is not using 'UEFI'.\n\nChecking if an unique name is set as the 'superusers' account:\n\u274c The 'superusers' setting is set to 'root' and exists in '/etc/passwd'. \n    set superusers=\"root\"\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2b514ed0-1d9d-40a4-ac1b-52e04f6d91f2",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230559",
          "group_id_src": "V-230559",
          "rule_id": "SV-230559r1155398",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230559r1155398_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040370",
          "rule_title": "The gssproxy package must not be installed unless mission essential on RHEL 8.",
          "fix_text": "Document the gssproxy package with the ISSO as an operational requirement or remove it from the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum remove gssproxy",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The gssproxy package must not be installed unless mission essential on RHEL 8.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nThe gssproxy package is a proxy for GSS API credential handling and could expose secrets on some networks. It is not needed for normal function of the OS.",
          "check_content": "Note: If NFS mounts are authorized and in use on the system, this control is not applicable.\n\nVerify the gssproxy package is not installed with the following command:\n\n$ dnf list --installed gssproxy\n\nError: No matching Packages to list\n\nIf the \"gssproxy\" package is installed and is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230559"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230559",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'gssproxy' package (gssproxy.x86_64                       0.8.0-21.el8                       @baseos) is installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndf -hT | grep nfs\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed gssproxy\n\nChecking if the 'gssproxy' package is installed:\n\u274c The 'gssproxy' package ('gssproxy.x86_64                       0.8.0-21.el8                       @baseos') is installed.\n\nChecking if NFS mounts are being used:\n\ud83d\udd0d NFS mounts are not being used\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2b5e85c9-6e30-494b-a3e3-82f4eba82450",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230351",
          "group_id_src": "V-230351",
          "rule_id": "SV-230351r1017164",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230351r1017164_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020050",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be able to initiate directly a session lock for all connection types using smartcard when the smartcard is removed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enable a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nSelect/Create an authselect profile and incorporate the \"with-smartcard-lock-on-removal\" feature with the following example:\n\n$ sudo authselect select sssd with-smartcard with-smartcard-lock-on-removal\n\nAlternatively, the dconf settings can be edited in the /etc/dconf/db/* location.\n\nEdit or add the \"[org/gnome/settings-daemon/peripherals/smartcard]\" section of the database file and add or update the following lines:\n\nremoval-action='lock-screen'\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be able to initiate directly a session lock for all connection types using smartcard when the smartcard is removed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined. Rather than be forced to wait for a period of time to expire before the user session can be locked, RHEL 8 needs to provide users with the ability to manually invoke a session lock so users can secure their session if it is necessary to temporarily vacate the immediate physical vicinity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system enables a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures with the following command:\n\nThis requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep -R removal-action /etc/dconf/db/*\n\n/etc/dconf/db/distro.d/20-authselect:removal-action='lock-screen'\n\nIf the \"removal-action='lock-screen'\" setting is missing or commented out from the dconf database files, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230351"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000056"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230351",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'removal-action' setting was not found in any '/etc/dconf/db/' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep gnome-shell\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -R removal-action /etc/dconf/db/* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if the system has a GUI installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system has a GUI installed:\n   xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking if 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n   chrome-gnome-shell.x86_64                          42.1-1.el8                                                  @appstream\n   gnome-shell.x86_64                                 3.32.2-58.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-apps-menu.noarch             3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-common.noarch                3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-desktop-icons.noarch         3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-horizontal-workspaces.noarch 3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-launch-new-instance.noarch   3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-places-menu.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n   gnome-shell-extension-window-list.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n\nChecking the 'removal-action' setting for 'Gnome Shell':\n\u274c The 'removal-action' setting was not found.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2bfbd314-8a7c-448f-a74d-a66c277823c0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-272483",
          "group_id_src": "V-272483",
          "rule_id": "SV-272483r1155361",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-272483r1155361_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010297",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH client must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH client connections.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the RHEL 8 SSH client to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nReinstall crypto-policies with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y reinstall crypto-policies\n\nSet the crypto-policy to FIPS with the following command:\n\n$ sudo update-crypto-policies --set FIPS\n\nSetting system policy to FIPS\n\nNote: Systemwide crypto policies are applied on application startup. It is recommended to restart the system for the change of policies to fully take place.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH client must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH client connections.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography, enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.\n\nRHEL 8 incorporates systemwide crypto policies by default. The SSH configuration file has no effect on the ciphers, MACs, or algorithms unless specifically defined in the /etc/sysconfig/sshd file. The employed algorithms can be viewed in the /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/openssh.config file.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093, SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174, SRG-OS-000125-GPOS-00066",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 SSH client is configured to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nTo verify the ciphers in the systemwide SSH configuration file, use the following command:\n\n$ grep -i Ciphers /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/openssh.config\n\nCiphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\n\nIf the cipher entries in the \"openssh.config\" file have any ciphers other than \"aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\", or they are missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-272483"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001453"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-272483",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following hashes were found in '/etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/openssh.config', but should not be in the Ciphers line:\nchacha20-poly1305@openssh.com, aes128-cbc, aes256-cbc",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i ciphers /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/openssh.config\n\nChecking that SSH client is configured to use only Ciphers employing FIPS 140-3:\n\u274c Ciphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2c577368-c7f6-4dd2-99c9-49931b29f26a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230369",
          "group_id_src": "V-230369",
          "rule_id": "SV-230369r1017181",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230369r1017181_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020230",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 passwords must have a minimum of 15 characters.",
          "fix_text": "Configure operating system to enforce a minimum 15-character password length.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nminlen = 15\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 passwords must have a minimum of 15 characters.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. Use of more characters in a password helps to increase exponentially the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Configurations are set in the \"etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file.\n\nThe \"minlen\", sometimes noted as minimum length, acts as a \"score\" of complexity based on the credit components of the \"pwquality\" module. By setting the credit components to a negative value, not only will those components be required, they will not count towards the total \"score\" of \"minlen\". This will enable \"minlen\" to require a 15-character minimum.\n\nThe DoD minimum password requirement is 15 characters.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system enforces a minimum 15-character password length. The \"minlen\" option sets the minimum number of characters in a new password.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"minlen\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:minlen = 15\n\nIf the command does not return a \"minlen\" value of 15 or greater, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230369"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000205"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230369",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'minlen' setting is commented out in '/etc/security/pwquality.conf'.\nAll 'minlen' settings are commented out in '/etc/security/pwquality.conf*'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -H -r minlen /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'minlen':\n\u274c /etc/security/pwquality.conf:# minlen = 8\n\u274c All 'minlen' settings are commented out in '/etc/security/pwquality.conf*'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2db2ecc9-9e3a-423d-9ef0-7b9aff369551",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-250317",
          "group_id_src": "V-250317",
          "rule_id": "SV-250317r1017358",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-250317r1017358_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040259",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not allow IPv4 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not enable IPv4 packet forwarding unless the system is a router.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 is not performing IPv4 packet forwarding, unless the system is a router.\n\nCheck that IPv4 forwarding is disabled using the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\nIf the IPv4 forwarding value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-250317"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-250317",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' variable:\n\u274c net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.ipv4.conf.all.forwarding' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "2dc3c305-8936-4997-a215-461f5837723a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230521",
          "group_id_src": "V-230521",
          "rule_id": "SV-230521r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230521r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040133",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/tmp with the nosuid option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/tmp is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp /var/tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/tmp with the nosuid option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/tmp\" is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp on /var/tmp type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"nosuid\" option is configured for /var/tmp:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp /var/tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"nosuid\" option is missing, or if /var/tmp is mounted without the \"nosuid\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230521"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230521",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nmount | grep /var/tmp\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep \"/var/tmp\" /etc/fstab\n\nChecking if '/var/tmp' is mounted with 'nosuid' option:\n\u274c '/var/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'nosuid' is configured for '/var/tmp':\n\u274c '/var/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3123842e-fdb2-4af2-b05e-e2378e19105a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230507",
          "group_id_src": "V-230507",
          "rule_id": "SV-230507r1017287",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230507r1017287_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040111",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 Bluetooth must be disabled.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the Bluetooth adapter when not in use.\n\nBuild or modify the \"/etc/modprobe.d/bluetooth.conf\" file with the following line:\n\n     install bluetooth /bin/false\n\nDisable the ability to use the Bluetooth kernel module.\n\n     $ sudo vi /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\n\nAdd or update the line:\n\n     blacklist bluetooth\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 Bluetooth must be disabled.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without protection of communications with wireless peripherals, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read, altered, or used to compromise the RHEL 8 operating system.\n\nThis requirement applies to wireless peripheral technologies (e.g., wireless mice, keyboards, displays, etc.) used with RHEL 8 systems. Wireless peripherals (e.g., Wi-Fi/Bluetooth/IR Keyboards, Mice, and Pointing Devices and Near Field Communications [NFC]) present a unique challenge by creating an open, unsecured port on a computer. Wireless peripherals must meet DoD requirements for wireless data transmission and be approved for use by the Authorizing Official (AO). Even though some wireless peripherals, such as mice and pointing devices, do not ordinarily carry information that need to be protected, modification of communications with these wireless peripherals may be used to compromise the RHEL 8 operating system. Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification.\n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical barriers to wireless radio frequencies) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa. If the wireless peripheral is only passing telemetry data, encryption of the data may not be required.",
          "check_content": "If the device or operating system does not have a Bluetooth adapter installed, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nThis requirement is not applicable to mobile devices (smartphones and tablets), where the use of Bluetooth is a local AO decision.\n\nDetermine if Bluetooth is disabled with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep bluetooth /etc/modprobe.d/*\n     /etc/modprobe.d/bluetooth.conf:install bluetooth /bin/false\n\nIf the Bluetooth driver blacklist entry is missing, a Bluetooth driver is determined to be in use, and the collaborative computing device has not been authorized for use, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the operating system disables the ability to use Bluetooth with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep -r bluetooth /etc/modprobe.d | grep -i \"blacklist\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n     blacklist bluetooth\n\nIf the command does not return any output or the output is not \"blacklist bluetooth\", and use of Bluetooth is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230507"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001443"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230507",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000300-GPOS-00118",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No bluetooth adapters were discovered, per DISA this check is 'Not Appplicable'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nls /sys/class/bluetooth\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep bluetooth /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep install 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r bluetooth /etc/modprobe.d | grep -i \"blacklist\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nChecking if any bluetooth adapters are installed:\n\ud83d\udd36 No bluetooth adapters were discovered\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3242695a-29cc-4ee5-ab41-a8098daff5b0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230361",
          "group_id_src": "V-230361",
          "rule_id": "SV-230361r1017173",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230361r1017173_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020150",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to require the change of the number of repeating consecutive characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"maxrepeat\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nmaxrepeat = 3\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must require the maximum number of repeating characters be limited to three when passwords are changed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. The \"maxrepeat\" option sets the maximum number of allowed same consecutive characters in a new password.",
          "check_content": "Check for the value of the \"maxrepeat\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r maxrepeat /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:maxrepeat = 3\n\nIf the value of \"maxrepeat\" is set to more than \"3\" or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230361"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000195"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230361",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'maxrepeat' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*maxrepeat' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'maxrepeat':\n\u274c The 'maxrepeat' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3304343c-667a-4327-af0e-f38d9f8fb1c1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230269",
          "group_id_src": "V-230269",
          "rule_id": "SV-230269r1137695",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230269r1137695_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010375",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict access to the kernel message buffer.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to restrict access to the kernel message buffer.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nkernel.dmesg_restrict = 1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict access to the kernel message buffer.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Preventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DoD or other government agencies.\n\nThere may be shared resources with configurable protections (e.g., files in storage) that may be assessed on specific information system components.\n\nRestricting access to the kernel message buffer limits access to only root. This prevents attackers from gaining additional system information as a non-privileged user.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system is configured to restrict access to the kernel message buffer with the following commands:\n\nCheck the status of the kernel.dmesg_restrict kernel parameter.\n\n$ sudo sysctl kernel.dmesg_restrict\n\nkernel.dmesg_restrict = 1\n\nIf \"kernel.dmesg_restrict\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this kernel parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r kernel.dmesg_restrict /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf:kernel.dmesg_restrict = 1\n\nIf \"kernel.dmesg_restrict\" is not set to \"1\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230269"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001090"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230269",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'kernel.dmesg_restrict' variable is set to '0' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '1'\nThe 'kernel.dmesg_restrict' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.dmesg_restrict\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*kernel.dmesg_restrict' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'kernel.dmesg_restrict' variable:\n\u274c kernel.dmesg_restrict = 0\n\nChecking config files to enable 'kernel.dmesg_restrict' variable:\n\u274c The 'kernel.dmesg_restrict' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "333e49a5-ad8f-48cd-b567-dd5c50905d55",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230413",
          "group_id_src": "V-230413",
          "rule_id": "SV-230413r1017219",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230413r1017219_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030200",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must be configured to audit any usage of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to audit the execution of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls by adding or updating the following lines to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must be configured to audit any usage of the setxattr, fsetxattr, lsetxattr, removexattr, fremovexattr, and lremovexattr system calls.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\n\"Setxattr\" is a system call used to set an extended attribute value.\n\"Fsetxattr\" is a system call used to set an extended attribute value. This is used to set extended attributes on a file.\n\"Lsetxattr\" is a system call used to set an extended attribute value. This is used to set extended attributes on a symbolic link.\n\"Removexattr\" is a system call that removes extended attributes.\n\"Fremovexattr\" is a system call that removes extended attributes. This is used for removal of extended attributes from a file.\n\"Lremovexattr\" is a system call that removes extended attributes. This is used for removal of extended attributes from symbolic links.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000458-GPOS-00203, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000463-GPOS-00207, SRG-OS-000468-GPOS-00212, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210",
          "check_content": "Verify if RHEL 8 is configured to audit the execution of the \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" system calls by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep xattr /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,fsetxattr,lsetxattr,removexattr,fremovexattr,lremovexattr -F auid=0 -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"setxattr\", \"fsetxattr\", \"lsetxattr\", \"removexattr\", \"fremovexattr\", and \"lremovexattr\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230413"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230413",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'setxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'setxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'fsetxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'fsetxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'lsetxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'lsetxattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'removexattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'removexattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'fremovexattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'fremovexattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'lremovexattr' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'lremovexattr' do not exist.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w setxattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w setxattr | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w fsetxattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w fsetxattr | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w lsetxattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w lsetxattr | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w removexattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w removexattr | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w fremovexattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w fremovexattr | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w lremovexattr | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w lremovexattr | grep b64\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'setxattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'setxattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'setxattr' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'fsetxattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'fsetxattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'fsetxattr' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'lsetxattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'lsetxattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'lsetxattr' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'removexattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'removexattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'removexattr' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'fremovexattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'fremovexattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'fremovexattr' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'lremovexattr':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'lremovexattr' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'lremovexattr' do not exist.\n\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "33a7dce1-6083-44dd-a55c-03eb81618adb",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-272484",
          "group_id_src": "V-272484",
          "rule_id": "SV-272484r1134875",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-272484r1134875_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010455",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must elevate the SELinux context when an administrator calls the sudo command.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to elevate the SELinux context when an administrator calls the sudo command.\n\nEdit a file in the \"/etc/sudoers.d\" directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/<customfile>\n\nUse the following example to build the <customfile> in the /etc/sudoers.d directory to allow any administrator belonging to a designated sudoers admin group to elevate their SELinux context with the use of the sudo command:\n\n{designated_group_or_user_name} ALL=(ALL) TYPE=sysadm_t ROLE=sysadm_r ALL\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n\n/etc/sudoers\n/etc/sudoers.d/",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must elevate the SELinux context when an administrator calls the sudo command.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Preventing nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions mitigates the risk that unauthorized individuals or processes may gain unnecessary access to information or privileges.\n\nPrivileged functions include, for example, establishing accounts, performing system integrity checks, or administering cryptographic key management activities. Nonprivileged users are individuals who do not possess appropriate authorizations. Circumventing intrusion detection and prevention mechanisms or malicious code protection mechanisms are examples of privileged functions that require protection from nonprivileged users.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system elevates the SELinux context when an administrator calls the sudo command with the following command:\n\nThis command must be run as root:\n\n# grep -r sysadm_r /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d\n/etc/sudoers.d/admins:<username> ALL=(ALL) TYPE=sysadm_t ROLE=sysadm_r ALL\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.\n\nIf a designated sudoers administrator group or account(s) is not configured to elevate the SELinux type and role to \"sysadm_t\" and \"sysadm_r\" with the use of the sudo command, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-272484"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002235"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-272484",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No SELinux sudo context elevation configuration found for sysadm_r and sysadm_t in /etc/sudoers or /etc/sudoers.d.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -rH sysadm_r /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d\n\nChecking that the OS elevates the SELinux context when an administrator calls the sudo command:\n\u274c No output\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "344abff8-ab12-48a7-8358-e07a6d177be3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-251712",
          "group_id_src": "V-251712",
          "rule_id": "SV-251712r1050789",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-251712r1050789_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010385",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 operating system must not be configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to require users to supply a password for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/ pam.d/sudo\" file with the following command:\n$ sudo vi /etc/pam.d/sudo\n\nRemove any occurrences of \"pam_succeed_if\" in the file.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 operating system must not be configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without re-authentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization.\n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the user re-authenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system is not be configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.\n\nCheck the configuration of the \"/etc/pam.d/sudo\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep pam_succeed_if /etc/pam.d/sudo\n\nIf any occurrences of \"pam_succeed_if\" is returned from the command, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-251712"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002038",
            "CCI-004895"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-251712",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The OS is not configured to bypass password requirements for privilege escalation.",
          "finding_details": "#grep pam_succeed_if /etc/pam.d/sudo\n\nChecking the configuration of '/etc/pam.d/sudo':\n\u2705 No occurences of 'pam_succeed_if' exist in '/etc/pam.d/sudo'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "34b2dfd2-1fc9-4ddc-a621-5808f23b7c1f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230552",
          "group_id_src": "V-230552",
          "rule_id": "SV-230552r1101902",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230552r1101902_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040310",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 file integrity tool must be configured to verify Access Control Lists (ACLs).",
          "fix_text": "Configure the file integrity tool to check file and directory ACLs.\n\nIf AIDE is installed, ensure the \"acl\" rule is present on all file and directory selection lists.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 file integrity tool must be configured to verify Access Control Lists (ACLs).",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "ACLs can provide permissions beyond those permitted through the file mode and must be verified by file integrity tools.\n\nSelection lines in the aide.conf file determine which files and directories AIDE will monitor for changes. They follow this format:\n\n<path> <rules>\n\nThe <path> specifies a file, directory or wildcard pattern to monitor.\nThe <rules>define which attributes (hashes, permissions, timestamps, etc.) to check.\n\nRHEL 8 installation media come with a file integrity tool, Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment (AIDE).",
          "check_content": "Verify the file integrity tool is configured to verify ACLs.\n\nNote: AIDE is highly configurable at install time. This requirement assumes the \"aide.conf\" file is under the \"/etc\" directory.\n\nIf AIDE is not installed, ask the system administrator (SA) how file integrity checks are performed on the system.\n\nUse the following command to determine if the file is in a location other than \"/etc/aide/aide.conf\":\n\n$ sudo find / -name aide.conf\n\nUse the following command to review the \"aide.conf\" file to determine if the \"acl\" rule has been added to the rule list being applied to the files and directories selection lists:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/aide.conf | more\n\nIf the \"acl\" rule is not being used on all selection lines in the \"/etc/aide.conf\" file, is commented out, or ACLs are not being checked by another file integrity tool, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230552"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230552",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Ask the System Administrator how file integrity checks are performed on the system.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nrpm -q aide\nfind $(df -Th | awk '$2 ~ /^(btrfs|xfs|zfs|reiserfs|ext[2-4]|.*fat.*)$/ {print $7}') -xdev -name aide.conf 2>/dev/null | xargs -I AIDEFILE sh -c 'echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; echo AIDEFILE; echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; cat AIDEFILE'\n\nChecking if 'AIDE' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d 'AIDE' is not installed on the system\n\n\ud83d\udd36 Ask the System Administrator how file integrity checks are performed on the system.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "34c2848b-fa2b-4c3a-9a6d-631ad45519b5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230464",
          "group_id_src": "V-230464",
          "rule_id": "SV-230464r1017256",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230464r1017256_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030570",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chacl command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"chacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chacl command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"chacl\" command is used to change the access control list of a file or directory.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chacl\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w chacl /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/chacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230464"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230464",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chacl' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/bin/chacl\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chacl' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chacl' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "359effb1-2c2f-4b09-9fe8-9b64c1224068",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230251",
          "group_id_src": "V-230251",
          "rule_id": "SV-230251r1155370",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230251r1155370_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010290",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH server must be configured to use only Message Authentication Codes (MACs) employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the RHEL 8 SSH server to use only MACs employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nReinstall crypto-policies with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y reinstall crypto-policies\n\nSet the crypto-policy to FIPS with the following command:\n\n$ sudo update-crypto-policies --set FIPS\n\nSetting system policy to FIPS\n\nNote: Systemwide crypto policies are applied on application startup. It is recommended to restart the system for the change of policies to fully take place.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH server must be configured to use only Message Authentication Codes (MACs) employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.\n\nRHEL 8 incorporates systemwide crypto policies by default. The SSH configuration file has no effect on the ciphers, MACs, or algorithms unless specifically defined in the /etc/sysconfig/sshd file. The employed algorithms can be viewed in the /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config file.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093, SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174, SRG-OS-000125-GPOS-00065",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 SSH server is configured to use only MACs employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nTo verify the MACs in the systemwide SSH configuration file, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i MACs /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config\n\n-oMACs=hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512,hmac-sha2-256\n\nIf the MACs entries in the \"opensshserver.config\" file have any hashes other than \"hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512,hmac-sha2-256\", or they are missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230251"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001453"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230251",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "There are extra macs not defined by DISA listed in the '-oMACs' setting:\nhmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com,umac-128-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha1,umac-128@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i '\\-omacs' /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config\n\nChecking the SSH server macs:\n\u274c There are extra macs not defined by DISA listed in the '-oMACs' setting:\nhmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha1-etm@openssh.com,umac-128-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha1,umac-128@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-512\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "35e450f3-3ca0-44e6-8016-57d38373faa1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230502",
          "group_id_src": "V-230502",
          "rule_id": "SV-230502r1155393",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230502r1155393_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040070",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 file system automounter must be disabled.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to disable the ability to automount devices.\n\nTurn off the automount service with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo systemctl stop autofs\n$ sudo systemctl disable autofs",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 file system automounter must be disabled.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Automatically mounting file systems permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 disables the ability to automount devices.\n\nCheck to see if automounter service is active with the following command:\n\nNote: If the autofs service is not installed, this requirement is not applicable.\n\n$ sudo systemctl status autofs\n\no autofs.service - Automounts filesystems on demand\n   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/autofs.service; disabled)\n   Active: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the \"autofs\" status is set to \"active\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230502"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000778"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230502",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'autofs.service' is not installed on the system, per DISA this requirment is not applicable.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nsystemctl --no-pager status autofs\n\nChecking if the autofs service is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'autofs.service' is not installed on the system, per DISA this requirment is not applicable.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "363605e9-7de9-4fbc-b050-2d468a99450d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230295",
          "group_id_src": "V-230295",
          "rule_id": "SV-230295r1017106",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230295r1017106_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010543",
          "rule_title": "A separate RHEL 8 filesystem must be used for the /tmp directory.",
          "fix_text": "Migrate the \"/tmp\" directory onto a separate file system/partition.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "A separate RHEL 8 filesystem must be used for the /tmp directory.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.",
          "check_content": "Verify that a separate file system/partition has been created for non-privileged local interactive user home directories.\n\n$ sudo grep /tmp /etc/fstab\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-tmp  /tmp  xfs   defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a separate entry for the file system/partition \"/tmp\" does not exist, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230295"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230295",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "A separate entry for the file system/partition '/tmp' does not exist.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /tmp /etc/fstab\n\nChecking that a seperate file system/partition has been created for non-privileged local interactive user home directories:\n\u274c A separate entry for the file system/partition '/tmp' does not exist.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3686ab5b-1d0e-4b7f-8583-3a020a55d3e0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230274",
          "group_id_src": "V-230274",
          "rule_id": "SV-230274r1017089",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230274r1017089_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010400",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.\n\nReview the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file to determine if the system is configured to prevent OCSP or certificate verification.\n\nAdd the following line to the [sssd] section of the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file:\n\ncertificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha1\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must implement certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Using an authentication device, such as a DoD Common Access Card (CAC) or token that is separate from the information system, ensures that even if the information system is compromised, credentials stored on the authentication device will not be affected.\n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from information systems gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification (PIV) card and the DoD CAC.\n\nRHEL 8 includes multiple options for configuring certificate status checking, but for this requirement focuses on the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD). By default, sssd performs Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) checking and certificate verification using a sha256 digest function.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160, SRG-OS-000377-GPOS-00162",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system implements certificate status checking for multifactor authentication.\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nCheck to see if Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) is enabled and using the proper digest value on the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep certificate_verification /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/*.conf | grep -v \"^#\"\n\ncertificate_verification = ocsp_dgst=sha1\n\nIf the certificate_verification line is missing from the [sssd] section, or is missing \"ocsp_dgst=sha1\", ask the administrator to indicate what type of multifactor authentication is being utilized and how the system implements certificate status checking.  If there is no evidence of certificate status checking being used, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230274"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001948",
            "CCI-004046"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230274",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000375-GPOS-00160",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'certificate_verification' setting was not found uncommented in /etc/sssd/sssd.conf or any file in /etc/sssd/conf.d.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\necho 'File Name: /etc/sssd/sssd.conf'\nsed -n '/^\\[sssd\\]/,/^$/p' \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\"\ndirectory=\"/etc/sssd/conf.d\"\n\nfor file in \"$directory\"/*; do\n    # Check if the file is a regular file\n    if [[ -f \"$file\" ]]; then\n        echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n        echo \"File Name: $file\"\n        \n        # Extract the [sssd] portion using sed\n        sed -n '/^\\[sssd\\]/,/^$/p' \"$file\"\n    fi\ndone\n\nChecking for the 'certificate_verification' setting:\n\u274c The 'certificate_verification' setting was not found uncommented in '/etc/sssd/sssd.conf' or any file in '/etc/sssd/conf.d'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "37aade33-232d-46c6-9ee2-1a5dff56039e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230407",
          "group_id_src": "V-230407",
          "rule_id": "SV-230407r1017213",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230407r1017213_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030160",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/gshadow.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/gshadow\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/gshadow -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/gshadow.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/gshadow\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/gshadow /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/gshadow -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230407"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230407",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/gshadow' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/gshadow' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/gshadow /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/gshadow\n\nChecking for '/etc/gshadow' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/gshadow' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/gshadow' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/gshadow' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3855936e-0f35-41dc-a49a-3be7e6462800",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230424",
          "group_id_src": "V-230424",
          "rule_id": "SV-230424r1017225",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230424r1017225_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030301",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"umount\" command by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the umount command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"umount\" command is used to unmount a filesystem.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"umount\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w /usr/bin/umount /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/umount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230424"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230424",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/usr/bin/umount' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/usr/bin/umount' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w /usr/bin/umount /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w /usr/bin/umount\n\nChecking for '/usr/bin/umount' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/umount' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/usr/bin/umount' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/umount' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "399fea2b-96da-4efd-ad33-59e57c6d2c1a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244539",
          "group_id_src": "V-244539",
          "rule_id": "SV-244539r1069325",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244539r1069325_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020082",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent non-privileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the screensaver lock-enabled setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.\n\nImplementing session settings will have little value if a user is able to manipulate these settings from the defaults prescribed in the other requirements of this implementation guide.\n\nLocking these settings from non-privileged users is crucial to maintaining a protected baseline.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010, SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\nsystem-db:local\n\nCheck that graphical settings are locked from non-privileged user modification with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n$ sudo grep -i lock-enabled /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled\n\nIf the command does not return at least the example result, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244539"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000057"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244539",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled' was not found in any of the 'system-db' directories identified in '/etc/dconf/profile/user'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep gnome-shell\ngrep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user | cut -d: -f2 | xargs -I DIR sh -c 'echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; echo \"Directory: /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks\"; grep -iH lock-delay /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks/*' 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if the system has a GUI installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system has a GUI installed:\n   xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking if 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n   chrome-gnome-shell.x86_64                          42.1-1.el8                                                  @appstream\ngnome-shell.x86_64                                 3.32.2-58.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-apps-menu.noarch             3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-common.noarch                3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-desktop-icons.noarch         3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-horizontal-workspaces.noarch 3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-launch-new-instance.noarch   3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-places-menu.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-window-list.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n\nChecking the 'lock-enabled' setting is protected for 'Gnome Shell':\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/site.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/distro.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-enabled' not found in any files\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3a0bdc9b-5b33-41e1-837e-5c4f69a9c2d9",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230347",
          "group_id_src": "V-230347",
          "rule_id": "SV-230347r1017160",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230347r1017160_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020030",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures for graphical user sessions.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enable a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following example:\n\n$ sudo vi /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-screensaver\n\nEdit the \"[org/gnome/desktop/screensaver]\" section of the database file and add or update the following lines:\n\n# Set this to true to lock the screen when the screensaver activates\nlock-enabled=true\n\nUpdate the system databases:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable a user session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures for graphical user sessions.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A session lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not want to log out because of the temporary nature of the absence.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined.\n\nRegardless of where the session lock is determined and implemented, once invoked, the session lock must remain in place until the user reauthenticates. No other activity aside from reauthentication must unlock the system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009, SRG-OS-000030-GPOS-00011",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system enables a user's session lock until that user re-establishes access using established identification and authentication procedures with the following command:\n\n$ sudo gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-enabled\n\ntrue\n\nIf the setting is \"false\", this is a finding.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230347"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000056"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230347",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000028-GPOS-00009",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'lock-enabled' setting is set to 'true' for the 'Gnome Shell'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep gnome-shell\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngsettings get org.gnome.desktop.screensaver lock-enabled\n\nChecking if the system has a GUI installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system has a GUI installed:\n   xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking if 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n   chrome-gnome-shell.x86_64                          42.1-1.el8                                                  @appstream\ngnome-shell.x86_64                                 3.32.2-58.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-apps-menu.noarch             3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-common.noarch                3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-desktop-icons.noarch         3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-horizontal-workspaces.noarch 3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-launch-new-instance.noarch   3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-places-menu.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-window-list.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n\nChecking the 'lock-enabled' setting for 'Gnome Shell':\n\u2705 true\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3bb7d518-3a9d-426b-bd4a-9afc87728bdb",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230519",
          "group_id_src": "V-230519",
          "rule_id": "SV-230519r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230519r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040131",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log/audit with the noexec option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/log/audit is mounted with the \"noexec\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit /var/log/audit xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log/audit with the noexec option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/log/audit\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit on /var/log/audit type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"noexec\" option is configured for /var/log/audit:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log/audit\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit /var/log/audit xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"noexec\" option is missing, or if /var/log/audit is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230519"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230519",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/log/audit' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/log/audit' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /var/log/audit\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log/audit\n\nChecking if '/var/log/audit' is mounted with 'noexec' option:\n\u274c '/var/log/audit' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'noexec' is configured for '/var/log/audit':\n\u274c '/var/log/audit' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3eff7eff-bd68-4264-a689-20930d5429c6",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230342",
          "group_id_src": "V-230342",
          "rule_id": "SV-230342r1017154",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230342r1017154_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020020",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" files to match the following lines:\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nRHEL 8 can utilize the \"pam_faillock.so\" for this purpose. Note that manual changes to the listed files may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.\n\nFrom \"Pam_Faillock\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module. Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Check that the system logs user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur with the following commands:\n\nIf the system is RHEL version 8.2 or newer, this check is not applicable.\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved centralized account management method that locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes, this requirement is not applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is missing from the \"preauth\" line with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, this is a finding.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"audit\" option is missing from the \"preauth\" line with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230342"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230342",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "System is running Red Hat version 8.10 which is less than 8.2, per DISA this check is not applicable",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep -w preauth\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth\n\nChecking the Red Hat Version:\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\ud83d\udd36 System is running Red Hat version 8.10 which is less than 8.2, per DISA this check is not applicable\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3f1a24d4-e8ac-4706-8824-509b46c38e7b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244519",
          "group_id_src": "V-244519",
          "rule_id": "SV-244519r1017326",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244519r1017326_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010049",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must display a banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to display a banner before granting access to the system.\n\nNote: If the system does not have a graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide graphical user logon settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\n\nAdd the following lines to the [org/gnome/login-screen] section of the \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d/01-banner-message\":\n\n[org/gnome/login-screen]\n\nbanner-message-enable=true\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must display a banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a graphical user logon.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nSystem use notifications are required only for access via logon interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 displays a banner before granting access to the operating system via a graphical user logon.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck to see if the operating system displays a banner at the logon screen with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep banner-message-enable /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\nbanner-message-enable=true\n\nIf \"banner-message-enable\" is set to \"false\" or is missing, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244519"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000048"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244519",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No valid 'banner-message-enable' settings found in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d/*'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -H banner-message-enable /etc/dconf/db/local.d/* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if any graphical user interface is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d A graphical user interface is installed\n\nChecking if the OS displays a banner at the logon screen:\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3f20bf9a-82d5-433d-bd12-dbf431a62eda",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230497",
          "group_id_src": "V-230497",
          "rule_id": "SV-230497r1069313",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230497r1069313_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040024",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the transparent inter-process communication (TIPC) protocol.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the TIPC protocol kernel module.\n\nAdd or update the following lines in the file \"/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\":\n\n     install tipc /bin/false\n     blacklist tipc\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the transparent inter-process communication (TIPC) protocol.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nFailing to disconnect unused protocols can result in a system compromise.\n\nThe Transparent Inter-Process Communication (TIPC) protocol is designed to provide communications between nodes in a cluster. Disabling TIPC protects the system against exploitation of any flaws in its implementation.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the TIPC protocol kernel module and ensure that TIPC is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r tipc /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\"\n\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:install tipc /bin/false\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:blacklist tipc\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of the TIPC protocol is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230497"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230497",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'install TIPC protocol /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\nThe 'TIPC protocol blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r tipc /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"install\" 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r tipc /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\" 2>/dev/null\n\n\nChecking if TIPC protocol is disabled:\n\u274c The 'install TIPC protocol /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\n\nChecking if the TIPC protocol blacklist entry exists:\n\u274c The 'TIPC protocol blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "3ffd1e93-488d-4644-80a0-bf9bb5755d2c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230257",
          "group_id_src": "V-230257",
          "rule_id": "SV-230257r1017077",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230257r1017077_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010300",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 system commands must have mode 755 or less permissive.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system commands to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[FILE]\" with any system command with a mode more permissive than \"755\".\n\n$ sudo chmod 755 [FILE]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 system commands must have mode 755 or less permissive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If RHEL 8 were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 8 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals will be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.",
          "check_content": "Verify the system commands contained in the following directories have mode \"755\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin -perm /022 -exec ls -l {} \\;\n\nIf any system commands are found to be group-writable or world-writable, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230257"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001499"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230257",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No system commands were found to be group-writable or wold-writable.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nfind -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin -perm /022 -exec ls -l {} \\;\n\nChecking the mode of system commands in '/bin', '/sbin', '/usr/bin', '/usr/sbin', '/usr/local/bin', and '/usr/local/sbin':\n\u2705 No system commands were found to be group-writable or wold-writable.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4002c8c4-156b-48e1-ac9b-246a5797384f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230323",
          "group_id_src": "V-230323",
          "rule_id": "SV-230323r1017134",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230323r1017134_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010750",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.",
          "fix_text": "Create home directories to all local interactive users that currently do not have a home directory assigned. Use the following commands to create the user home directory assigned in \"/etc/ passwd\":\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\", a UID of \"smithj\", and a Group Identifier (GID) of \"users assigned\" in \"/etc/passwd\".\n\n$ sudo mkdir /home/smithj\n$ sudo chown smithj /home/smithj\n$ sudo chgrp users /home/smithj\n$ sudo chmod 0750 /home/smithj",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directories defined in the /etc/passwd file must exist.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If a local interactive user has a home directory defined that does not exist, the user may be given access to the \"/\" directory as the current working directory upon logon. This could create a denial of service because the user would not be able to access their logon configuration files, and it may give them visibility to system files they normally would not be able to access.",
          "check_content": "Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users on RHEL 8 exists with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 smithj admin 4096 Jun 5 12:41 smithj\n\nNote: This may miss interactive users that have been assigned a privileged User ID (UID). Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information.\n\nCheck that all referenced home directories exist with the following command:\n\n$ sudo pwck -r\n\nuser 'smithj': directory '/home/smithj' does not exist\n\nIf any home directories referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" are returned as not defined, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230323"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230323",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\npwck -r\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\necho \"Interactive Users:\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n         if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                 echo \"USER: $username\"; stat -c \"%a %n\" $homedir\n         fi\ndone < $FILENAME\n\nChecking that local interactive users have valid home directory assigned in '/etc/passwd':\n\u2705 The home directory ('/root') for user ('root') exists and is valid.\n\u2705 The home directory ('/home/deckerr') for user ('deckerr') exists and is valid.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "401505f3-065a-42e8-bb67-07888e3a87c7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230455",
          "group_id_src": "V-230455",
          "rule_id": "SV-230455r1017251",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230455r1017251_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030480",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" system calls by adding or updating the following line to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the chown, fchown, fchownat, and lchown system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"chown\" command is used to change file owner and group.\n\nThe \"fchown\" system call is used to change the ownership of a file referred to by the open file descriptor.\nThe \"fchownat\" system call is used to change ownership of a file relative to a directory file descriptor.\nThe \"lchown\" system call is used to change the ownership of the file specified by a path, which does not dereference symbolic links.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\" and \"lchown\" system calls by using the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep chown /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat,lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf audit rules are not defined for \"chown\", \"fchown\", \"fchownat\", and \"lchown\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230455"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230455",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'chown' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'chown' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'fchown' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'fchown' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'fchownat' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'fchownat' does not exist on the system.\nThe 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'lchown' does not exist on the system.i\nThe 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'lchown' does not exist on the system.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"chown\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"chown\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"fchown\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"fchown\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"fchownat\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"fchownat\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"lchown\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"lchown\" | grep b64\n\nChecking for auditing of 'chown':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'chown' does not exist on the system.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'chown' does not exist on the system.\nChecking for auditing of 'fchown':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'fchown' does not exist on the system.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'fchown' does not exist on the system.\nChecking for auditing of 'fchownat':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'fchownat' does not exist on the system.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'fchownat' does not exist on the system.\nChecking for auditing of 'lchown':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' entry for auditing 'lchown' does not exist on the system.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' entry for auditing 'lchown' does not exist on the system.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "404aaf44-e9ef-4733-a204-73f22f297a6e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230544",
          "group_id_src": "V-230544",
          "rule_id": "SV-230544r1017306",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230544r1017306_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040280",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to ignore IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must ignore IPv6 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 ignores IPv6 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230544"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230544",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' setting returned from 'sysctl' is set to '1', but should have returned '0'.\nNo configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' setting.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl -a 2>/dev/null | grep 'net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if IPv6 is disabled on the system:\n\ud83d\udd0d IPv6 is not disabled\n\nChecking the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' setting using 'sysctl':\n\u274c net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 1\n\nChecking for the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' setting in configuration files:\n\u274c No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects' setting\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4102225f-6ec9-4e72-90d2-044d4e1c9648",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230397",
          "group_id_src": "V-230397",
          "rule_id": "SV-230397r1017203",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230397r1017203_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030080",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log to be protected from unauthorized read access, by setting the correct owner as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [audit_log_file]\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_file]\" to the correct audit log path, by default this location is \"/var/log/audit/audit.log\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 8 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit logs are owned by \"root\". First, determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log is owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -al /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nrw------- 2 root root 23 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit log is not owned by \"root\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230397"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230397",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The owner of '/var/log/audit/audit.log' is 'root'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nstat -c \"%U\" /var/log/audit/audit.log 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d= -f2 | xargs stat -c \"%U\" 2>/dev/null\n\nDetermining the audit log location:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log Location: /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nChecking the owner of '/var/log/audit/audit.log':\n\u2705 Owner = root\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4125987b-8c61-416a-b78f-4047724df6a0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230405",
          "group_id_src": "V-230405",
          "rule_id": "SV-230405r1017211",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230405r1017211_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030140",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/security/opasswd.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/security/opasswd\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/security/opasswd -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/security/opasswd.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/security/opasswd\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/security/opasswd /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/security/opasswd -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230405"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230405",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/security/opasswd' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/security/opasswd' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/security/opasswd /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/security/opasswd\n\nChecking for '/etc/security/opasswd' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/security/opasswd' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/security/opasswd' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/security/opasswd' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "42347861-f587-4a18-b214-62fb8907b44e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230543",
          "group_id_src": "V-230543",
          "rule_id": "SV-230543r1017305",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230543r1017305_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040270",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not allow interfaces to perform Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) ICMP redirects by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow interfaces to perform Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects by default.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table, possibly revealing portions of the network topology.\n\nThere are notable differences between Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6). There is only a directive to disable sending of IPv4 redirected packets. Refer to RFC4294 for an explanation of \"IPv6 Node Requirements\", which resulted in this difference between IPv4 and IPv6.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not allow interfaces to perform Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) ICMP redirects by default.\n\nCheck the value of the \"default send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects=0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230543"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230543",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' variable:\n\u274c net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4334420d-4e53-4fd5-ab63-1eca931f38cf",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230371",
          "group_id_src": "V-230371",
          "rule_id": "SV-230371r1017183",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230371r1017183_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020240",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 duplicate User IDs (UIDs) must not exist for interactive users.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the file \"/etc/passwd\" and provide each interactive user account that has a duplicate User ID (UID) with a unique UID.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 duplicate User IDs (UIDs) must not exist for interactive users.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, interactive users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nInteractive users include organizational employees or individuals the organization deems to have equivalent status of employees (e.g., contractors). Interactive users (and processes acting on behalf of users) must be uniquely identified and authenticated to all accesses, except for the following:\n\n1) Accesses explicitly identified and documented by the organization. Organizations document specific user actions that can be performed on the information system without identification or authentication; and\n\n2) Accesses that occur through authorized use of group authenticators without individual authentication. Organizations may require unique identification of individuals in group accounts (e.g., shared privilege accounts) or for detailed accountability of individual activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051, SRG-OS-000121-GPOS-00062, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020",
          "check_content": "Verify that RHEL 8 contains no duplicate User IDs (UIDs) for interactive users.\n\nCheck that the operating system contains no duplicate UIDs for interactive users with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F \":\" 'list[$3]++{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd\n\nIf output is produced, and the accounts listed are interactive user accounts, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230371"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230371",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000104-GPOS-00051",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No duplicate UIDs exist on the system for interactive users.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/passwd\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\necho \"Interactive Users:\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n         if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false/\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                 echo \"$username,$userid\"\n         fi\ndone < $FILENAME\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nawk -F \":\" 'list[$3]++{print $1, $3}' /etc/passwd\n\nChecking if the OS contains duplicate UIDs for interactive users:\n\u2705 No duplicate UIDs exist on the system for interactive users.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "453ed4bc-9521-4ee5-ae94-9a967ad2831c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230401",
          "group_id_src": "V-230401",
          "rule_id": "SV-230401r1017207",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230401r1017207_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030120",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must have a mode of 0700 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log directory to be protected from unauthorized read access by setting the correct permissive mode with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0700 [audit_log_directory]\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_directory]\" to the correct audit log directory path, by default this location is \"/var/log/audit\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must have a mode of 0700 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit RHEL 8 system activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit log directories have a mode of \"0700\" or less permissive by first determining where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log, determine the directory where the audit logs are stored (ex: \"/var/log/audit\"). Run the following command to determine the permissions for the audit log folder:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /var/log/audit\n\n700 /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit log directory has a mode more permissive than \"0700\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230401"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230401",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The mode of '/var/log/audit' is '700'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndirname /var/log/audit/audit.log | xargs -I DIR stat -c \"%a %n\" DIR \necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR | xargs stat -c \"%a %n\"\n\nDetermining the audit log directory:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log Directory: /var/log/audit\n\nChecking the mode of '/var/log/audit':\n\u2705 Mode = 700\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "45bd230d-fae6-47e9-860d-e7b64627f46f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230225",
          "group_id_src": "V-230225",
          "rule_id": "SV-230225r1069297",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230225r1069297_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010040",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a ssh logon.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system via the ssh.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment the banner keyword and configure it to point to a file that will contain the logon banner (this file may be named differently or be in a different location if using a version of SSH that is provided by a third-party vendor). An example configuration line is:\n\nbanner /etc/issue\n\nEither create the file containing the banner or replace the text in the file with the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner. The DOD-required text is:\n\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only. By using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must display the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting local or remote access to the system via a ssh logon.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Display of a standardized and approved use notification before granting access to the operating system ensures privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.\n\nSystem use notifications are required only for access via logon interfaces with human users and are not required when such human interfaces do not exist.\n\nThe banner must be formatted in accordance with applicable DOD policy. Use the following verbiage for operating systems that can accommodate banners of 1300 characters:\n\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only.\n\nBy using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\nUse the following verbiage for operating systems that have severe limitations on the number of characters that can be displayed in the banner:\n\n\"I've read & consent to terms in IS user agreem't.\"\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006, SRG-OS-000228-GPOS-00088",
          "check_content": "Verify any publicly accessible connection to the operating system displays the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to the system.\n\nCheck for the location of the banner file being used with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*banner'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:banner /etc/issue\n\nThis command will return the banner keyword and the name of the file that contains the ssh banner (in this case \"/etc/issue\").\n\nIf the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.\n\nView the file specified by the banner keyword to check that it matches the text of the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner:\n\n\"You are accessing a U.S. Government (USG) Information System (IS) that is provided for USG-authorized use only. By using this IS (which includes any device attached to this IS), you consent to the following conditions:\n\n-The USG routinely intercepts and monitors communications on this IS for purposes including, but not limited to, penetration testing, COMSEC monitoring, network operations and defense, personnel misconduct (PM), law enforcement (LE), and counterintelligence (CI) investigations.\n\n-At any time, the USG may inspect and seize data stored on this IS.\n\n-Communications using, or data stored on, this IS are not private, are subject to routine monitoring, interception, and search, and may be disclosed or used for any USG-authorized purpose.\n\n-This IS includes security measures (e.g., authentication and access controls) to protect USG interests--not for your personal benefit or privacy.\n\n-Notwithstanding the above, using this IS does not constitute consent to PM, LE or CI investigative searching or monitoring of the content of privileged communications, or work product, related to personal representation or services by attorneys, psychotherapists, or clergy, and their assistants. Such communications and work product are private and confidential. See User Agreement for details.\"\n\nIf the system does not display a graphical logon banner or the banner does not match the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner, this is a finding.\n\nIf the text in the file does not match the Standard Mandatory DOD Notice and Consent Banner, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230225"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000048"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230225",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000023-GPOS-00006",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All 'banner' settings are commented out",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iHr banner /etc/ssh/sshd_config*\ngrep -iHr banner /etc/ssh/sshd_config* | cut -d \":\" -f 2 | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d \" \" -f 2 | xargs -I FILE sh -c 'echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; echo \"File Name: FILE\"; cat FILE' \n\nChecking for the location of the 'banner' file being used:\n\u274c /etc/ssh/sshd_config:# no default banner path\n\u274c /etc/ssh/sshd_config:#Banner none\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4638e4ca-e3e0-4a08-a412-b3cef09a0131",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230430",
          "group_id_src": "V-230430",
          "rule_id": "SV-230430r1017231",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230430r1017231_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030314",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of setfiles in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"setfiles\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of setfiles in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise. The \"setfiles\" command is primarily used to initialize the security context fields (extended attributes) on one or more filesystems (or parts of them).  Usually it is initially run as part of the SELinux installation process (a step commonly known as labeling).\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of \"setfiles\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"setfiles\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setfiles -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230430"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230430",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfiles' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/sbin/setfiles\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfiles' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfiles' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "469a78e2-710a-41cc-86e9-ffe4f38c4622",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-251708",
          "group_id_src": "V-251708",
          "rule_id": "SV-251708r1017362",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-251708r1017362_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010341",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 library directories must be owned by root.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system-wide shared library directories within (/lib, /lib64, /usr/lib and /usr/lib64) to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[DIRECTORY]\" with any library directory not owned by \"root\".\n\n$ sudo chown root [DIRECTORY]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 library directories must be owned by root.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If RHEL 8 were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 8 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals will be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.",
          "check_content": "Verify the system-wide shared library directories are owned by \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 ! -user root -type d -exec stat -c \"%n %U\" '{}' \\;\n\nIf any system-wide shared library directory is returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-251708"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001499"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-251708",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "There are no system-wide shared library files not owned by 'root'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nfind /lib /lib64 /usr/lib /usr/lib64 ! -user root -type d -exec stat -c \"%n %U\" '{}' \\; 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if system-wide shared library directories are owned by 'root':\n\u2705 There are no system-wide shared library files not owned by 'root''.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4707e233-89ed-4da0-a113-2ff75e29f09e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230319",
          "group_id_src": "V-230319",
          "rule_id": "SV-230319r1017130",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230319r1017130_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010710",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 world-writable directories must be group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application group.",
          "fix_text": "All directories in local partitions which are world-writable must be group-owned by root or another system account.  If any world-writable directories are not group-owned by a system account, this must be investigated.  Following this, the directories must be deleted or assigned to an appropriate group.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 world-writable directories must be group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application group.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If a world-writable directory is not group-owned by root, sys, bin, or an application Group Identifier (GID), unauthorized users may be able to modify files created by others.\n\nThe only authorized public directories are those temporary directories supplied with the system or those designed to be temporary file repositories. The setting is normally reserved for directories used by the system and by users for temporary file storage, (e.g., /tmp), and for directories requiring global read/write access.",
          "check_content": "The following command will discover and print world-writable directories that are not group-owned by a system account, given the assumption that only system accounts have a gid lower than 1000. Run it once for each local partition [PART]:\n\n$ sudo find [PART] -xdev -type d -perm -0002 -gid +999 -print\n\nIf there is output, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230319"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230319",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "There are no world-writable directories that are not group-owned by a system account",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndf --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | xargs -I PART find PART -mount -xdev -type d -perm -0002  -gid +999 -print 2>/dev/null |xargs -I FILENAME stat -c \"%G %n\" FILENAME\n\nChecking for world-writable directories that are not group-owned by a system account:\n\u2705 There are no world-writable directories that are not group-owned by a system account\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "478d63b4-d372-442e-a053-a341019ca5de",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230426",
          "group_id_src": "V-230426",
          "rule_id": "SV-230426r1017227",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230426r1017227_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030310",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the unix_update in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"unix_update\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_update -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the unix_update in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise. \"Unix_update\" is a helper program for the \"pam_unix\" module that updates the password for a given user. It is not intended to be run directly from the command line and logs a security violation if done so.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"unix_update\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"unix_update\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/unix_update -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230426"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230426",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for 'unix_update' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for 'unix_update' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w \"unix_update\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"unix_update\"\n\nChecking for 'unix_update' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for 'unix_update' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the 'unix_update' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for 'unix_update' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "484590cc-f5d5-4142-88e4-81e0d0d28d72",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230470",
          "group_id_src": "V-230470",
          "rule_id": "SV-230470r1017261",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230470r1017261_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030603",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable Linux audit logging for the USBGuard daemon.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to enable Linux audit logging of the USBGuard daemon by adding or modifying the following line in \"/etc/usbguard/usbguard-daemon.conf\":\n\nAuditBackend=LinuxAudit",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable Linux audit logging for the USBGuard daemon.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nIf auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some startup processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nThe list of audited events is the set of events for which audits are to be generated. This set of events is typically a subset of the list of all events for which the system is capable of generating audit records.\n\nDoD has defined the list of events for which RHEL 8 will provide an audit record generation capability as the following:\n\n1) Successful and unsuccessful attempts to access, modify, or delete privileges, security objects, security levels, or categories of information (e.g., classification levels);\n\n2) Access actions, such as successful and unsuccessful logon attempts, privileged activities or other system-level access, starting and ending time for user access to the system, concurrent logons from different workstations, successful and unsuccessful accesses to objects, all program initiations, and all direct access to the information system;\n\n3) All account creations, modifications, disabling, and terminations; and\n\n4) All kernel module load, unload, and restart actions.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 enables Linux audit logging of the USBGuard daemon with the following commands:\n\nNote: If the USBGuard daemon is not installed and enabled, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep -i auditbackend /etc/usbguard/usbguard-daemon.conf\n\nAuditBackend=LinuxAudit\n\nIf the \"AuditBackend\" entry does not equal \"LinuxAudit\", is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is a virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230470"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230470",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'USBGuard daemon' is not installed, per DISA this check is 'Not Applicable'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed | grep usbguard\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsystemctl status usbguard.service | egrep \"Loaded:|Active:\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i auditbackend /etc/usbguard/usbguard-daemon.conf\n\nChecking if 'USBGuard daemon' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd36 The 'USBGuard daemon' is not installed\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "489f32a4-8124-40c0-9391-84322bfa9d86",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230383",
          "group_id_src": "V-230383",
          "rule_id": "SV-230383r1017192",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230383r1017192_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020351",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nAdd or edit the line for the \"UMASK\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" file to \"077\":\n\nUMASK 077",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must define default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Setting the most restrictive default permissions ensures that when new accounts are created, they do not have unnecessary access.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system defines default permissions for all authenticated users in such a way that the user can only read and modify their own files.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter in \"/etc/login.defs\" file with the following command:\n\nNote: If the value of the \"UMASK\" parameter is set to \"000\" in \"/etc/login.defs\" file, the Severity is raised to a CAT I.\n\n# grep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nUMASK 077\n\nIf the value for the \"UMASK\" parameter is not \"077\", or the \"UMASK\" parameter is missing or is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230383"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230383",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'UMASK' setting is set to '022' in '/etc/login.defs', should be set to '077'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i umask /etc/login.defs\n\nChecking the value for 'UMASK':\n\u274c # Default initial \"umask\" value used by login(1) on non-PAM enabled systems.\n\u274c # Default \"umask\" value for pam_umask(8) on PAM enabled systems.\n\u274c # UMASK is also used by useradd(8) and newusers(8) to set the mode for new\n\u274c UMASK\t\t022\n\u274c # If HOME_MODE is not set, the value of UMASK is used to create the mode.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "492313d1-dc06-4937-9346-4d81023d3642",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230313",
          "group_id_src": "V-230313",
          "rule_id": "SV-230313r1155379",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230313r1155379_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010673",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable core dumps for all users.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable core dumps for all users.\n\nAdd the following line to the top of the /etc/security/limits.conf or in a single \".conf\" file defined in /etc/security/limits.d/:\n\n* hard core 0\n\nRemove or comment out any entries for users or groups with a value set to anything other than \"0\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable core dumps for all users.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore, may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nA core dump includes a memory image taken at the time the operating system terminates an application. The memory image could contain sensitive data and is generally useful only for developers trying to debug problems.",
          "check_content": "Note: If kernel dumps are disabled in accordance with RHEL-08-010671, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 8 disables core dumps for all users by issuing the following command:\n\n$ grep -r -s core /etc/security/limits.conf /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/limits.conf:* hard core 0\n\nThis can be set as a global domain (with the * wildcard) but may be set differently for multiple domains.\n\nIf the \"core\" item is missing or commented out, or the value is anything other than \"0\", and the need for core dumps is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement for all domains that have the \"core\" item assigned, this is a finding.\n\nIf entries exist for users or groups with a value set to anything other than \"0\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230313"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230313",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No 'core' setting found in /etc/security/limits.conf or /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf. Expected: hard core 0.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.core_pattern\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -REsv '^[[:space:]]*#' /etc/security/limits* | grep core\n\nChecking that the OS disables core dumps for all users:\n\u274c No output\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4a79238f-c2f6-4f05-954b-d2fb8a06063b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230434",
          "group_id_src": "V-230434",
          "rule_id": "SV-230434r1017235",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230434r1017235_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030320",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the ssh-keysign in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"ssh-keysign\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/libexec/openssh/ssh-keysign -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-ssh\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the ssh-keysign in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"ssh-keysign\" program is an SSH helper program for host-based authentication.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"ssh-keysign\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep ssh-keysign /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/libexec/openssh/ssh-keysign -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-ssh\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230434"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230434",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'ssh-keysign' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/libexec/openssh/ssh-keysign\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'ssh-keysign' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'ssh-keysign' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4ac77eb7-ccfa-4aee-a964-63214a475513",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230483",
          "group_id_src": "V-230483",
          "rule_id": "SV-230483r971542",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230483r971542_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030730",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nspace_left = 25%\n\nNote: Option names and values in the auditd.conf file are case insensitive.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must take action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nspace_left = 25%\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left\" keyword is not set to \"25%\" or if the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO.\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230483"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001855"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230483",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'space_left' setting is set to '75' in the '/etc/audit/auditd.conf' file, but should be set to '25%'.\nspace_left = 75",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w space_left /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking that the OS takes action when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum:\n\u274c space_left = 75\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4ae9e97f-0cd0-49ed-8fa8-981d39dbd031",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230548",
          "group_id_src": "V-230548",
          "rule_id": "SV-230548r1017310",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230548r1017310_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040284",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the use of user namespaces.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to disable the use of user namespaces by adding the following line to a file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d\" directory:\n\nuser.max_user_namespaces = 0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the use of user namespaces.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 disables the use of user namespaces with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl user.max_user_namespaces\n\nuser.max_user_namespaces = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r user.max_user_namespaces /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: user.max_user_namespaces = 0\n\nIf \"user.max_user_namespaces\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.\n\nIf the use of namespaces is operationally required and documented with the ISSM, it is not a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230548"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230548",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'user.max_user_namespaces' variable is set to '31588' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'user.max_user_namespaces' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl user.max_user_namespaces 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*user.max_user_namespaces' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'user.max_user_namespaces' variable:\n\u274c user.max_user_namespaces = 31588\n\nChecking config files to enable 'user.max_user_namespaces' variable:\n\u274c The 'user.max_user_namespaces' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4b4210c5-7400-4327-8d5f-b251f565fb62",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230390",
          "group_id_src": "V-230390",
          "rule_id": "SV-230390r1038966",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230390r1038966_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030040",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 System must take appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_error_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the ISSO, configure the operating system to notify system administration staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_error_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 System must take appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without this notification, the security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAudit processing failures include software/hardware errors, failures in the audit capturing mechanisms, and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded.\n\nThis requirement applies to each audit data storage repository (i.e., distinct information system component where audit records are stored), the centralized audit storage capacity of organizations (i.e., all audit data storage repositories combined), or both.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs.\n\nCheck that RHEL 8 takes the appropriate action when an audit processing failure occurs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_error_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\ndisk_error_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_error_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit process failure occurs.  If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230390"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000140"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230390",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'disk_error_action' setting is set to 'SUSPEND' in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf', but should be set to 'HALT', 'SYSLOG', or 'SINGLE'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep disk_error_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking the 'disk_error_action' setting in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf:\n\u274c disk_error_action = SUSPEND\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "4cc7006b-5745-40b5-9065-64d9bb1db243",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230230",
          "group_id_src": "V-230230",
          "rule_id": "SV-230230r1069287",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230230r1069287_rule",
