          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'CREATE_HOME' parameter is set to 'yes' in '/etc/login.defs'.\nCREATE_HOME\tyes",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i create_home /etc/login.defs\n\nChecking that all interactive users are assigned a home directory upon creation:\n\u2705 The 'CREATE_HOME' parameter is set to 'yes' in '/etc/login.defs'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "59f43268-f13f-40c1-93fa-c8aabcc98964",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230252",
          "group_id_src": "V-230252",
          "rule_id": "SV-230252r1155364",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230252r1155364_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010291",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH server must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the RHEL 8 SSH server to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nReinstall crypto-policies with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y reinstall crypto-policies\n\nSet the crypto-policy to FIPS with the following command:\n\n$ sudo update-crypto-policies --set FIPS\n\nSetting system policy to FIPS\n\nNote: Systemwide crypto policies are applied on application startup. It is recommended to restart the system for the change of policies to fully take place.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH server must be configured to use only DOD-approved encryption ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-validated cryptographic hash algorithms to protect the confidentiality of SSH server connections.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.\n\nRHEL 8 incorporates systemwide crypto policies by default. The SSH configuration file has no effect on the ciphers, MACs, or algorithms unless specifically defined in the /etc/sysconfig/sshd file. The employed algorithms can be viewed in the /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config file.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093, SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174, SRG-OS-000125-GPOS-00065",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 SSH server is configured to use only ciphers employing FIPS 140-3-approved algorithms.\n\nTo verify the ciphers in the systemwide SSH configuration file, use the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i Ciphers /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config\nCRYPTO_POLICY='-oCiphers=aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\n\nIf the cipher entries in the \"opensshserver.config\" file have any ciphers other than \"aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr\", or they are missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230252"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001453"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230252",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000250-GPOS-00093",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "There are extra ciphers not defined by DISA listed in the '-oCiphers' setting:\naes256-gcm@openssh.com,chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i '\\-ociphers' /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/opensshserver.config\n\nChecking the SSH server ciphers:\n\u274c There are extra ciphers not defined by DISA listed in the '-oCiphers' setting:\naes256-gcm@openssh.com,chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5acd0256-e411-4bcf-af6b-4180c27495ad",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244525",
          "group_id_src": "V-244525",
          "rule_id": "SV-244525r1017331",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244525r1017331_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010201",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic are terminated after 10 minutes of becoming unresponsive.",
          "fix_text": "Note: This setting must be applied in conjunction with RHEL-08-010200 to function correctly.\n\nConfigure the SSH server to terminate a user session automatically after the SSH client has been unresponsive for 10 minutes.\n\nModify or append the following lines in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file:\n\n     ClientAliveInterval 600\n\nFor the changes to take effect, the SSH daemon must be restarted.\n\n     $ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic are terminated after 10 minutes of becoming unresponsive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Terminating an unresponsive SSH session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended. In addition, quickly terminating an idle SSH session will also free up resources committed by the managed network element.\n\nTerminating network connections associated with communications sessions includes, for example, deallocating associated TCP/IP address/port pairs at the operating system level and deallocating networking assignments at the application level if multiple application sessions are using a single operating system-level network connection. This does not mean that the operating system terminates all sessions or network access; it only ends the unresponsive session and releases the resources associated with that session.\n\nRHEL 8 uses /etc/ssh/sshd_config for configurations of OpenSSH. Within the sshd_config, the product of the values of \"ClientAliveInterval\" and \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is used to establish the inactivity threshold. The \"ClientAliveInterval\" is a timeout interval in seconds after which if no data has been received from the client, sshd will send a message through the encrypted channel to request a response from the client. The \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is the number of client alive messages that may be sent without sshd receiving any messages back from the client. If this threshold is met, sshd will disconnect the client. For more information on these settings and others, refer to the sshd_config man pages.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072, SRG-OS-000126-GPOS-00066, SRG-OS-000279-GPOS-00109",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH server automatically terminates a user session after the SSH client has been unresponsive for 10 minutes.\n\nCheck that the \"ClientAliveInterval\" variable is set to a value of \"600\" or less by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*clientaliveinterval'\n\nClientAliveInterval 600\n\nIf \"ClientAliveInterval\" does not exist, does not have a value of \"600\" or less in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\", or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244525"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001133"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244525",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All the 'ClientAliveInterval' settings are commented out",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iH ClientAliveInterval /etc/ssh/sshd_config\n\nChecking the 'ClientAliveInterval' variable:\n\u274c /etc/ssh/sshd_config:#ClientAliveInterval 0\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5b37db4d-7780-4744-ad00-06ae95a96002",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244534",
          "group_id_src": "V-244534",
          "rule_id": "SV-244534r1069319",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244534r1069319_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020026",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/password-auth file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\nThe preauth argument must be used when the module is called before the modules which ask for the user credentials such as the password.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Note: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.2 or newer, if the system is RHEL version 8.0 or 8.1, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the pam_faillock.so module is present and is listed before the pam.unix.so line in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file:\nNote: The first field in the output is the line number of the entry\n\n$ sudo grep -E -n 'pam_faillock.so|pam_unix.so' /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\n7:auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent\n11:auth sufficient pam_unix.so\n15:auth required pam_faillock.so authfail\n19:account required pam_faillock.so\n20:account required pam_unix.so\n31:password sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 shadow use_authtok\n40:session required pam_unix.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244534"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244534",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "pam_faillock.so with 'preauth' was not found in /etc/pam.d/password-auth.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -E -n 'pam_faillock.so|pam_unix.so' /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\u2705 Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking if pam_faillock.so module is present and is listed before the pam.unix.so line:\n5:auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\n8:account     required      pam_unix.so\n11:password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n18:session     required      pam_unix.so\n\u274c pam_faillock.so with 'preauth' not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5b390826-854f-45f8-82af-0b48138c3afe",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230510",
          "group_id_src": "V-230510",
          "rule_id": "SV-230510r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230510r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040122",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /dev/shm with the noexec option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /dev/shm is mounted with the \"noexec\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\ntmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /dev/shm with the noexec option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/dev/shm\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /dev/shm\n\ntmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"noexec\" options is configured for /dev/shm:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /dev/shm\n\ntmpfs /dev/shm tmpfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"noexec\" option is missing, or if /dev/shm is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230510"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230510",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/dev/shm' is not mounted with the 'noexec' option.\n   tmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,seclabel)\n'/dev/shm' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /dev/shm\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /dev/shm\n\nChecking if '/dev/shm' is mounted with 'noexec' option:\n\u274c '/dev/shm' is not mounted with the 'noexec' option.\n   tmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev,seclabel)\n\n\nChecking that the 'noexec' is configured for '/dev/shm':\n\u274c '/dev/shm' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5d00d85f-397a-4685-bb9c-61e926c3db36",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-237641",
          "group_id_src": "V-237641",
          "rule_id": "SV-237641r1101904",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-237641r1101904_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010382",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict privilege elevation to authorized personnel.",
          "fix_text": "Remove the following entries from the sudoers file:\nALL     ALL=(ALL) ALL\nALL     ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict privilege elevation to authorized personnel.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The sudo command allows a user to execute programs with elevated (administrator) privileges. It prompts the user for their password and confirms your request to execute a command by checking a file, called sudoers. If the \"sudoers\" file is not configured correctly, any user defined on the system can initiate privileged actions on the target system.",
          "check_content": "Verify the \"sudoers\" file restricts sudo access to authorized personnel.\n\n$ sudo grep -iwR 'ALL' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/ | grep -v '#'\n\nIf the either of the following entries are returned, this is a finding:\nALL     ALL=(ALL) ALL\nALL     ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-237641"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-237641",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'ALL ALL=(ALL) ALL' and 'ALL ALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL' entries were not found in '/etc/sudoers' or any file in '/etc/sudoers.d/*'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iwRH 'ALL' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/ 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if 'sudoers' file restricts sudo access:\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:root\tALL=(ALL) \tALL\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:# %sys ALL = NETWORKING, SOFTWARE, SERVICES, STORAGE, DELEGATING, PROCESSES, LOCATE, DRIVERS\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:## Allows people in group wheel to run all commands\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:%wheel\tALL=(ALL)\tALL\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:# %wheel\tALL=(ALL)\tNOPASSWD: ALL\n\u2705 /etc/sudoers:# %users  ALL=/sbin/mount /mnt/cdrom, /sbin/umount /mnt/cdrom\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5d317d83-f408-4192-a553-01d9f1fe475e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230317",
          "group_id_src": "V-230317",
          "rule_id": "SV-230317r1069320",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230317r1069320_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010690",
          "rule_title": "Executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive RHEL 8 users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the local interactive user initialization files to change any PATH variable statements that reference directories other than their home directory.\n\nIf a local interactive user requires path variables to reference a directory owned by the application, it must be documented with the ISSO.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Executable search paths within the initialization files of all local interactive RHEL 8 users must only contain paths that resolve to the system default or the users home directory.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The executable search path (typically the PATH environment variable) contains a list of directories for the shell to search to find executables. If this path includes the current working directory (other than the user's home directory), executables in these directories may be executed instead of system commands. This variable is formatted as a colon-separated list of directories. If there is an empty entry, such as a leading or trailing colon or two consecutive colons, this is interpreted as the current working directory. If deviations from the default system search path for the local interactive user are required, they must be documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO).",
          "check_content": "Verify that all local interactive user initialization file executable search path statements do not contain statements that will reference a working directory other than user home directories with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep -irw path= /home/*/.*\n\n/home/[localinteractiveuser]/.bash_profile:PATH=$PATH:$HOME/.local/bin:$HOME/bin\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files have executable search path statements that include directories outside of their home directory and is not documented with the ISSO as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230317"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230317",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No local interactive user initialization files have executable search path statements that include directories outside of their home directory",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n        if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n                echo \"#USERNAME:$username HOMEDIRECTORY:$homedir\"\n                grep -REIH '^\\s*export\\s*PATH=|^\\s*PATH=' $homedir/.[^.]* 2>/dev/null\n        fi\ndone < $FILENAME\n\nChecking interactive users initilaization files for 'PATH' entries:\nUser Name: root\n\u2705 'root' has no executable path statements that include directories outside ot their home directory ('/root')\nUser Name: deckerr\n\u2705 'deckerr' has no executable path statements that include directories outside ot their home directory ('/home/deckerr')\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5e1621c9-efb6-47ad-b22a-aa39cb980f6b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230327",
          "group_id_src": "V-230327",
          "rule_id": "SV-230327r1069285",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230327r1069285_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010790",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 local files and directories must have a valid group owner.",
          "fix_text": "Either remove all files and directories from RHEL 8 that do not have a valid group, or assign a valid group to all files and directories on the system with the \"chgrp\" command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp <group> <file>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 local files and directories must have a valid group owner.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Files without a valid group owner may be unintentionally inherited if a group is assigned the same Group Identifier (GID) as the GID of the files without a valid group owner.",
          "check_content": "Verify all local files and directories on RHEL 8 have a valid group with the following command:\n\n$ df --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | sudo xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nogroup\n\nIf any files on the system do not have an assigned group, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230327"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230327",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All local files and directories on RHEL 8 have a valid group assigned.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndf --local -P | awk {'if (NR!=1) print $6'} | xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -nogroup 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking that all local files and directories on RHEL 8 have a valid group:\n\u2705 No groupless files found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5eb48504-1443-4568-9352-7fd12289f529",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230425",
          "group_id_src": "V-230425",
          "rule_id": "SV-230425r1017226",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230425r1017226_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030302",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the mount syscall in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"mount\" syscall by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S mount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S mount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the mount syscall in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"mount\" syscall is used to mount a filesystem.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"mount\" syscall by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"\\-S mount\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S mount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S mount -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230425"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230425",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The rule for the 'mount' syscall was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe rule for the 'mount' syscall was not found in the running rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -w \"\\-S mount\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"\\-S mount\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\nChecking for the 'mount' syscall rule in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The rule for the 'mount' syscall was not found\n\nChecking for the running audit rule for the 'mount' syscall:\n\u274c The rule for the 'mount' syscall was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "5f7671f1-6818-495f-ac20-74986588a662",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230435",
          "group_id_src": "V-230435",
          "rule_id": "SV-230435r1017236",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230435r1017236_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030330",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the setfacl command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"setfacl\" command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the setfacl command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"setfacl\" command is used to set file access control lists.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"setfacl\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w setfacl /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/setfacl -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_mod\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230435"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230435",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfacl' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"/usr/bin/setfacl\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfacl' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setfacl' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "60792d81-f9f4-48a4-b2ea-3d1b28df3ec7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230428",
          "group_id_src": "V-230428",
          "rule_id": "SV-230428r1017229",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230428r1017229_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030312",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of postqueue in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"postqueue\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/postqueue -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of postqueue in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise. The \"postqueue\" command implements the Postfix user interface for queue management.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of \"postqueue\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"postqueue\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/postqueue -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230428"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230428",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for 'postqueue' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for 'postqueue' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w \"postqueue\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"postqueue\"\n\nChecking for 'postqueue' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for 'postqueue' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the 'postqueue' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for 'postqueue' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "615bd3e0-ea49-48e7-97ed-198edd0e35de",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230328",
          "group_id_src": "V-230328",
          "rule_id": "SV-230328r1155410",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230328r1155410_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010800",
          "rule_title": "A separate RHEL 8 filesystem must be used for user home directories (such as /home or an equivalent).",
          "fix_text": "Migrate the \"/home\" directory onto a separate file system.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "A separate RHEL 8 filesystem must be used for user home directories (such as /home or an equivalent).",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.",
          "check_content": "Verify a separate file system has been created for nonprivileged local interactive user home directories.\n\nCheck the home directory assignment for all nonprivileged users, users with a User Identifier (UID) greater than 1000, on the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1,$3,$6,$7}' /etc/passwd\npdosadmin 1000 /home/pdosadmin /bin/bash\nsystemuser 1001 /home/systemuser /bin/bash\nacas 1002 /home/acas /bin/bash\n\nThe output of the command will give the directory/partition that contains the home directories for the nonprivileged users on the system (in this example, \"/home\") and users\u2019 shell. All accounts with a valid shell (such as /bin/bash) are considered interactive users.\n\nCheck that a file system/partition has been created for the nonprivileged interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The partition of \"/home\" is used in the example.\n\n$ sudo grep /home /etc/fstab\n\n/dev/mapper/...   /home   xfs   defaults,noexec,nosuid,nodev 0 0\n\nIf a separate entry for the file system/partition containing the nonprivileged interactive user home directories does not exist, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230328"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230328",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Home directories not on a separate partition as required.",
          "finding_details": "##echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#grep 'HOME=' /etc/default/useradd\n#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#cut -d: -f 1,3,6,7 /etc/passwd | grep -v \"/sbin/nologin\\|/sbin/halt\\|/bin/sync\\|/sbin/shutdown\\|/bin/false\\|/bin/true\\|/usr/sbin/nologin\\|root\" | grep -v \"^#\"\n#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#cat /etc/fstab\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nwhile IFS=\":\" read -r username password uid gid info home shell; do\n  rootDevID=$(stat -c \"%d\" /)\n  homeDevID=$(stat -c \"%d\" \"$home\")\n  echo \"$username:$home:$rootDevID:$homeDevID\"\ndone < <(grep -E -v \"(nologin|false|true|halt|shutdown|sync|root)\" /etc/passwd)\n\ndeckerr:/home/deckerr:64768:64768\n\u274c User: deckerr | home directory /home/deckerr not on separate partition from /\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6201b048-0407-4e15-8fc8-db6006f54a0c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230244",
          "group_id_src": "V-230244",
          "rule_id": "SV-230244r1069300",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230244r1069300_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010200",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic terminate after becoming unresponsive.",
          "fix_text": "Note: This setting must be applied in conjunction with RHEL-08-010201 to function correctly.\n\nConfigure the SSH server to terminate a user session automatically after the SSH client has become unresponsive.\n\nModify or append the following lines in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file:\n\n     ClientAliveCountMax 1\n\nFor the changes to take effect, the SSH daemon must be restarted:\n\n     $ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all network connections associated with SSH traffic terminate after becoming unresponsive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Terminating an unresponsive SSH session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended. In addition, quickly terminating an idle SSH session will also free up resources committed by the managed network element.\n\nTerminating network connections associated with communications sessions includes, for example, deallocating associated TCP/IP address/port pairs at the operating system level and deallocating networking assignments at the application level if multiple application sessions are using a single operating system-level network connection. This does not mean the operating system terminates all sessions or network access; it only ends the unresponsive session and releases the resources associated with that session.\n\nRHEL 8 uses /etc/ssh/sshd_config for configurations of OpenSSH. Within the sshd_config, the product of the values of \"ClientAliveInterval\" and \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is used to establish the inactivity threshold. The \"ClientAliveInterval\" is a timeout interval in seconds after which if no data has been received from the client, sshd will send a message through the encrypted channel to request a response from the client. The \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is the number of client alive messages that may be sent without sshd receiving any messages back from the client. If this threshold is met, sshd will disconnect the client. For more information on these settings and others, refer to the sshd_config man pages.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072, SRG-OS-000126-GPOS-00066, SRG-OS-000279-GPOS-00109",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH server automatically terminates a user session after the SSH client has become unresponsive.\n\nCheck that the \"ClientAliveCountMax\" is set to \"1\" by performing the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*clientalivecountmax'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:ClientAliveCountMax 1\n\nIf \"ClientAliveCountMax\" do not exist, is not set to a value of \"1\" in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\", or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230244"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001133"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230244",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000163-GPOS-00072",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'ClientAliveCountMax' is set to '3' in the sshd effective configuration, but should be set to '1':\nclientalivecountmax 3",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'ClientAliveCountMax' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u274c clientalivecountmax 3\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "625d8a02-aa41-4635-975d-f8e7a6703dce",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230541",
          "group_id_src": "V-230541",
          "rule_id": "SV-230541r1017303",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230541r1017303_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040261",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces unless the system is a router.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Routing protocol daemons are typically used on routers to exchange network topology information with other routers. If this software is used when not required, system network information may be unnecessarily transmitted across the network.\n\nAn illicit router advertisement message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not accept router advertisements on all IPv6 interfaces, unless the system is a router.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nCheck to see if router advertisements are not accepted by using the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl  net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf the \"accept_ra\" value is not \"0\" and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230541"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230541",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' setting returned from 'sysctl' is set to '1', but should have returned '0'.\nNo configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' setting.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl -a 2>/dev/null | grep 'net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if IPv6 is disabled on the system:\n\ud83d\udd0d IPv6 is not disabled\n\nChecking the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' setting using 'sysctl':\n\u274c net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 1\n\nChecking for the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' setting in configuration files:\n\u274c No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra' setting\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "63115444-434e-4b51-91aa-79182145d50f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230282",
          "group_id_src": "V-230282",
          "rule_id": "SV-230282r958944",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230282r958944_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010450",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable the SELinux targeted policy.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to verify correct operation of all security functions.\n\nSet the \"SELinuxtype\" to the \"targeted\" policy by modifying the \"/etc/selinux/config\" file to have the following line:\n\nSELINUXTYPE=targeted\n\nA reboot is required for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable the SELinux targeted policy.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nThis requirement applies to operating systems performing security function verification/testing and/or systems and environments that require this functionality.",
          "check_content": "Ensure the operating system verifies correct operation of all security functions.\n\nCheck if \"SELinux\" is active and is enforcing the targeted policy with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sestatus\n\nSELinux status: enabled\nSELinuxfs mount: /sys/fs/selinux\nSELinux root directory: /etc/selinux\nLoaded policy name: targeted\nCurrent mode: enforcing\nMode from config file: enforcing\nPolicy MLS status: enabled\nPolicy deny_unknown status: allowed\nMemory protection checking: actual (secure)\nMax kernel policy version: 31\n\nIf the \"Loaded policy name\" is not set to \"targeted\", this is a finding.\n\nVerify that the /etc/selinux/config file is configured to the \"SELINUXTYPE\" to \"targeted\":\n\n$ sudo grep -i \"selinuxtype\" /etc/selinux/config | grep -v '^#'\n\nSELINUXTYPE = targeted\n\nIf no results are returned or \"SELINUXTYPE\" is not set to \"targeted\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230282"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002696"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230282",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000445-GPOS-00199",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'Loaded policy name' setting via 'sestatus' is set to 'targeted' and the 'SELINUXTYPE' setting in '/etc/selinux/config' is set to 'targeted'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsestatus | grep \"Loaded policy name:\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i \"selinuxtype\" /etc/selinux/config | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nChecking 'Loaded policy name' setting via 'sestatus':\n\u2705 Loaded policy name:             targeted\n\nChecking 'SELINUXTYPE' in '/etc/selinux/config':\n\u2705 SELINUXTYPE=targeted\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "63408131-d37d-4dc2-a96c-98e58c6f2ded",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230281",
          "group_id_src": "V-230281",
          "rule_id": "SV-230281r958936",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230281r958936_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010440",
          "rule_title": "YUM must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed on RHEL 8.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.\n\nSet the \"clean_requirements_on_remove\" option to \"True\" in the \"/etc/dnf/dnf.conf\" file:\n\nclean_requirements_on_remove=True",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "YUM must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed on RHEL 8.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Previous versions of software components that are not removed from the information system after updates have been installed may be exploited by adversaries. Some information technology products may remove older versions of software automatically from the information system.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system removes all software components after updated versions have been installed.\n\nCheck if YUM is configured to remove unneeded packages with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i clean_requirements_on_remove /etc/dnf/dnf.conf\n\nclean_requirements_on_remove=True\n\nIf \"clean_requirements_on_remove\" is not set to either \"1\", \"True\", or \"yes\", commented out, or is missing from \"/etc/dnf/dnf.conf\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230281"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002617"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230281",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000437-GPOS-00194",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'clean_requirements_on_remove' setting is set to 'True' in the '/etc/dnf/dnf.conf' file.\nclean_requirements_on_remove=True",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i clean_requirements_on_remove /etc/dnf/dnf.conf\n\nChecking if 'YUM' is configured to remove unneeded packages:\n\u2705 clean_requirements_on_remove=True\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "64443bfe-e951-4110-9f85-d429a2b23720",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230395",
          "group_id_src": "V-230395",
          "rule_id": "SV-230395r1017201",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230395r1017201_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030063",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must resolve audit information before writing to disk.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"log_format\" option:\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must resolve audit information before writing to disk.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nEnriched logging aids in making sense of who, what, and when events occur on a system.  Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 Audit Daemon is configured to resolve audit information before writing to disk, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"log_format\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_format = ENRICHED\n\nIf the \"log_format\" option is not \"ENRICHED\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230395"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230395",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'log_format' setting is set to 'ENRICHED' in the '/etc/audit/auditd.conf' file.\nlog_format = ENRICHED",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep \"log_format\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking that the Audit Daemon is configured to resolve audit information be writing to disk:\n\u2705 log_format = ENRICHED\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "662bf5ef-358c-482c-8bad-ba655dce422c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230301",
          "group_id_src": "V-230301",
          "rule_id": "SV-230301r1155405",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230301r1155405_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010580",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent special devices on non-root local partitions.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on all non-root local partitions.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent special devices on non-root local partitions.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for nonprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access. The only legitimate location for device files is the /dev directory located on the root partition.",
          "check_content": "Note: This control is not applicable to vfat file systems.\n\nVerify all non-root local partitions are mounted with the \"nodev\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep '^/dev\\S* on /\\S' | grep --invert-match 'nodev'\n\nIf any output is produced, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230301"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230301",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following non-root local partitions are mounted without the 'nodev' option:\n/dev/vda1 on /boot type ext4 (rw,relatime,seclabel)",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep '^/dev\\S* on /\\S' | grep -v vfat | grep --invert-match 'nodev'\n\nChecking that all non-root local partitions are mounted with the 'nodev' option:\n\u274c The following non-root local partitions are mounted without the 'nodev' option:\n/dev/vda1 on /boot type ext4 (rw,relatime,seclabel)\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6642d473-173d-4b0e-a5c3-3d38c6b6f6d3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230229",
          "group_id_src": "V-230229",
          "rule_id": "SV-230229r1017048",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230229r1017048_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010090",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8, for PKI-based authentication, to validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nObtain a valid copy of the DoD root CA file from the PKI CA certificate bundle at cyber.mil and copy into the following file:\n\n/etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8, for PKI-based authentication, must validate certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without path validation, an informed trust decision by the relying party cannot be made when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted.\n\nA trust anchor is an authoritative entity represented via a public key and associated data. It is used in the context of public key infrastructures, X.509 digital certificates, and DNSSEC.\n\nWhen there is a chain of trust, usually the top entity to be trusted becomes the trust anchor; it can be, for example, a Certification Authority (CA). A certification path starts with the subject certificate and proceeds through a number of intermediate certificates up to a trusted root certificate, typically issued by a trusted CA.\n\nThis requirement verifies that a certification path to an accepted trust anchor is used for certificate validation and that the path includes status information. Path validation is necessary for a relying party to make an informed trust decision when presented with any certificate not already explicitly trusted. Status information for certification paths includes certificate revocation lists or online certificate status protocol responses. Validation of the certificate status information is out of scope for this requirement.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034, SRG-OS-000384-GPOS-00167",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 for PKI-based authentication has valid certificates by constructing a certification path (which includes status information) to an accepted trust anchor.\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nCheck that the system has a valid DoD root CA installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo openssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\n\nCertificate:\n   Data:\n      Version: 3 (0x2)\n      Serial Number: 1 (0x1)\n      Signature Algorithm: sha256WithRSAEncryption\n      Issuer: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DoD, OU = PKI, CN = DoD Root CA 3\n      Validity\n         Not Before: Mar 20 18:46:41 2012 GMT\n         Not After   : Dec 30 18:46:41 2029 GMT\n      Subject: C = US, O = U.S. Government, OU = DoD, OU = PKI, CN = DoD Root CA 3\n      Subject Public Key Info:\n         Public Key Algorithm: rsaEncryption\n\nIf the root ca file is not a DoD-issued certificate with a valid date and installed in the /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem location, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230229"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000185"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230229",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000066-GPOS-00034",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'sssd_auth_ca.pem' file does not exist in '/etc/sssd/pki'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nopenssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nopenssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem | grep -i 'Issuer:'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nopenssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem | grep -i 'Not Before:'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nopenssl x509 -text -in /etc/sssd/pki/sssd_auth_ca_db.pem | grep -i 'Not After :'\n\nChecking that the system has a valid DoD root CA installed:\n\u274c The 'sssd_auth_ca.pem' file does not exist in '/etc/sssd/pki'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "664fd7cc-3369-4258-af44-7a31d5c1f819",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230392",
          "group_id_src": "V-230392",
          "rule_id": "SV-230392r1038966",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230392r1038966_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030060",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to shut down by default upon audit failure (unless availability is an overriding concern).\n\nAdd or update the following line (depending on configuration \"disk_full_action\" can be set to \"SYSLOG\" or \"SINGLE\" depending on configuration) in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf availability has been determined to be more important, and this decision is documented with the ISSO, configure the operating system to notify system administration staff and ISSO staff in the event of an audit processing failure by setting the \"disk_full_action\" to \"SYSLOG\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must take appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is critical that when RHEL 8 is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required, it takes action to mitigate the failure. Audit processing failures include software/hardware errors; failures in the audit capturing mechanisms; and audit storage capacity being reached or exceeded. Responses to audit failure depend upon the nature of the failure mode.\n\nWhen availability is an overriding concern, other approved actions in response to an audit failure are as follows:\n\n1) If the failure was caused by the lack of audit record storage capacity, RHEL 8 must continue generating audit records if possible (automatically restarting the audit service if necessary) and overwriting the oldest audit records in a first-in-first-out manner.\n\n2) If audit records are sent to a centralized collection server and communication with this server is lost or the server fails, RHEL 8 must queue audit records locally until communication is restored or until the audit records are retrieved manually. Upon restoration of the connection to the centralized collection server, action should be taken to synchronize the local audit data with the collection server.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full.\n\nCheck that RHEL 8 takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep disk_full_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\ndisk_full_action = HALT\n\nIf the value of the \"disk_full_action\" option is not \"SYSLOG\", \"SINGLE\", or \"HALT\", or the line is commented out, ask the system administrator to indicate how the system takes appropriate action when an audit storage volume is full.  If there is no evidence of appropriate action, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230392"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000140"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230392",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000047-GPOS-00023",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'disk_full_action' setting is set to 'SUSPEND' in the '/etc/audit/auditd.conf' file, but should be set to 'HALT', 'SYSLOG', or 'SINGLE'.\ndisk_full_action = SUSPEND",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep disk_full_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking that the OS takes the appropriate action when the audit storage volume is full:\n\u274c disk_full_action = SUSPEND\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "665fa684-c36c-4446-8177-5f2753dde7bf",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230444",
          "group_id_src": "V-230444",
          "rule_id": "SV-230444r1017244",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230444r1017244_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030370",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the gpasswd command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"gpasswd\" command by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/gpasswd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-gpasswd\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the gpasswd command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"gpasswd\" command is used to administer /etc/group and /etc/gshadow. Every group can have administrators, members and a password.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"gpasswd\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w gpasswd /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/gpasswd -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-gpasswd\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230444"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230444",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'gpasswd' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/bin/gpasswd\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'gpasswd' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'gpasswd' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "67b1b59f-43ec-470b-aabc-0ec404dddd91",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-250316",
          "group_id_src": "V-250316",
          "rule_id": "SV-250316r1017357",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-250316r1017357_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020028",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 systems below version 8.2 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a non-default faillock tally directory.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to allow the use of a non-default faillock tally directory while SELinux enforces a targeted policy.\n\nUpdate the /etc/selinux/targeted/contexts/files/file_contexts.local with \"faillog_t\" context type for the non-default faillock tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo semanage fcontext -a -t faillog_t \"/var/log/faillock(/.*)?\"\n\nNext, update the context type of the non-default faillock directory/subdirectories and files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo restorecon -R -v /var/log/faillock",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 systems below version 8.2 must configure SELinux context type to allow the use of a non-default faillock tally directory.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nFrom \"Pam_Faillock\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable, a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSELinux, enforcing a targeted policy, will require any non-default tally directory's security context type to match the default directory's security context type. Without updating the security context type, the pam_faillock module will not write failed login attempts to the non-default tally directory.",
          "check_content": "If the system does not have SELinux enabled and enforcing a targeted policy, or if the pam_faillock module is not configured for use, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nNote: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.0 and 8.1. If the system is RHEL version 8.2 or newer, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the location of the non-default tally directory for the pam_faillock module with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w dir /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth   required   pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock\nauth   required   pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock\n\nCheck the security context type of the non-default tally directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -Zd /var/log/faillock\n\nunconfined_u:object_r:faillog_t:s0 /var/log/faillock\n\nIf the security context type of the non-default tally directory is not \"faillog_t\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-250316"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044",
            "CCI-002238"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-250316",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The version of Red Hat is '8.10', per DISA this requirement is Not Applicable\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsestatus |grep 'SELinux status\\|Loaded policy name\\|Current mode'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#Checking if the pam_faillock module is configured for use\n#if a line is returned the module is configured\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep preauth | grep -v \"^#\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#Checking the default tally directory\nls -Zd /var/run/faillock\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth |grep preauth | grep -v \"^#\" | awk -F \"dir=\" '{print $2}' |cut -d\" \" -f1 |xargs -I DIR echo \"DIR\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth |grep preauth | grep -v \"^#\" | awk -F \"dir=\" '{print $2}' |cut -d\" \" -f1 |xargs -I DIR ls -Zd DIR\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\ud83d\udd0d Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\nThe version of Red Hat is '8.10', per DISA this requirement is Not Applicable\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "67d94b13-ddd0-4657-9471-a2bf112847c5",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230399",
          "group_id_src": "V-230399",
          "rule_id": "SV-230399r1017205",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230399r1017205_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030100",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log to be protected from unauthorized read access, by setting the correct owner as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chown root [audit_log_directory]\n\nReplace \"[audit_log_directory]\" with the correct audit log directory path, by default this location is usually \"/var/log/audit\".",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit log directory must be owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit RHEL 8 activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit log directory is owned by \"root\" to prevent unauthorized read access.\n\nDetermine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nDetermine the owner of the audit log directory by using the output of the above command (ex: \"/var/log/audit/\"). Run the following command with the correct audit log directory path:\n\n$ sudo ls -ld /var/log/audit\n\ndrw------- 2 root root 23 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit log directory is not owned by \"root\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230399"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230399",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The owner of '/var/log/audit' is 'root'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndirname /var/log/audit/audit.log | xargs -I DIR stat -c \"%U\" DIR \necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d= -f2 | xargs -I DIR dirname DIR | xargs stat -c \"%U\"\n\nDetermining the audit log directory:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log Directory: /var/log/audit\n\nChecking the owner of '/var/log/audit':\n\u2705 Owner = root\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "67faee78-a942-45df-8ef2-4bb9252db7c6",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-256974",
          "group_id_src": "V-256974",
          "rule_id": "SV-256974r1069321",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-256974r1069321_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010358",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to allow sending email notifications of unauthorized configuration changes to designated personnel.",
          "fix_text": "Install the \"mailx\" package on the system:\n\n     $ sudo yum install mailx",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to allow sending email notifications of unauthorized configuration changes to designated personnel.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized changes to the baseline configuration could make the system vulnerable to various attacks or allow unauthorized access to the operating system. Changes to operating system configurations can have unintended side effects, some of which may be relevant to security.\n\nDetecting such changes and providing an automated response can help avoid unintended, negative consequences that could ultimately affect the security state of the operating system. The operating system's IMO/ISSO and SAs must be notified via email and/or monitoring system trap when there is an unauthorized modification of a configuration item.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the operating system is configured to allow sending email notifications.\n\nNote: The \"mailx\" package provides the \"mail\" command that is used to send email messages. The s-nail package is also suitable and may be used in place of mailx.\n\nVerify that the \"mailx\" package is installed on the system:\n\n     $ sudo yum list installed mailx\n\n     mailx.x86_64     12.5-29.el8     @rhel-8-for-x86_64-baseos-rpm\n\nIf \"mailx\" package is not installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-256974"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001744"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-256974",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000363-GPOS-00150",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Neither mailx nor s-nail is installed; one is required to support email notifications.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndnf list installed mailx\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndnf list installed s-nail\n\nChecking if 'mail-x' is installed:\n\u274c No output\n\nChecking if 's-nail' is installed:\n\u274c No output\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "68143806-fedb-4a57-aeb9-91066603534a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230259",
          "group_id_src": "V-230259",
          "rule_id": "SV-230259r1017079",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230259r1017079_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010320",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 system commands must be group-owned by root or a system account.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system commands to be protected from unauthorized access.\n\nRun the following command, replacing \"[FILE]\" with any system command file not group-owned by \"root\" or a required system account.\n\n$ sudo chgrp root [FILE]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 system commands must be group-owned by root or a system account.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If RHEL 8 were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to RHEL 8 with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs that execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals will be allowed to obtain access to information system components for purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.",
          "check_content": "Verify the system commands contained in the following directories are group-owned by \"root\", or a required system account, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo find -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -exec ls -l {} \\;\n\nIf any system commands are returned and is not group-owned by a required system account, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230259"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001499"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230259",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000259-GPOS-00100",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following system commands are not grou-owned by 'root':\ntty:5:/bin/write\nslocate:21:/bin/locate\nlock:54:/sbin/lockdev\ntty:5:/usr/bin/write\nslocate:21:/usr/bin/locate\nlock:54:/usr/sbin/lockdev",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nfind -L /bin /sbin /usr/bin /usr/sbin /usr/local/bin /usr/local/sbin ! -group root -exec stat -c '%G:%g:%n' {} \\; 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking that 'root' is the group-owner of system commands in '/bin', '/sbin', '/usr/bin', '/usr/sbin', '/usr/local/bin', and '/usr/local/sbin':\n\u274c The following system commands are not group-owned by 'root'\nand need to be reviewed to check for system accounts:\n   tty:5:/bin/write\n   slocate:21:/bin/locate\n   lock:54:/sbin/lockdev\n   tty:5:/usr/bin/write\n   slocate:21:/usr/bin/locate\n   lock:54:/usr/sbin/lockdev\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "68630bee-60fe-468f-bb80-e73f384c9185",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230438",
          "group_id_src": "V-230438",
          "rule_id": "SV-230438r1017241",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230438r1017241_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030360",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the init_module and finit_module system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"init_module\" and \"finit_module\" system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the init_module and finit_module system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"init_module\" and \"finit_module\" system calls are used to load a kernel module.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"init_module\" and \"finit_module\" system calls by using the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep init_module /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module,finit_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"init_module\" and \"finit_module\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230438"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230438",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'init_module' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'init_module' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'finit_module' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'finit_module' does not exist.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w init_module | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w init_module | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w finit_module | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w finit_module | grep b64\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'init_module':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'init_module' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'init_module' does not exist.\nChecking audit records are generated for 'finit_module':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'finit_module' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'finit_module' does not exist.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "68e3fce6-5e59-4af3-a3c6-5d1694f86a9f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230491",
          "group_id_src": "V-230491",
          "rule_id": "SV-230491r1017274",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230491r1017274_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040004",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enable mitigations against processor-based vulnerabilities.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to enable kernel page-table isolation with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=\"pti=on\"\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/default/grub\" to ensure the configuration survives kernel updates:\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"pti=on\"",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enable mitigations against processor-based vulnerabilities.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nExamples of non-essential capabilities include, but are not limited to, games, software packages, tools, and demonstration software not related to requirements or providing a wide array of functionality not required for every mission, but which cannot be disabled.\n\nVerify the operating system is configured to disable non-essential capabilities. The most secure way of ensuring a non-essential capability is disabled is to not have the capability installed.\n\nKernel page-table isolation is a kernel feature that mitigates the Meltdown security vulnerability and hardens the kernel against attempts to bypass kernel address space layout randomization (KASLR).",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 enables kernel page-table isolation with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grub2-editenv list | grep pti\n\nkernelopts=root=/dev/mapper/rhel-root ro crashkernel=auto resume=/dev/mapper/rhel-swap rd.lvm.lv=rhel/root rd.lvm.lv=rhel/swap rhgb quiet fips=1 audit=1 audit_backlog_limit=8192 pti=on boot=UUID=8d171156-cd61-421c-ba41-1c021ac29e82\n\nIf the \"pti\" entry does not equal \"on\", is missing, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that kernel page-table isolation is enabled by default to persist in kernel updates:\n\n$ sudo grep pti /etc/default/grub\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"pti=on\"\n\nIf \"pti\" is not set to \"on\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230491"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230491",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'pti' setting does not exist in 'grub2-editenv'\nThe 'pti' setting does not exist in '/etc/default/grub'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrub2-editenv list | grep kernelopts\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pti /etc/default/grub\n\nChecking 'pti' in 'grub2-editenv':\n\u274c The 'pti' setting does not exist\n\nChecking 'pti' in '/etc/default/grub':\n\u274c The 'pti' setting does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "69d8b5e0-bbff-404f-a79a-77beec3ea54d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-237642",
          "group_id_src": "V-237642",
          "rule_id": "SV-237642r991589",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-237642r991589_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010383",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must use the invoking user's password for privilege escalation when using \"sudo\".",
          "fix_text": "Define the following in the Defaults section of the /etc/sudoers file or a configuration file in the /etc/sudoers.d/ directory:\n     Defaults !targetpw\n     Defaults !rootpw\n     Defaults !runaspw\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n     /etc/sudoers\n     /etc/sudoers.d/",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must use the invoking user's password for privilege escalation when using \"sudo\".",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The sudoers security policy requires that users authenticate themselves before they can use sudo. When sudoers requires authentication, it validates the invoking user's credentials. If the rootpw, targetpw, or runaspw flags are defined and not disabled, by default the operating system will prompt the invoking user for the \"root\" user password.\nFor more information on each of the listed configurations, reference the sudoers(5) manual page.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the sudoers security policy is configured to use the invoking user's password for privilege escalation.\n\n     $ sudo grep -Eir '(rootpw|targetpw|runaspw)' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d* | grep -v '#'\n\n     /etc/sudoers:Defaults !targetpw\n     /etc/sudoers:Defaults !rootpw\n     /etc/sudoers:Defaults !runaspw\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.\nIf \"Defaults !targetpw\" is not defined, this is a finding.\nIf \"Defaults !rootpw\" is not defined, this is a finding.\nIf \"Defaults !runaspw\" is not defined, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-237642"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002227"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-237642",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'Defaults !rootpw' line does not exist in '/etc/sudoers or in any configuration file in the '/etc/sudoers.d/' directory\n'Defaults !targetpw' line does not exist in '/etc/sudoers or in any configuration file in the '/etc/sudoers.d/' directory\n'Defaults !runaspw' line does not exist in '/etc/sudoers or in any configuration file in the '/etc/sudoers.d/' directory",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -ir 'rootpw' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d* 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -ir 'targetpw' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d* 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -ir 'runaspw' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'rootpw' option:\n\u274c 'Defaults !rootpw' line does not exist\n\nChecking for the 'targetpw' option:\n\u274c 'Defaults !targetpw' line does not exist\n\nChecking for the 'runaspw' option:\n\u274c 'Defaults !runaspw' line does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6a2960fa-e2fc-409e-bb86-f48b9076794d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230277",
          "group_id_src": "V-230277",
          "rule_id": "SV-230277r1017090",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230277r1017090_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010421",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must clear the page allocator to prevent use-after-free attacks.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to enable page poisoning with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=\"page_poison=1\"\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/default/grub\" to ensure the configuration survives kernel updates:\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"page_poison=1\"",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must clear the page allocator to prevent use-after-free attacks.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Some adversaries launch attacks with the intent of executing code in non-executable regions of memory or in memory locations that are prohibited. Security safeguards employed to protect memory include, for example, data execution prevention and address space layout randomization. Data execution prevention safeguards can be either hardware-enforced or software-enforced with hardware providing the greater strength of mechanism.\n\nPoisoning writes an arbitrary value to freed pages, so any modification or reference to that page after being freed or before being initialized will be detected and prevented. This prevents many types of use-after-free vulnerabilities at little performance cost. Also prevents leak of data and detection of corrupted memory.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068, SRG-OS-000433-GPOS-00192",
          "check_content": "Verify that GRUB 2 is configured to enable page poisoning to mitigate use-after-free vulnerabilities with the following commands:\n\nCheck that the current GRUB 2 configuration has page poisoning enabled:\n\n$ sudo grub2-editenv list | grep page_poison\n\nkernelopts=root=/dev/mapper/rhel-root ro crashkernel=auto resume=/dev/mapper/rhel-swap rd.lvm.lv=rhel/root rd.lvm.lv=rhel/swap rhgb quiet fips=1 page_poison=1 vsyscall=none audit=1 audit_backlog_limit=8192 boot=UUID=8d171156-cd61-421c-ba41-1c021ac29e82\n\nIf \"page_poison\" is not set to \"1\" or is missing, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that page poisoning is enabled by default to persist in kernel updates:\n\n$ sudo grep page_poison /etc/default/grub\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"page_poison=1\"\n\nIf \"page_poison\" is not set to \"1\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230277"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001084"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230277",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'page_poison' setting does not exist in 'grub2-editenv'\nThe 'page_poison' setting does not exist in '/etc/default/grub'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrub2-editenv list | grep kernelopts\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep page_poison /etc/default/grub\n\nChecking 'page_poison' in 'grub2-editenv':\n\u274c The 'page_poison' setting does not exist\n\nChecking 'page_poison' in '/etc/default/grub':\n\u274c The 'page_poison' setting does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6ae31ad4-8e53-4aa6-a5ce-a2984bcba98e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230367",
          "group_id_src": "V-230367",
          "rule_id": "SV-230367r1038967",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230367r1038967_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020210",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 user account passwords must be configured so that existing passwords are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.",
          "fix_text": "Configure non-compliant accounts to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.\n\n$ sudo chage -M 60 [user]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 user account passwords must be configured so that existing passwords are restricted to a 60-day maximum lifetime.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked. Therefore, passwords need to be changed periodically. If RHEL 8 does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that RHEL 8 passwords could be compromised.",
          "check_content": "Check whether the maximum time period for existing passwords is restricted to 60 days with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 > 60 {print $1 \" \" $5}' /etc/shadow\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '$5 <= 0 {print $1 \" \" $5}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf any results are returned that are not associated with a system account, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230367"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000199"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230367",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000076-GPOS-00044",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following interactive users have a maximum password lifetime greater than 60 days or is not restricted at all:\nroot\ndeckerr",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\n# Get the list of interactive user accounts\nuser_list=$(awk -F: '{if ($NF != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" && $NF != \"/usr/bin/false\" && $NF != \"/sbin/nologin\" && $NF != \"/sbin/halt\" && $NF != \"/bin/sync\" && $NF != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && $NF != \"/bin/false\" && $NF != \"/bin/true\" && $NF != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\") print $1}' /etc/passwd)\n\n# Loop through each interactive user account\nfor user in $user_list; do\n    # Get the maximum password age in days for the user\n    max_age=$(grep -w \"$user\" /etc/shadow | cut -d: -f5)\n    \n    # List users and their maxpasswordage\n    echo \"USERNAME:$user \\t MAXPASSWORDAGE:$max_age\"\ndone\n\nChecking maximum password lifetime for interactive users:\n\u274c USERNAME:root \\t MAXPASSWORDAGE:99999\n\u274c USERNAME:deckerr \\t MAXPASSWORDAGE:99999\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6b0289a1-ca2e-42c5-a667-5334cb7af75d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230408",
          "group_id_src": "V-230408",
          "rule_id": "SV-230408r1017214",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230408r1017214_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030170",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/group.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/group\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/group -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/group.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, CCI-002884, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/group\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/group /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/group -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230408"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230408",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/group' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/group' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/group /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/group\n\nChecking for '/etc/group' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/group' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/group' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/group' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6c5ebb34-4edc-4f8c-afaa-d69c428173cb",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230466",
          "group_id_src": "V-230466",
          "rule_id": "SV-230466r1017258",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230466r1017258_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030590",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful modifications to the faillock log file in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"faillock\" file by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful modifications to the faillock log file in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nThe list of audited events is the set of events for which audits are to be generated. This set of events is typically a subset of the list of all events for which the system is capable of generating audit records.\n\nDoD has defined the list of events for which RHEL 8 will provide an audit record generation capability as the following:\n\n1) Successful and unsuccessful attempts to access, modify, or delete privileges, security objects, security levels, or categories of information (e.g., classification levels);\n\n2) Access actions, such as successful and unsuccessful logon attempts, privileged activities or other system-level access, starting and ending time for user access to the system, concurrent logons from different workstations, successful and unsuccessful accesses to objects, all program initiations, and all direct access to the information system;\n\n3) All account creations, modifications, disabling, and terminations; and\n\n4) All kernel module load, unload, and restart actions.\n\nFrom \"Pam_Faillock man\" pages: Note the default directory that pam_faillock uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"faillock\" file occur. First, determine where the faillock tallies are stored with the following commands:\n\nFor RHEL versions 8.0 and 8.1:\n\n$ sudo grep -i pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth     required          pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent deny=3 fail_interval=900 even_deny_root\n\nFor RHEL versions 8.2 and newer:\n\n$ sudo grep dir /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\ndir=/var/log/faillock\n\nUsing the location of the faillock log file, check that the following calls are being audited by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w faillock /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /var/log/faillock -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230466"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230466",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'pam_faillock.so' module with the 'dir' option does not exist on a 'preauth' line in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth | grep -v \"^#\" |grep \"dir=\" |awk -F'dir=' '{print $2}' | cut -d\" \" -f1\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth | grep -v \"^#\" |grep \"dir=\" |awk -F'dir=' '{print $2}' |cut -d\" \" -f1 |xargs -I dir grep -w dir /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth | grep -v \"^#\" |grep \"dir=\" |awk -F'dir=' '{print $2}' |cut -d\" \" -f1 |xargs -I dir sh -c 'auditctl -l | grep -w dir' \necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep \"dir=\\|dir =\" /etc/security/faillock.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d\"=\" -f2\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep \"dir=\\|dir =\" /etc/security/faillock.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d\"=\" -f2 |xargs -I dir grep -w dir /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep \"dir=\\|dir =\" /etc/security/faillock.conf | grep -v \"^#\" | cut -d\"=\" -f2 |xargs -I dir sh -c 'auditctl -l | grep -w dir'\n\nChecking the RHEL version:\n\ud83d\udd0d RHEL version is '8.10'\n\nDetermining the audit record directory:\n\u274c The 'pam_faillock.so' module with the 'dir' option does not exist on a 'preauth' line\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6c8f1d92-5584-42f5-9747-7164189a0bdd",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230517",
          "group_id_src": "V-230517",
          "rule_id": "SV-230517r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230517r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040129",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log/audit with the nodev option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/log/audit is mounted with the \"nodev\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit /var/log/audit xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log/audit with the nodev option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/log/audit\" is mounted with the \"nodev\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/log/audit\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit on /var/log/audit type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"nodev\" option is configured for /var/log/audit:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log/audit\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log-audit /var/log/audit xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"nodev\" option is missing, or if /var/log/audit is mounted without the \"nodev\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230517"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230517",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/log/audit' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/log/audit' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /var/log/audit\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log/audit\n\nChecking if '/var/log/audit' is mounted with 'nodev' option:\n\u274c '/var/log/audit' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'nodev' is configured for '/var/log/audit':\n\u274c '/var/log/audit' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6c90a8da-9746-4f2b-94f1-7f7e8d5d796e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230336",
          "group_id_src": "V-230336",
          "rule_id": "SV-230336r1017148",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230336r1017148_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020014",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to lock an account until released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur in 15 minutes.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" files to match the following lines:\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nRHEL 8 can utilize the \"pam_faillock.so\" for this purpose. Note that manual changes to the listed files may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.\n\nFrom \"Pam_Faillock\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Check that the system locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes until released by an administrator with the following commands:\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved centralized account management method that locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nNote: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.0 and 8.1, if the system is RHEL version 8.2 or newer, this check is not applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" option is not set to \"0\" on the \"preauth\" and \"authfail\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" option is not set to \"0\" on the \"preauth\" and \"authfail\" lines with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, or is missing from these lines, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230336"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230336",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The RHEL version is '8.10', per DISA this check is 'Not Applicable'\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep -w preauth\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep -w authfail\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w authfail\n\nChecking the RHEL version:\n\ud83d\udd36 RHEL version is '8.10'\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6ce8f089-05c6-47fe-8efa-1d13185e5902",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230370",
          "group_id_src": "V-230370",
          "rule_id": "SV-230370r1017182",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230370r1017182_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020231",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 passwords for new users must have a minimum of 15 characters.",
          "fix_text": "Configure operating system to enforce a minimum 15-character password length for new user accounts.\n\nAdd, or modify the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file:\n\nPASS_MIN_LEN 15",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 passwords for new users must have a minimum of 15 characters.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. Use of more characters in a password helps to increase exponentially the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.\n\nThe DoD minimum password requirement is 15 characters.",
          "check_content": "Verify that RHEL 8 enforces a minimum 15-character password length for new user accounts by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i  pass_min_len /etc/login.defs\n\nPASS_MIN_LEN 15\n\nIf the \"PASS_MIN_LEN\" parameter value is less than \"15\", or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230370"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000205"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230370",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000078-GPOS-00046",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'PASS_MIN_LEN' setting is '5' in '/etc/login.defs', should be \u2265 15",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i pass_min_len /etc/login.defs\n\nChecking the value for 'PASS_MIN_LEN':\n\u274c #\tPASS_MIN_LEN\tMinimum acceptable password length.\n\u274c PASS_MIN_LEN\t5\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6d19c8e5-94fe-4bc8-a9cc-240876a17895",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244524",
          "group_id_src": "V-244524",
          "rule_id": "SV-244524r1017330",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244524r1017330_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010159",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 pam_unix.so module must be configured in the system-auth file to use a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to use a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.\n\nEdit/modify the following line in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file to include the sha512 option for pam_unix.so:\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 pam_unix.so module must be configured in the system-auth file to use a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm for system authentication.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified and therefore cannot be relied upon to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DoD data may be compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 systems utilizing encryption are required to use FIPS-compliant mechanisms for authenticating to cryptographic modules.\n\nFIPS 140-2 is the current standard for validating that mechanisms used to access cryptographic modules utilize authentication that meets DoD requirements. This allows for Security Levels 1, 2, 3, or 4 for use on a general-purpose computing system.",
          "check_content": "Verify that pam_unix.so module is configured to use sha512.\n\nCheck that pam_unix.so module is configured to use sha512 in /etc/pam.d/system-auth with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep password /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep pam_unix\n\npassword sufficient pam_unix.so sha512\n\nIf \"sha512\" is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244524"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000803"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244524",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The pam_unix.so module is configured to use 'sha512' in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth' file. \npassword    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep password /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep pam_unix\n\nChecking that the pam_unix.so module is configured to use 'sha512' in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth' file:\n\u2705 The pam_unix.so module is configured to use 'sha512' in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth' file. \npassword    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6d52b91a-df14-4921-b310-18c85c0a31b2",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230377",
          "group_id_src": "V-230377",
          "rule_id": "SV-230377r1017188",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230377r1017188_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020300",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.\n\nAdd or update the following line in the \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" file or a configuration file in the /etc/pwquality.conf.d/ directory to contain the \"dictcheck\" parameter:\n\ndictcheck=1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent the use of dictionary words for passwords.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If RHEL 8 allows the user to select passwords based on dictionary words, this increases the chances of password compromise by increasing the opportunity for successful guesses, and brute-force attacks.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 prevents the use of dictionary words for passwords.\n\nDetermine if the field \"dictcheck\" is set with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r dictcheck /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:dictcheck=1\n\nIf the \"dictcheck\" parameter is not set to \"1\", or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230377"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230377",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00225",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'dictcheck' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*dictcheck' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'dictcheck':\n\u274c The 'dictcheck' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6d73918f-25aa-4e33-9e6f-663986ac41e9",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230485",
          "group_id_src": "V-230485",
          "rule_id": "SV-230485r1017269",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230485r1017269_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030741",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server by adding or modifying the following line in the \"/etc/chrony.conf\" file:\n\nport 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the chrony daemon from acting as a server.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nMinimizing the exposure of the server functionality of the chrony daemon diminishes the attack surface.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes the \"timedatectl\" command to view the status of the \"systemd-timesyncd.service\". The \"timedatectl\" status will display the local time, UTC, and the offset from UTC.\n\nNote that USNO offers authenticated NTP service to DOD and U.S. Government agencies operating on the NIPR and SIPR networks. Visit https://www.usno.navy.mil/USNO/time/ntp/DOD-customers for more information.",
          "check_content": "Note: If the system is approved and documented by the information system security officer (ISSO) to function as an NTP time server, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 8 disables the chrony daemon from acting as a server with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w 'port' /etc/chrony.conf\nport 0\n\nIf the \"port\" option is not set to \"0\", is commented out or missing, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230485"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230485",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'port' option does not exist in '/etc/chrony.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w 'port' /etc/chrony.conf\n\nChecking 'port' value in '/etc/chrony.conf':\n\u274c The 'port' option does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6ebb57c1-126e-4e67-a276-5daaf0e20253",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230247",
          "group_id_src": "V-230247",
          "rule_id": "SV-230247r1017065",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230247r1017065_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010230",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 /var/log/messages file must be group-owned by root.",
          "fix_text": "Change the group of the file \"/var/log/messages\" to \"root\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chgrp root /var/log/messages",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 /var/log/messages file must be group-owned by root.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 8 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.",
          "check_content": "Verify the \"/var/log/messages\" file is group-owned by root with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%G\" /var/log/messages\n\nroot\n\nIf \"root\" is not returned as a result, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230247"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001314"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230247",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The '/var/log/messages' file is group-owned by 'root'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nstat -c \"%G\" /var/log/messages\n\nChecking if '/var/log/messages' is group-owned by 'root':\n\u2705 GROUP: root\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "6fa707e8-b594-4165-bdb7-27367318aa93",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230292",
          "group_id_src": "V-230292",
          "rule_id": "SV-230292r1017103",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230292r1017103_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010540",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must use a separate file system for /var.",
          "fix_text": "Migrate the \"/var\" path onto a separate file system.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must use a separate file system for /var.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The use of separate file systems for different paths can protect the system from failures resulting from a file system becoming full or failing.",
          "check_content": "Verify that a separate file system has been created for \"/var\".\n\nCheck that a file system has been created for \"/var\" with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep /var /etc/fstab\n\n     /dev/mapper/...   /var   xfs   defaults,nodev 0 0\n\nIf a separate entry for \"/var\" is not in use, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230292"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230292",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No entry for '/var' was found in '/etc/fstab'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /var /etc/fstab 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking that a separate file system has been created for '/var':\n\u274c No entry for '/var' was found in '/etc/fstab'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7051678f-5b05-4dce-8887-687d8ce149e7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230376",
          "group_id_src": "V-230376",
          "rule_id": "SV-230376r1069307",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230376r1069307_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020290",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prohibit the use of cached authentications after one day.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the SSSD to prohibit the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nAdd or change the following line in \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" just below the line \"[pam]\".\n\n     offline_credentials_expiration = 1",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prohibit the use of cached authentications after one day.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If cached authentication information is out-of-date, the validity of the authentication information may be questionable.\n\nRHEL 8 includes multiple options for configuring authentication, but this requirement will be focus on the System Security Services Daemon (SSSD). By default sssd does not cache credentials.",
          "check_content": "Note: If smart card authentication is not being used on the system this item is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify that the SSSD prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day.\n\nCheck that SSSD allows cached authentications with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep cache_credentials /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\n/etc/sssd/sssd.conf:cache_credentials = true\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"false\" or missing from the configuration file, this is not a finding, and no further checks are required.\n\nIf \"cache_credentials\" is set to \"true\", check that SSSD prohibits the use of cached authentications after one day with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep offline_credentials_expiration  /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\n/etc/sssd/sssd.conf:offline_credentials_expiration = 1\n\nIf \"offline_credentials_expiration\" is not set to a value of \"1\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230376"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002007"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230376",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000383-GPOS-00166",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Smart card authentication is not enabled \u2014 control is not applicable.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nif grep -iq 'pam_cert_auth *= *true' /etc/sssd/sssd.conf 2>/dev/null; then\n    echo \"ENABLED\"\nelse\n    echo \"NOT ENABLED or NOT CONFIGURED\"\nfi\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iH cache_credentials /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iH offline_credentials_expiration /etc/sssd/sssd.conf\n\nChecking if smart card authentication is being used:\n\ud83d\udd36 smart card authentication is not enabled, per DISA this check is not applicable\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "70dd23d5-a353-400e-bbd7-882adc6ea11a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244531",
          "group_id_src": "V-244531",
          "rule_id": "SV-244531r1017338",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244531r1017338_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010731",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directory files must have mode 0750 or less permissive.",
          "fix_text": "Set the mode on files and directories in the local interactive user home directory with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and is a member of the users group.\n\n$ sudo chmod 0750 /home/smithj/<file or directory>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directory files must have mode 0750 or less permissive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Excessive permissions on local interactive user home directories may allow unauthorized access to user files by other users.",
          "check_content": "Verify all files and directories contained in a local interactive user home directory, excluding local initialization files, have a mode of \"0750\".\nFiles that begin with a \".\" are excluded from this requirement.\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n$ sudo ls -lLR /home/smithj\n-rwxr-x--- 1 smithj smithj 18 Mar 5 17:06 file1\n-rwxr----- 1 smithj smithj 193 Mar 5 17:06 file2\n-rw-r-x--- 1 smithj smithj 231 Mar 5 17:06 file3\n\nIf any files or directories are found with a mode more permissive than \"0750\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
