          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chsh' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/bin/chsh\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chsh' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'chsh' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7da0f590-9bbd-4948-b145-13cc673bc17f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230248",
          "group_id_src": "V-230248",
          "rule_id": "SV-230248r1069291",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230248r1069291_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010240",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 /var/log directory must have mode 0755 or less permissive.",
          "fix_text": "Change the permissions of the directory \"/var/log\" to \"0755\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0755 /var/log",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 /var/log directory must have mode 0755 or less permissive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 8 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the \"/var/log\" directory has a mode of \"0755\" or less with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /var/log\n\n755 /var/log\n\nIf a value of \"0755\" or less permissive is not returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230248"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001314"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230248",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The mode of '755' for '/var/log' is '755' or less permissive.\n755 /var/log",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nstat -c \"%a %n\" /var/log\n\nChecking the mode of '/var/log':\n\u2705 755 /var/log\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7e08a6ae-618d-43f9-bf11-3f4cac91d7ec",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-268322",
          "group_id_src": "V-268322",
          "rule_id": "SV-268322r1017568",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-268322r1017568_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020331",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow blank or null passwords in the system-auth file.",
          "fix_text": "Remove any instances of the \"nullok\" option in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nNote: Manual changes to the listed file may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow blank or null passwords in the system-auth file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.",
          "check_content": "To verify that null passwords cannot be used, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nIf output is produced, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-268322"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-268322",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'nullok' option was found on '2' lines in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i nullok /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -v \"^#\"\n\nChecking that null systems cannont be used:\n\u274c auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\n\u274c password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7eb27cc1-d2df-4514-a035-380bbbfe454d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230272",
          "group_id_src": "V-230272",
          "rule_id": "SV-230272r1101898",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230272r1101898_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010381",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must require users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.",
          "fix_text": "Remove any occurrence of \"!authenticate\" found in \"/etc/sudoers\" file or files in the \"/etc/sudoers.d\" directory.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must require users to reauthenticate for privilege escalation.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without reauthentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization.\n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the user reauthenticate.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00157, SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00158",
          "check_content": "Verify that \"/etc/sudoers\" has no occurrences of \"!authenticate\".\n\nCheck that the \"/etc/sudoers\" file has no occurrences of \"!authenticate\" by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo egrep -iR '!authenticate' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/\n\nIf any occurrences of \"!authenticate\" return from the command, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230272"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002038",
            "CCI-004895"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230272",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No occurences of '!authenticate' were found in '/etc/sudoers' or in a file in '/etc/sudoers.d'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\negrep -iRH '!authenticate' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/ | grep -v \"^#\" 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for no occurences of '!authenticate' in '/etc/sudoers':\n\u2705 No occurences of '!authenticate' were found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7ef43364-a7ed-44d7-8a0f-ad7bc9401161",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230303",
          "group_id_src": "V-230303",
          "rule_id": "SV-230303r1017113",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230303r1017113_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010600",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent special devices on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nodev\" option on file systems that are associated with removable media.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent special devices on file systems that are used with removable media.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"nodev\" mount option causes the system not to interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify file systems that are used for removable media are mounted with the \"nodev\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=2bc871e4-e2a3-4f29-9ece-3be60c835222 /mnt/usbflash vfat noauto,owner,ro,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 0\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to removable media and it does not have the \"nodev\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230303"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230303",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No removable media found",
          "finding_details": "#fstab_file=\"/etc/fstab\"\nremovable_media_found=false\n\nwhile read -r line; do\n    line=$(echo \"$line\" | sed -e 's/^[[:space:]]*//' -e 's/[[:space:]]*$//')\n    if [[ -n \"$line\" && ! \"$line\" =~ ^# ]]; then\n        fields=($line)\n        mount_point=${fields[1]}\n\n        # Check if the mount point is a removable media\n        transport=$(lsblk --output TRAN -n \"$mount_point\" 2>/dev/null)\n        if [[ -n \"$transport\" && \"$transport\" != \"loop\" ]]; then\n            echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n            echo \"Removable media found: $mount_point\"\n            echo \"$line\"\n            removable_media_found=true\n        fi\n    fi\ndone < \"$fstab_file\"\n\nif [[ \"$removable_media_found\" == false ]]; then\n    echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n    echo \"No removable media found\"\nfi\n\nChecking for 'nodev' option mounted removable media:\n\u2705 No removable media found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7f0561ac-4da7-4fea-89e7-e074d426c6d3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230467",
          "group_id_src": "V-230467",
          "rule_id": "SV-230467r1017259",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230467r1017259_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030600",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful modifications to the lastlog file in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"lastlog\" file by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful modifications to the lastlog file in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without the capability to generate audit records, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nThe list of audited events is the set of events for which audits are to be generated. This set of events is typically a subset of the list of all events for which the system is capable of generating audit records.\n\nDoD has defined the list of events for which RHEL 8 will provide an audit record generation capability as the following:\n\n1) Successful and unsuccessful attempts to access, modify, or delete privileges, security objects, security levels, or categories of information (e.g., classification levels);\n\n2) Access actions, such as successful and unsuccessful logon attempts, privileged activities or other system-level access, starting and ending time for user access to the system, concurrent logons from different workstations, successful and unsuccessful accesses to objects, all program initiations, and all direct access to the information system;\n\n3) All account creations, modifications, disabling, and terminations; and\n\n4) All kernel module load, unload, and restart actions.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000473-GPOS-00218",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the \"lastlog\" file by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w lastlog /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230467"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230467",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for the successful/unsuccessful modifications to the 'lastlog' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"/var/log/lastlog\"\n\nChecking if the generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful modifications to the 'lastlog' file:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for the successful/unsuccessful modifications to the 'lastlog' file.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7fc70c18-9c67-4e81-8e90-b0016fda4a66",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244551",
          "group_id_src": "V-244551",
          "rule_id": "SV-244551r1017351",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244551r1017351_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040239",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not forward IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not accept IPv4 source-routed packets.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244551"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244551",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route' is set to '0' in the return from the 'sysctl' command.\nThe following config files were found with the 'net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route' set to '0':\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route' variable:\n\u2705 net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route' variable:\n\u2705 /usr/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf:net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\u2705 /lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf:net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "7ffc41cf-3d67-4285-abc5-c753aae18850",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-237640",
          "group_id_src": "V-237640",
          "rule_id": "SV-237640r1017323",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-237640r1017323_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010163",
          "rule_title": "The krb5-server package must not be installed on RHEL 8.",
          "fix_text": "Document the krb5-server package with the ISSO as an operational requirement or remove it from the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum remove krb5-server",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The krb5-server package must not be installed on RHEL 8.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified and therefore cannot be relied upon to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DoD data may be compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 systems utilizing encryption are required to use FIPS-compliant mechanisms for authenticating to cryptographic modules.\n\nCurrently, Kerberos does not utilize FIPS 140-2 cryptography.\n\nFIPS 140-2 is the current standard for validating that mechanisms used to access cryptographic modules utilize authentication that meets DoD requirements. This allows for Security Levels 1, 2, 3, or 4 for use on a general-purpose computing system.",
          "check_content": "Verify the krb5-server package has not been installed on the system with the following commands:\n\nIf the system is a workstation or is utilizing krb5-server-1.17-18.el8.x86_64 or newer, this is Not Applicable\n\n$ sudo yum list installed krb5-server\n\nkrb5-server.x86_64 1.17-9.el8 repository\n\nIf the krb5-server package is installed and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-237640"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000803"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-237640",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'krb5-server' is not installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed | grep krb5-server\n\nChecking if 'krb5-server'' is installed:\n\u274c 'krb5-server' is not installed.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8101212a-5843-43e9-8815-36c1399675c7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230393",
          "group_id_src": "V-230393",
          "rule_id": "SV-230393r1017200",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230393r1017200_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030061",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must audit local events.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to audit local events on the system.\n\nAdd or update the following line in \"/etc/audit/auditd.conf\" file:\n\nlocal_events = yes",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 audit system must audit local events.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 Audit Daemon is configured to include local events, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep local_events /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlocal_events = yes\n\nIf the value of the \"local_events\" option is not set to \"yes\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230393"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230393",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'local_events' setting is set to 'yes' in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep local_events /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking the 'local_events' setting in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf:\n\u2705 local_events = yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8111f625-41e5-4ddf-91ba-393507969dfb",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230484",
          "group_id_src": "V-230484",
          "rule_id": "SV-230484r1038944",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230484r1038944_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030740",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with a server synchronized to an authoritative time source, such as the United States Naval Observatory (USNO) time servers, or a time server designated for the appropriate DoD network (NIPRNet/SIPRNet), and/or the Global Positioning System (GPS).",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an NTP server by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/chrony.conf file.\n\nserver [ntp.server.name] iburst maxpoll 16",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must securely compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with a server synchronized to an authoritative time source, such as the United States Naval Observatory (USNO) time servers, or a time server designated for the appropriate DoD network (NIPRNet/SIPRNet), and/or the Global Positioning System (GPS).",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nSynchronizing internal information system clocks provides uniformity of time stamps for information systems with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.\n\nOrganizations should consider endpoints that may not have regular access to the authoritative time server (e.g., mobile, teleworking, and tactical endpoints).\n\nIf time stamps are not consistently applied and there is no common time reference, it is difficult to perform forensic analysis.\n\nTime stamps generated by the operating system include date and time. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes the \"timedatectl\" command to view the status of the \"systemd-timesyncd.service\". The \"timedatectl\" status will display the local time, UTC, and the offset from UTC.\n\nNote that USNO offers authenticated NTP service to DoD and U.S. Government agencies operating on the NIPR and SIPR networks. Visit https://www.usno.navy.mil/USNO/time/ntp/dod-customers for more information.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143, SRG-OS-000356-GPOS-00144, SRG-OS-000359-GPOS-00146",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 is securely comparing internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an NTP server with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo grep maxpoll /etc/chrony.conf\n\nserver 0.us.pool.ntp.mil iburst maxpoll 16\n\nIf the \"maxpoll\" option is set to a number greater than 16 or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the \"chrony.conf\" file is configured to an authoritative DoD time source by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i server /etc/chrony.conf\nserver 0.us.pool.ntp.mil\n\nIf the parameter \"server\" is not set or is not set to an authoritative DoD time source, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230484"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004923",
            "CCI-001891"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230484",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000355-GPOS-00143",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All 'server' directives are commented out in '/etc/chrony.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i server /etc/chrony.conf\n\nChecking the 'server' directive for 'maxpoll' option in '/etc/chrony.conf':\n\u274c # Use public servers from the pool.ntp.org project.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "82282b19-d4b5-429c-9ff0-e72fff9d7ba2",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230341",
          "group_id_src": "V-230341",
          "rule_id": "SV-230341r1017153",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230341r1017153_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020019",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent system messages from being presented when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to prevent informative messages from being presented at logon attempts.\n\nAdd/Modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\nsilent",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent system messages from being presented when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Note: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.2 or newer, if the system is RHEL version 8.0 or 8.1, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to prevent informative messages from being presented at logon attempts:\n\n$ sudo grep silent /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nsilent\n\nIf the \"silent\" option is not set, is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230341"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230341",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'silent' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -E '^[[:space:]]*silent' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nChecking the version of RHEL:\n\ud83d\udd0d The RHEL version is '8.10'. \nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file is configured to prevent informative messages from being presented at logon attempts:\n\u274c The 'silent' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "83debf56-a292-427d-9fb2-a7948d4a2654",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230278",
          "group_id_src": "V-230278",
          "rule_id": "SV-230278r1017091",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230278r1017091_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010422",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable virtual syscalls.",
          "fix_text": "Document the use of vsyscalls with the ISSO as an operational requirement or disable them with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=\"vsyscall=none\"\n\nAdd or modify the following line in \"/etc/default/grub\" to ensure the configuration survives kernel updates:\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"vsyscall=none\"",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable virtual syscalls.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Syscalls are special routines in the Linux kernel, which userspace applications ask to do privileged tasks.  Invoking a system call is an expensive operation because the processor must interrupt the currently executing task and switch context to kernel mode and then back to userspace after the system call completes.  Virtual Syscalls map into user space a page that contains some variables and the implementation of some system calls.  This allows the system calls to be executed in userspace to alleviate the context switching expense.\n\nVirtual Syscalls provide an opportunity of attack for a user who has control of the return instruction pointer.  Disabling vsyscalls help to prevent return oriented programming (ROP) attacks via buffer overflows and overruns. If the system intends to run containers based on RHEL 6 components, then virtual syscalls will need enabled so the components function properly.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068, SRG-OS-000433-GPOS-00192",
          "check_content": "Verify that GRUB 2 is configured to disable vsyscalls with the following commands:\n\nCheck that the current GRUB 2 configuration disables vsyscalls:\n\n$ sudo grub2-editenv list | grep vsyscall\n\nkernelopts=root=/dev/mapper/rhel-root ro crashkernel=auto resume=/dev/mapper/rhel-swap rd.lvm.lv=rhel/root rd.lvm.lv=rhel/swap rhgb quiet fips=1 page_poison=1 vsyscall=none audit=1 audit_backlog_limit=8192 boot=UUID=8d171156-cd61-421c-ba41-1c021ac29e82\n\nIf \"vsyscall\" is not set to \"none\" or is missing, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that vsyscalls are disabled by default to persist in kernel updates:\n\n$ sudo grep vsyscall /etc/default/grub\n\nGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"vsyscall=none\"\n\nIf \"vsyscall\" is not set to \"none\", is missing or commented out and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230278"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001084"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230278",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000134-GPOS-00068",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'vsyscall' setting does not exist in 'grub2-editenv'\nThe 'vsyscall' setting does not exist in '/etc/default/grub'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrub2-editenv list | grep kernelopts\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep vsyscall /etc/default/grub\n\nChecking 'vsyscall' in 'grub2-editenv':\n\u274c The 'vsyscall' setting does not exist\n\nChecking 'vsyscall' in '/etc/default/grub':\n\u274c The 'vsyscall' setting does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "84461a28-e186-41e7-bea1-1c72e778988c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230404",
          "group_id_src": "V-230404",
          "rule_id": "SV-230404r1017210",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230404r1017210_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030130",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/shadow.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/shadow\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/shadow.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/shadow\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/shadow /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230404"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230404",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/shadow' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/shadow' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/shadow /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/shadow\n\nChecking for '/etc/shadow' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/shadow' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/shadow' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/shadow' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "84927081-a558-4edb-9f4f-e9b61da0a267",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230253",
          "group_id_src": "V-230253",
          "rule_id": "SV-230253r1044799",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230253r1044799_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010292",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must ensure the SSH server uses strong entropy.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system SSH server to use strong entropy.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in the \"/etc/sysconfig/sshd\" file.\n\nSSH_USE_STRONG_RNG=32\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect.\n\nRestart the SSH Daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must ensure the SSH server uses strong entropy.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The most important characteristic of a random number generator is its randomness, namely its ability to deliver random numbers that are impossible to predict. Entropy in computer security is associated with the unpredictability of a source of randomness. The random source with high entropy tends to achieve a uniform distribution of random values. Random number generators are one of the most important building blocks of cryptosystems.\n\nThe SSH implementation in RHEL 8 uses the OPENSSL library, which does not use high-entropy sources by default. By using the SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG environment variable the OPENSSL random generator is reseeded from /dev/random. This setting is not recommended on computers without the hardware random generator because insufficient entropy causes the connection to be blocked until enough entropy is available.",
          "check_content": "Note: If the operating system is RHEL versions 8.0 or 8.1, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system SSH server uses strong entropy with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i ssh_use_strong_rng /etc/sysconfig/sshd\n\nSSH_USE_STRONG_RNG=32\n\nIf the \"SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG\" line does not equal \"32\", is commented out, or is missing, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230253"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230253",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG' parameter is set to '0' in '/etc/sysconfig/sshd', but should be set to '32'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -i ssh_use_strong_rng /etc/sysconfig/sshd\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\ud83d\udd0d Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking the 'SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG' parameter:\n\u274c SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG=0\n\u274c # SSH_USE_STRONG_RNG=1\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "84d350ea-7b11-49cc-bf4f-d06757faf691",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230310",
          "group_id_src": "V-230310",
          "rule_id": "SV-230310r1155383",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230310r1155383_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010670",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable kernel dumps unless needed.",
          "fix_text": "If kernel core dumps are not required, disable the \"kdump\" service with the following command:\n\n# systemctl disable kdump.service\n\nIf kernel core dumps are required, document the need with the ISSO.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable kernel dumps unless needed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Kernel core dumps may contain the full contents of system memory at the time of the crash. Kernel core dumps may consume a considerable amount of disk space and may result in denial of service by exhausting the available space on the target file system partition.\n\nRHEL 8 installation media presents the option to enable or disable the kdump service at the time of system installation.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 kernel core dumps are disabled unless needed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl status kdump.service\n\no kdump.service - Crash recovery kernel arming\n   Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/kdump.service; disabled; vendor preset: enabled)\n   Active: inactive (dead)\n\nIf the \"kdump\" service is active, ask the system administrator if the use of the service is required and documented with the information system security officer (ISSO).\n\nIf the service is active and is not documented, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230310"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230310",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'kdump.service' is not 'active'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsystemctl --no-pager status kdump.service\n\nChecking if kernel core dumps are disabled:\n\u2705 The 'kdump.service' is not 'active'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "85288366-7cfb-48a9-b562-994db94312d7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230374",
          "group_id_src": "V-230374",
          "rule_id": "SV-230374r1069293",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230374r1069293_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020270",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to expire temporary accounts after 72 hours with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo chage -E $(date -d +3days +%Y-%m-%d) <temporary_account_name>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically expire temporary accounts within 72 hours.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Temporary accounts are privileged or nonprivileged accounts that are established during pressing circumstances, such as new software or hardware configuration or an incident response, where the need for prompt account activation requires bypassing normal account authorization procedures. If any inactive temporary accounts are left enabled on the system and are not either manually removed or automatically expired within 72 hours, the security posture of the system will be degraded and exposed to exploitation by unauthorized users or insider threat actors.\n\nTemporary accounts are different from emergency accounts. Emergency accounts, also known as \"last resort\" or \"break glass\" accounts, are local logon accounts enabled on the system for emergency use by authorized system administrators to manage a system when standard logon methods are failing or not available. Emergency accounts are not subject to manual removal or scheduled expiration requirements.\n\nThe automatic expiration of temporary accounts may be extended as needed by the circumstances but it must not be extended indefinitely. A documented permanent account should be established for privileged users who need long-term maintenance accounts.",
          "check_content": "Note: If temporary accounts do not exist or are not used this is not applicable.\n\nVerify temporary accounts have been provisioned with an expiration date of 72 hours.\n\nFor every existing temporary account, run the following command to obtain its account expiration information:\n\n     $ sudo chage -l <temporary_account_name> | grep -i \"account expires\"\n\nVerify each of these accounts has an expiration date set within 72 hours.\nIf any temporary accounts have no expiration date set or do not expire within 72 hours, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230374"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001682"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230374",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000123-GPOS-00064",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "User: deckerr, Account Expires: Never",
          "finding_details": "## Get the list of users excluding those with certain shells or root\nusers=$(grep -v \"/sbin/nologin\\|/sbin/halt\\|/bin/sync\\|/sbin/shutdown\\|/bin/false\\|/bin/true\\|/usr/sbin/nologin\\|root\" /etc/passwd | cut -d: -f1)\n\n# Iterate through the users and display the account expiration information\nfor user in $users; do\n    # Print delimiter before each user, including before the first one\n    echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n\n    # Display the username and account expiration info\n    echo \"Username: $user\"\n    chage -l \"$user\" | grep -i \"account expires\"\ndone\n\n\ud83d\udd36***Review the list of users below for Temporary Accounts***\ud83d\udd36\n\nList of interactive users and account expiration date (based on scan date of Mar 28, 2026 at 04:09):\nUser: deckerr Account Expires: Never\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "86c00c57-f2b5-4f54-bafc-1787c61636b3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230412",
          "group_id_src": "V-230412",
          "rule_id": "SV-230412r1017218",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230412r1017218_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030190",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the su command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"su\" command occur by adding or updating the following rule in \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the su command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"su\" command allows a user to run commands with a substitute user and group ID.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-0003, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"su\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w /usr/bin/su /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-priv_change\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230412"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230412",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/usr/bin/su' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/usr/bin/su' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w /usr/bin/su /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w /usr/bin/su\n\nChecking for '/usr/bin/su' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/su' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/usr/bin/su' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/su' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8827e04c-a4cd-425e-925b-b70bcf293a8b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230536",
          "group_id_src": "V-230536",
          "rule_id": "SV-230536r1017298",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230536r1017298_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040220",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not allow interfaces to perform IPv4 ICMP redirects.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not send Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirects.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages contain information from the system's route table, possibly revealing portions of the network topology.\n\nThere are notable differences between Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6). There is only a directive to disable sending of IPv4 redirected packets. Refer to RFC4294 for an explanation of \"IPv6 Node Requirements\", which resulted in this difference between IPv4 and IPv6.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the \"all send_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230536"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230536",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' variable:\n\u274c net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "886a2653-51dd-44f3-ac82-1b2fde631fc7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230503",
          "group_id_src": "V-230503",
          "rule_id": "SV-230503r1069316",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230503r1069316_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040080",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to disable USB mass storage.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the USB Storage kernel module and the ability to use USB mass storage devices.\n\nAdd or update the following lines in the file \"/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\":\n\n     install usb-storage /bin/false\n     blacklist usb-storage\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to disable USB mass storage.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "USB mass storage permits easy introduction of unknown devices, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059, SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the USB Storage kernel module and ensure that the USB Storage kernel module is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"blacklist\"\n\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:install usb-storage /bin/false\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:blacklist usb-storage\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of USB Storage is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230503"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000778"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230503",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000114-GPOS-00059",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'install usb-storage kernel module /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\nThe 'usb-storage kernel module blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"install\" 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep usb-storage /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep -i \"blacklist\" 2>/dev/null\n\n\nChecking if usb-storage kernel module is disabled:\n\u274c The 'install usb-storage kernel module /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\n\nChecking if the usb-storage kernel module blacklist entry exists:\n\u274c The 'usb-storage kernel module blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "89741fcc-31db-4c88-a996-2e71afbe9f1b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230494",
          "group_id_src": "V-230494",
          "rule_id": "SV-230494r1069310",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230494r1069310_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040021",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) protocol.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the ATM protocol kernel module.\n\nAdd or update the following lines in the file \"/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\":\n\n     install atm /bin/false\n     blacklist atm\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the asynchronous transfer mode (ATM) protocol.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nFailing to disconnect unused protocols can result in a system compromise.\n\nThe Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) is a protocol operating on network, data link, and physical layers, based on virtual circuits and virtual paths. Disabling ATM protects the system against exploitation of any laws in its implementation.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the ATM protocol kernel module and ensure that the ATM protocol kernel module is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r atm /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\"\n\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:install atm /bin/false\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:blacklist atm\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of the ATM protocol is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230494"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230494",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'install ATM protocol /bin/false' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\nThe 'ATM protocol blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r atm /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"install\" 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r atm /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\" 2>/dev/null\n\n\nChecking if ATM protocol is disabled:\n\u274c The 'install ATM protocol /bin/false' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\n\nChecking if the ATM protocol blacklist entry exists:\n\u274c The 'ATM protocol blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8984be01-ffcb-48af-8ace-8ce6868a5977",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230358",
          "group_id_src": "V-230358",
          "rule_id": "SV-230358r1017170",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230358r1017170_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020120",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lower-case character be used.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lower-case character be used by setting the \"lcredit\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to /etc/security/pwquality.conf (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\nlcredit = -1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lower-case character be used.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes pwquality as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. Note that in order to require lower-case characters without degrading the \"minlen\" value, the credit value must be expressed as a negative number in \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\".",
          "check_content": "Verify the value for \"lcredit\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r lcredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:lcredit = -1\n\nIf the value of \"lcredit\" is a positive number or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230358"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000193",
            "CCI-004066"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230358",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000070-GPOS-00038",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'lcredit' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*lcredit' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'lcredit':\n\u274c The 'lcredit' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8997299d-0255-4942-89b3-559872eab920",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230228",
          "group_id_src": "V-230228",
          "rule_id": "SV-230228r1069299",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230228r1069299_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010070",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 remote access methods must be monitored.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to monitor all remote access methods by installing rsyslog with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install rsyslog\n\nThen add or update the following lines to the \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" file:\n\nauth.*;authpriv.*;daemon.* /var/log/secure\n\nThe \"rsyslog\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"rsyslog\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 remote access methods must be monitored.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Remote access services, such as those providing remote access to network devices and information systems, which lack automated monitoring capabilities, increase risk and make remote user access management difficult at best.\n\nRemote access is access to DOD nonpublic information systems by an authorized user (or an information system) communicating through an external, nonorganization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nAutomated monitoring of remote access sessions allows organizations to detect cyber attacks and ensure ongoing compliance with remote access policies by auditing connection activities of remote access capabilities, such as Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP), on a variety of information system components (e.g., servers, workstations, notebook computers, smartphones, and tablets).",
          "check_content": "Verify that RHEL 8 monitors all remote access methods.\n\nCheck that remote access methods are being logged by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -E '(auth\\.\\*|authpriv\\.\\*|daemon\\.\\*)' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf     auth.*;authpriv.*;daemon.* /var/log/secure\n\nIf \"auth.*\", \"authpriv.*\" or \"daemon.*\" are not configured to be logged, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230228"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000067"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230228",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000032-GPOS-00013",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'auth.*' is cofigured to be logged in 'grep'\n'authpriv.*' is cofigured to be logged in 'grep'\n'daemon.*' is cofigured to be logged in 'grep'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -H 'auth\\.\\*' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf | grep -v '^#' 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -H 'authpriv\\.\\*' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf | grep -v '^#' 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -H 'daemon\\.\\*' /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf | grep -v '^#' 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if 'auth.*' is configured to be logged:\n\u2705 grep: /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf: No such file or directory\n\nChecking if 'authpriv.*' is configured to be logged:\n\u2705 grep: /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf: No such file or directory\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:authpriv.*                                              /var/log/secure\n\nChecking if 'daemon.*' is configured to be logged:\n\u2705 grep: /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf: No such file or directory\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8bdc9a86-1e29-4188-bc08-2b2eeb50164e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230515",
          "group_id_src": "V-230515",
          "rule_id": "SV-230515r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230515r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040127",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log with the nosuid option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/log is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log /var/log xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log with the nosuid option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/log\" is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/log\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log on /var/log type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"nosuid\" option is configured for /var/log:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log /var/log xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"nosuid\" option is missing, or if /var/log is mounted without the \"nosuid\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230515"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230515",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/log' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/log' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /var/log\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log\n\nChecking if '/var/log' is mounted with 'nosuid' option:\n\u274c '/var/log' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'nosuid' is configured for '/var/log':\n\u274c '/var/log' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8cc72d6b-a5ef-4a3b-938c-e48cd60a7006",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244533",
          "group_id_src": "V-244533",
          "rule_id": "SV-244533r1069318",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244533r1069318_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020025",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to include the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file to match the following lines:\nNote: The \"preauth\" line must be listed before pam_unix.so.\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail\naccount required pam_faillock.so",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must configure the use of the pam_faillock.so module in the /etc/pam.d/system-auth file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module. Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\nThe preauth argument must be used when the module is called before the modules which ask for the user credentials such as the password.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Verify the pam_faillock.so module is present and is listed before the pam.unix.so line in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file:\nNote: The first field in the output is the line number of the entry\n\n$ sudo grep -E -n 'pam_faillock.so|pam_unix.so' /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\n7:auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent\n13:auth sufficient pam_unix.so\n17:auth required pam_faillock.so authfail\n21:account required pam_faillock.so\n22:account required pam_unix.so\n33:password sufficient pam_unix.so sha512 shadow use_authtok\n42:session required pam_unix.so\n\nIf the pam_faillock.so module is not present in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file with the \"preauth\" line listed before pam_unix.so, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244533"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244533",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "pam_faillock.so with 'preauth' was not found in /etc/pam.d/system-auth.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -E -n 'pam_faillock.so|pam_unix.so' /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\u2705 Rocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking if pam_faillock.so module is present and is listed before the pam.unix.so line:\n5:auth        sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass nullok\n8:account     required      pam_unix.so\n11:password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n18:session     required      pam_unix.so\n\u274c pam_faillock.so with 'preauth' not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8e16e44e-19e2-4495-98a8-580cf33ecc04",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230547",
          "group_id_src": "V-230547",
          "rule_id": "SV-230547r1017309",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230547r1017309_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040283",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict exposed kernel pointer addresses access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to restrict exposed kernel pointer addresses access by adding the following line to a file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d\" directory:\n\nkernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must restrict exposed kernel pointer addresses access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 restricts exposed kernel pointer addresses access with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl kernel.kptr_restrict\n\nkernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"1\" or \"2\", or a line is not returned, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r kernel.kptr_restrict /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: kernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\nIf \"kernel.kptr_restrict\" is not set to \"1\" or \"2\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230547"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230547",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'kernel.kptr_restrict' is set to '1' or '2' in the return from the 'sysctl' command.\nThe following config files were found with the 'kernel.kptr_restrict' set to '1' or '2':\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.kptr_restrict 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*kernel.kptr_restrict' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'kernel.kptr_restrict' variable:\n\u2705 kernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'kernel.kptr_restrict' variable:\n\u2705 /usr/lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf:kernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\u2705 /lib/sysctl.d/50-default.conf:kernel.kptr_restrict = 1\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8e9288c2-289b-4d26-a869-f9ea1b9cc8dd",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230493",
          "group_id_src": "V-230493",
          "rule_id": "SV-230493r1017276",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230493r1017276_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040020",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must cover or disable the built-in or attached camera when not in use.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the built-in or attached camera when not in use.\n\nBuild or modify the \"/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\" file by using the following example:\n\n     install uvcvideo /bin/false\n     blacklist uvcvideo\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must cover or disable the built-in or attached camera when not in use.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nFailing to disconnect from collaborative computing devices (i.e., cameras) can result in subsequent compromises of organizational information. Providing easy methods to physically disconnect from such devices after a collaborative computing session helps to ensure participants actually carry out the disconnect activity without having to go through complex and tedious procedures.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049, SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155",
          "check_content": "If the device or operating system does not have a camera installed, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nThis requirement is not applicable to mobile devices (smartphones and tablets), where the use of the camera is a local AO decision.\n\nThis requirement is not applicable to dedicated VTC suites located in approved VTC locations that are centrally managed.\n\nFor an external camera, if there is not a method for the operator to manually disconnect the camera at the end of collaborative computing sessions, this is a finding.\n\nFor a built-in camera, the camera must be protected by a camera cover (e.g., laptop camera cover slide) when not in use. If the built-in camera is not protected with a camera cover, or is not physically disabled, this is a finding.\n\nIf the camera is not disconnected, covered, or physically disabled, determine if it is being disabled via software with the following commands:\n\nVerify the operating system disables the ability to load the uvcvideo kernel module.\n\n     $ sudo grep -r uvcvideo /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"/bin/false\"\n     install uvcvideo /bin/false\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and the collaborative computing device has not been authorized for use, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the camera is disabled via blacklist with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep -r uvcvideo /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\"\n     blacklist uvcvideo\n\nIf the command does not return any output or the output is not \"blacklist uvcvideo\", and the collaborative computing device has not been authorized for use, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230493"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230493",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No cameras were discovered, per DISA this check is 'Not Appplicable'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nls /dev/video*\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r uvcvideo /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"install\" 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r uvcvideo /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\" 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if any cameras are installed:\n\ud83d\udd36 No cameras were discovered\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8e9a709b-7faa-4ad5-a6b8-f24e513c476a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230387",
          "group_id_src": "V-230387",
          "rule_id": "SV-230387r1017195",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230387r1017195_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030010",
          "rule_title": "Cron logging must be implemented in RHEL 8.",
          "fix_text": "Configure \"rsyslog\" to log all cron messages by adding or updating the following line to \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or a configuration file in the /etc/rsyslog.d/ directory:\n\ncron.* /var/log/cron\n\nThe rsyslog daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect:\n$ sudo systemctl restart rsyslog.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Cron logging must be implemented in RHEL 8.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Cron logging can be used to trace the successful or unsuccessful execution of cron jobs. It can also be used to spot intrusions into the use of the cron facility by unauthorized and malicious users.",
          "check_content": "Verify that \"rsyslog\" is configured to log cron events with the following command:\n\nNote: If another logging package is used, substitute the utility configuration file for \"/etc/rsyslog.conf\" or \"/etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\" files.\n\n$ sudo grep -s cron /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                          /var/log/messages\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:# Log cron stuff\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.*                                                                                                    /var/log/cron\n\nIf the command does not return a response, check for cron logging all facilities with the following command.\n\n$ sudo grep -s /var/log/messages /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                          /var/log/messages\n\nIf \"rsyslog\" is not logging messages for the cron facility or all facilities, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230387"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230387",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Found line: /etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.*                                                  /var/log/cron",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -sH cron /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -sH /var/log/messages /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.d/*.conf\n\nChecking if rsyslog is configured to log cron events:\n\u274c /etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                /var/log/messages\n\u274c /etc/rsyslog.conf:# Log cron stuff\n\u2705 /etc/rsyslog.conf:cron.*                                                  /var/log/cron\n\nChecking if rsyslog is logging messages for all facilities:\n\u274c /etc/rsyslog.conf:*.info;mail.none;authpriv.none;cron.none                /var/log/messages\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8f480898-ee9a-4128-87cf-da2a178130ec",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230530",
          "group_id_src": "V-230530",
          "rule_id": "SV-230530r1069317",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230530r1069317_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040171",
          "rule_title": "The x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence in RHEL 8 must be disabled if a graphical user interface is installed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence when using a graphical user interface by creating or editing the /etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-disable-CAD file.\n\nAdd the setting to disable the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence for a graphical user interface:\n\n[org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys]\nlogout=''\n\nNote: The value above is set to two single quotations.\n\nThen update the dconf settings:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The x86 Ctrl-Alt-Delete key sequence in RHEL 8 must be disabled if a graphical user interface is installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A locally logged-on user, who presses Ctrl-Alt-Delete, when at the console, can reboot the system. If accidentally pressed, as could happen in the case of a mixed OS environment, this can create the risk of short-term loss of availability of systems due to unintentional reboot. In a graphical user environment, risk of unintentional reboot from the Ctrl-Alt-Delete sequence is reduced because the user will be prompted before any action is taken.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 is not configured to reboot the system when Ctrl-Alt-Delete is pressed when using a graphical user interface with the following command:\n\nThis requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep -r logout /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\n/etc/dconf/db/local.d/00-disable-CAD:logout=''\n\nIf the \"logout\" key is bound to an action, is commented out, or is missing, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230530"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230530",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No files were found in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d' with the 'logout' key.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -r logout /etc/dconf/db/local.d/*\n\nChecking if a GUI is installed:\n\u274c No files were found in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d' with the 'logout' key.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "8f868cd3-8f86-4482-8aa4-0abee9bb3e70",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-251713",
          "group_id_src": "V-251713",
          "rule_id": "SV-251713r1017366",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-251713r1017366_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020101",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to use \"pwquality\" to enforce password complexity rules.\n\nAdd the following line to the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" file (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\n     password requisite pam_pwquality.so",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must ensure the password complexity module is enabled in the system-auth file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \"pwquality\" enforces complex password construction configuration and has the ability to limit brute-force attacks on the system.\n\nRHEL 8 uses \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. This is set in both:\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth\n/etc/pam.d/system-auth",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system uses \"pwquality\" to enforce the password complexity rules.\n\nCheck for the use of \"pwquality\" in the system-auth file with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo cat /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep pam_pwquality\n\n     password requisite pam_pwquality.so\n\nIf the command does not return a line containing the value \"pam_pwquality.so\" as shown, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-251713"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-251713",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'pam_pwquality.so' line is set to 'password requisite pam_pwquality.so' in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep 'pam_pwquality.so' /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nChecking for the use of 'pwquality' in the '/etc/pam.d/system-auth' file:\n\u2705 password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "915ef23d-ad87-4c70-a6d4-802d49d0fd88",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230527",
          "group_id_src": "V-230527",
          "rule_id": "SV-230527r1017288",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230527r1017288_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040161",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system to force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server by add or modifying the following line in the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file:\n\nRekeyLimit 1G 1h\n\nRestart the SSH daemon for the settings to take effect.\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must force a frequent session key renegotiation for SSH connections to the server.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered.\n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification.\n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSession key regeneration limits the chances of a session key becoming compromised.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014, SRG-OS-000420-GPOS-00186, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH server is configured to force frequent session key renegotiation with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*rekeylimit'\n\nRekeyLimit 1G 1h\n\nIf \"RekeyLimit\" does not have a maximum data amount and maximum time defined, is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230527"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000068"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230527",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Rekey limit not set as required.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\n\u274c Found rekey limit set to 0 0\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "918f88c3-4544-49b1-8dac-8f19ba0227d8",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230411",
          "group_id_src": "V-230411",
          "rule_id": "SV-230411r1017217",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230411r1017217_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030180",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 audit package must be installed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit service to produce audit records containing the information needed to establish when (date and time) an event occurred.\n\nInstall the audit service (if the audit service is not already installed) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install audit",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 audit package must be installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nAssociating event types with detected events in RHEL 8 audit logs provides a means of investigating an attack, recognizing resource utilization or capacity thresholds, or identifying an improperly configured RHEL 8 system.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000038-GPOS-00016, SRG-OS-000039-GPOS-00017, SRG-OS-000040-GPOS-00018, SRG-OS-000041-GPOS-00019, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00021, SRG-OS-000051-GPOS-00024, SRG-OS-000054-GPOS-00025, SRG-OS-000122-GPOS-00063, SRG-OS-000254-GPOS-00095, SRG-OS-000255-GPOS-00096, SRG-OS-000337-GPOS-00129, SRG-OS-000348-GPOS-00136, SRG-OS-000349-GPOS-00137, SRG-OS-000350-GPOS-00138, SRG-OS-000351-GPOS-00139, SRG-OS-000352-GPOS-00140, SRG-OS-000353-GPOS-00141, SRG-OS-000354-GPOS-00142, SRG-OS-000358-GPOS-00145, SRG-OS-000365-GPOS-00152, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000475-GPOS-00220",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit service is configured to produce audit records.\n\nCheck that the audit service is installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed audit\n\nIf the \"audit\" package is not installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230411"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230411",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
