          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'audit' package (audit.x86_64                      3.1.2-1.el8_10.1                       @baseos) is installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed audit\n\nChecking if the 'audit' package is installed:\n\u2705 The 'audit' package ('audit.x86_64                      3.1.2-1.el8_10.1                       @baseos') is installed.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "91c338f7-8c8d-4c33-a193-a5865ca00002",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230314",
          "group_id_src": "V-230314",
          "rule_id": "SV-230314r1134881",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230314r1134881_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010674",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable storing core dumps.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable storing core dumps for all users.\n\nAdd or modify the following line in /etc/systemd/coredump.conf:\n\nStorage=none",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable storing core dumps.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nA core dump includes a memory image taken at the time the operating system terminates an application. The memory image could contain sensitive data and is generally useful only for developers trying to debug problems.",
          "check_content": "Note: If kernel dumps are disabled in accordance with RHEL-08-010671, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system disables storing core dumps for all users by issuing the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i storage /etc/systemd/coredump.conf\n\nStorage=none\n\nIf the \"Storage\" item is missing or commented out, or the value is anything other than \"none\", and the need for core dumps is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement for all domains that have the \"core\" item assigned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230314"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230314",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.core_pattern\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i storage /etc/systemd/coredump.conf\n\nChecking that the OS disables storing core dumps for all users:\n\ud83d\udd0d #Storage=external\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "920ed054-0167-49c7-ae48-2c8873577d7a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230325",
          "group_id_src": "V-230325",
          "rule_id": "SV-230325r1017136",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230325r1017136_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010770",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 local initialization files must have mode 0740 or less permissive.",
          "fix_text": "Set the mode of the local initialization files to \"0740\" with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the smithj user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     $ sudo chmod 0740 /home/smithj/.<INIT_FILE>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 local initialization files must have mode 0740 or less permissive.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Local initialization files are used to configure the user's shell environment upon logon. Malicious modification of these files could compromise accounts upon logon.",
          "check_content": "Verify that all local initialization files have a mode of \"0740\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the \"smithj\" user, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n     $ sudo ls -al /home/smithj/.[^.]* | more\n\n     -rw-------. 1 smithj users 2984 Apr 27 19:02 .bash_history\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users   18 Aug 21  2019 .bash_logout\n     -rw-r--r--. 1 smithj users  193 Aug 21  2019 .bash_profile\n\nIf any local initialization files have a mode more permissive than \"0740\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230325"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230325",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following local initialization files in the home directory ('/root') for 'root' have permissions more permissive than '0740':\n/root/.bash_logout\n/root/.bash_profile\n/root/.bashrc\n/root/.cshrc\n/root/.tcshrc\nThe following local initialization files in the home directory ('/home/deckerr') for 'deckerr' have permissions more permissive than '0740':\n/home/deckerr/.bash_logout\n/home/deckerr/.bash_profile\n/home/deckerr/.bashrc",
          "finding_details": "##!/usr/bin/env bash\nshopt -s nullglob\n\nwhile IFS=: read -r username _ uid gid _ homedir shell; do\n  case \"$shell\" in\n    /sbin/nologin|/usr/sbin/nologin|/bin/false|/bin/true) continue ;;\n  esac\n\n  echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n  echo \"#USERNAME:$username HOMEDIRECTORY:$homedir PRIMARYGROUPID:$gid\"\n\n  for init in \"$homedir\"/.[^.]*; do\n    [ -f \"$init\" ] || continue\n    stat -c \"%a:%n\" \"$init\"\n  done\n\ndone < /etc/passwd\nChecking local initialization files for 'root' (home: /root):\n\u2705 600:/root/.bash_history\n\u274c 644:/root/.bash_logout\n\u274c 644:/root/.bash_profile\n\u274c 644:/root/.bashrc\n\u274c 644:/root/.cshrc\n\u274c 644:/root/.tcshrc\n\u2705 600:/root/.viminfo\n\nChecking local initialization files for 'sync' (home: /sbin):\n\nChecking local initialization files for 'shutdown' (home: /sbin):\n\nChecking local initialization files for 'halt' (home: /sbin):\n\nChecking local initialization files for 'deckerr' (home: /home/deckerr):\n\u2705 600:/home/deckerr/.bash_history\n\u274c 644:/home/deckerr/.bash_logout\n\u274c 644:/home/deckerr/.bash_profile\n\u274c 644:/home/deckerr/.bashrc\n\u2705 600:/home/deckerr/.esd_auth\n\u2705 600:/home/deckerr/.ICEauthority\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "92ce202e-bedc-4c10-80bc-2f5a5063f16e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230522",
          "group_id_src": "V-230522",
          "rule_id": "SV-230522r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230522r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040134",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/tmp with the noexec option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/tmp is mounted with the \"noexec\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp /var/tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/tmp with the noexec option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/tmp\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp on /var/tmp type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"noexec\" option is configured for /var/tmp:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/tmp\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-tmp /var/tmp xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"noexec\" option is missing, or if /var/tmp is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230522"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230522",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nmount | grep /var/tmp\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep \"/var/tmp\" /etc/fstab\n\nChecking if '/var/tmp' is mounted with 'noexec' option:\n\u274c '/var/tmp' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'noexec' is configured for '/var/tmp':\n\u274c '/var/tmp' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "93ed843e-14e9-458a-afe3-28cf425a1413",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230372",
          "group_id_src": "V-230372",
          "rule_id": "SV-230372r1017184",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230372r1017184_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020250",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must implement smart card logon for multifactor authentication for access to interactive accounts.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to use multifactor authentication for local access to accounts.\n\nAdd or update the \"pam_cert_auth\" setting in the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\n     [pam]\n     pam_cert_auth = True\n\nAdd or update \"pam_sss.so\" with \"try_cert_auth\" or \"require_cert_auth\" in the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth\" files based on the following examples:\n\n     /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:auth   sufficient   pam_sss.so try_cert_auth\n\n     /etc/pam.d/system-auth:auth   [success=done authinfo_unavail=ignore ignore=ignore default=die]   pam_sss.so try_cert_auth\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n     $ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must implement smart card logon for multifactor authentication for access to interactive accounts.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Using an authentication device, such as a Common Access Card (CAC) or token that is separate from the information system, ensures that even if the information system is compromised, that compromise will not affect credentials stored on the authentication device.\n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from information systems gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification card and the DoD CAC.\n\nThere are various methods of implementing multifactor authentication for RHEL 8. Some methods include a local system multifactor account mapping or joining the system to a domain and utilizing a Red Hat idM server or Microsoft Windows Active Directory server. Any of these methods will require that the client operating system handle the multifactor authentication correctly.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052, SRG-OS-000106-GPOS-00053, SRG-OS-000107-GPOS-00054, SRG-OS-000108-GPOS-00055",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 uses multifactor authentication for local access to accounts.\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved alternate multifactor authentication method, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nCheck that the \"pam_cert_auth\" setting is set to \"true\" in the \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\" file.\n\nCheck that the \"try_cert_auth\" or \"require_cert_auth\" options are configured in both \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth\" files with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep -ir cert_auth /etc/sssd/sssd.conf /etc/sssd/conf.d/*.conf /etc/pam.d/*\n     /etc/sssd/sssd.conf:pam_cert_auth = True\n     /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:auth   sufficient   pam_sss.so try_cert_auth\n     /etc/pam.d/system-auth:auth   [success=done authinfo_unavail=ignore ignore=ignore default=die]   pam_sss.so try_cert_auth\n\nIf \"pam_cert_auth\" is not set to \"true\" in \"/etc/sssd/sssd.conf\", this is a finding.\n\nIf \"pam_sss.so\" is not set to \"try_cert_auth\" or \"require_cert_auth\" in both the \"/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" files, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230372"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000765"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230372",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000105-GPOS-00052",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'pam_cert_auth' setting was not found in '/etc/sssd/sssd.conf'The 'pam_sss.so' module was not found in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth'The 'pam_sss.so' module is not set to 'try_cert_auth' or 'require_cert_auth' in '/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_cert_auth /etc/sssd/sssd.conf 2>/dev/null | grep -Ev \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_sss.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth 2>/dev/null | grep -Ev \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_sss.so /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth  2>/dev/null | grep -Ev \"^[[:space:]]*#\"\n\nChecking the 'pam_cert_auth' setting in '/etc/sssd/sssd.conf':\n\u274c The 'pam_cert_auth' setting was not found\n\nChecking the 'pam_sss.so' module in '/etc/pam.d/system-auth':\n\u274c The 'pam_sss.so' module was not found\n\nChecking the 'pam_sss.so' module in '/etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth':\n\u274c auth sufficient pam_sss.so allow_missing_name\n\n\n\ud83d\udd36 ***If the System Administrator demonstrates the use\n   of an approved alternate multifactor authentication\n   method, per DISA this check is 'Not Applicable' ***\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "94a9fa8e-e1b4-4223-984b-2ff801fe447b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230489",
          "group_id_src": "V-230489",
          "rule_id": "SV-230489r1017273",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230489r1017273_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040002",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not have the sendmail package installed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable non-essential capabilities by removing the sendmail package from the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum remove sendmail",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not have the sendmail package installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nExamples of non-essential capabilities include, but are not limited to, games, software packages, tools, and demonstration software not related to requirements or providing a wide array of functionality not required for every mission, but which cannot be disabled.\n\nVerify the operating system is configured to disable non-essential capabilities. The most secure way of ensuring a non-essential capability is disabled is to not have the capability installed.",
          "check_content": "Check to see if the sendmail package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed sendmail\n\nIf the sendmail package is installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230489"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230489",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'sendmail' package is not installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed sendmail\n\nChecking if the 'sendmail' package is installed:\n\u2705 The 'sendmail' package is not installed.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "959e6999-e224-4975-a2f2-a740654565d9",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244550",
          "group_id_src": "V-244550",
          "rule_id": "SV-244550r1017350",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244550r1017350_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040209",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to prevent IPv4 ICMP redirect messages from being accepted.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent IPv4 Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) redirect messages from being accepted.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "ICMP redirect messages are used by routers to inform hosts that a more direct route exists for a particular destination. These messages modify the host's route table and are unauthenticated. An illicit ICMP redirect message could result in a man-in-the-middle attack.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 will not accept IPv4 ICMP redirect messages.\n\nCheck the value of the default \"accept_redirects\" variables with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244550"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244550",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' variable:\n\u274c net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9615fdc6-5048-429b-bd87-11d96666a59c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230396",
          "group_id_src": "V-230396",
          "rule_id": "SV-230396r1017202",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230396r1017202_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030070",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must have a mode of 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log to be protected from unauthorized read access by setting the correct permissive mode with the following command:\n\n$ sudo chmod 0600 /var/log/audit/audit.log",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must have a mode of 0600 or less permissive to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Only authorized personnel should be aware of errors and the details of the errors. Error messages are an indicator of an organization's operational state or can identify the RHEL 8 system or platform. Additionally, Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and operational information must not be revealed through error messages to unauthorized personnel or their designated representatives.\n\nThe structure and content of error messages must be carefully considered by the organization and development team. The extent to which the information system is able to identify and handle error conditions is guided by organizational policy and operational requirements.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029, SRG-OS-000206-GPOS-00084",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit logs have a mode of \"0600\" or less permissive.\n\nFirst, determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log file, check if the audit log has a mode of \"0600\" or less permissive with the following command:\n\n$ sudo stat -c \"%a %n\" /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\n600 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit log has a mode more permissive than \"0600\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230396"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230396",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The permissions for the audit log ('/var/log/audit/audit.log') are '600'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d= -f2 | xargs stat -c \"%a %n\"\n\nDetermining where audit logs are store:\n\ud83d\udd0d log_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nChecking the mode of '/var/log/audit/audit.log':\n\u2705 600 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "962cfede-5160-45ea-8013-2ed0a6f2e546",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-279930",
          "group_id_src": "V-279930",
          "rule_id": "SV-279930r1156343",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-279930r1156343_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010280",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 IP tunnels must use FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic algorithms.",
          "fix_text": "Configure Libreswan to use the system cryptographic policy.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/ipsec.conf\":\n\ninclude /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/libreswan.config",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 IP tunnels must use FIPS 140-3-approved cryptographic algorithms.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Overriding the system crypto policy makes the behavior of the Libreswan service violate expectations and makes system configuration more fragmented.",
          "check_content": "Note: If the ipsec service is not installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the IPsec service uses the system crypto policy with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep include /etc/ipsec.conf /etc/ipsec.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/ipsec.conf:include /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/libreswan.config\n/etc/ipsec.conf:include /etc/ipsec.d/*.conf\n\nIf the ipsec configuration file does not contain \"include /etc/crypto-policies/back-ends/libreswan.config\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-279930"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000068"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-279930",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000033-GPOS-00014",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Ipsec not installed",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndnf list --installed | grep libreswan || echo \"Ipsec package not installed\"\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -ir include /etc/ipsec* || echo \"Ipsec include statement not found\"\n\n\ud83d\udd36 Ipsec not installed\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "97463ac7-0794-47c3-9333-e2c626513f1b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230382",
          "group_id_src": "V-230382",
          "rule_id": "SV-230382r1069309",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230382r1069309_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020350",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must display the date and time of the last successful account logon upon an SSH logon.",
          "fix_text": "Configure SSH to provide users with feedback on when account accesses last occurred by setting the required configuration options in \"/etc/pam.d/sshd\" or in the \"sshd_config\" file used by the system (\"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" will be used in the example) (this file may be named differently or be in a different location if using a version of SSH that is provided by a third-party vendor).\n\nModify the \"PrintLastLog\" line in \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" to match the following:\n\nPrintLastLog yes\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to \"sshd_config\" to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must display the date and time of the last successful account logon upon an SSH logon.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Providing users with feedback on when account accesses via SSH last occurred facilitates user recognition and reporting of unauthorized account use.",
          "check_content": "Verify SSH provides users with feedback on when account accesses last occurred with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*printlastlog'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:PrintLastLog yes\n\nIf the \"PrintLastLog\" keyword is set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230382"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000052"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230382",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'PrintLastLog' keyword is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'PrintLastLog' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 printlastlog yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "97fceaf9-33a0-46cc-b4f3-1d4bda77a90b",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244530",
          "group_id_src": "V-244530",
          "rule_id": "SV-244530r1155403",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244530r1155403_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010572",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot/efi directory.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the /boot/efi directory.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot/efi directory.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Note: For vfat file systems and for systems that use BIOS, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the /boot/efi directory is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep '\\s/boot/efi\\s'\n\n/dev/sda1 on /boot/efi type vfat (rw,nosuid,relatime,fmask=0077,dmask=0077,codepage=437,iocharset=ascii,shortname=winnt,errors=remount-ro)\n\nIf the /boot/efi file system does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244530"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244530",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The system is using 'BIOS', per DISA this check is Not Applicable.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nls /sys/firmware/efi\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep '\\s/boot/efi\\s'\n\nChecking if the systems uses BIOS:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system is using 'BIOS', per DISA this check is Not Applicable.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "985a0aa2-56b9-4e86-9cd4-228468f0cb37",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230477",
          "group_id_src": "V-230477",
          "rule_id": "SV-230477r1017267",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230477r1017267_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030670",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must have the packages required for offloading audit logs installed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to offload audit logs by installing the required packages with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install rsyslog",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must have the packages required for offloading audit logs installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 8 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\".  \"rsyslogd\" is a system utility providing support for message logging.  Support for both internet and UNIX domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging.  Couple this utility with \"gnutls\" (which is a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols), and you have a method to securely encrypt and off-load auditing.\n\nRsyslog provides three ways to forward message: the traditional UDP transport, which is extremely lossy but standard; the plain TCP based transport, which loses messages only during certain situations but is widely available; and the RELP transport, which does not lose messages but is currently available only as part of the rsyslogd 3.15.0 and above.\nExamples of each configuration:\nUDP *.* @remotesystemname\nTCP *.* @@remotesystemname\nRELP *.* :omrelp:remotesystemname:2514\nNote that a port number was given as there is no standard port for RELP.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system has the packages required for offloading audit logs installed with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed rsyslog\n\nrsyslog.x86_64          8.1911.0-3.el8          @AppStream\n\nIf the \"rsyslog\" package is not installed, ask the administrator to indicate how audit logs are being offloaded and what packages are installed to support it.  If there is no evidence of audit logs being offloaded, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230477"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230477",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'rsyslog' is installed.\nrsyslog.x86_64                                     8.2102.0-15.el8_10.1                                        @appstream",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed | grep -w 'rsyslog'\n\nChecking if 'rsyslog'' is installed:\n\u2705 'rsyslog' is installed.\n   rsyslog.x86_64                                     8.2102.0-15.el8_10.1                                        @appstream\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "98607cf6-f8ae-427f-a8b0-d6840008f2d6",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230524",
          "group_id_src": "V-230524",
          "rule_id": "SV-230524r1155418",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230524r1155418_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040140",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must block unauthorized peripherals before establishing a connection.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enable the blocking of unauthorized peripherals with the following command:\nThis command must be run from a root shell and will create an allow list for any usb devices currently connect to the system.\n\n# usbguard generate-policy > /etc/usbguard/rules.conf\n\nNote: Enabling and starting usbguard without properly configuring it for an individual system will immediately prevent any access over a usb device such as a keyboard or mouse.\n\nRestart usbguard service after creation or update of rules with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart usbguard",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must block unauthorized peripherals before establishing a connection.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without authenticating devices, unidentified or unknown devices may be introduced, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nPeripherals include, but are not limited to, such devices as flash drives, external storage, and printers.\n\nA new feature that RHEL 8 provides is the USBGuard software framework. The USBguard-daemon is the main component of the USBGuard software framework. It runs as a service in the background and enforces the USB device authorization policy for all USB devices. The policy is defined by a set of rules using a rule language described in the usbguard-rules.conf file. The policy and the authorization state of USB devices can be modified during runtime using the usbguard tool.\n\nThe system administrator (SA) must work with the site information system security officer (ISSO) to determine a list of authorized peripherals and establish rules within the USBGuard software framework to allow only authorized devices.",
          "check_content": "Verify the USBGuard has a policy configured with the following command:\n\n$ sudo usbguard list-rules\n\nIf the command does not return results or an error is returned, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.\n\nIf the USBGuard package is not installed, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is a virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230524"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001958"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230524",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'usbguard' command was not found.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nusbguard list-rules\n\nChecking if 'USBGuard' has a policy configured:\n\u274c The 'usbguard' command was not found.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9949e5e5-df80-4dc6-a31b-f8444c9c64b4",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230384",
          "group_id_src": "V-230384",
          "rule_id": "SV-230384r1017193",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230384r1017193_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020352",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.",
          "fix_text": "Remove the umask statement from all local interactive user's initialization files.\n\nIf the account is for an application, the requirement for a umask less restrictive than \"077\" can be documented with the Information System Security Officer, but the user agreement for access to the account must specify that the local interactive user must log on to their account first and then switch the user to the application account with the correct option to gain the account's environment variables.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must set the umask value to 077 for all local interactive user accounts.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The umask controls the default access mode assigned to newly created files. A umask of 077 limits new files to mode 600 or less permissive. Although umask can be represented as a four-digit number, the first digit representing special access modes is typically ignored or required to be \"0\". This requirement applies to the globally configured system defaults and the local interactive user defaults for each account on the system.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the default umask for all local interactive users is \"077\".\n\nIdentify the locations of all local interactive user home directories by looking at the \"/etc/passwd\" file.\n\nCheck all local interactive user initialization files for interactive users with the following command:\n\nNote: The example is for a system that is configured to create users home directories in the \"/home\" directory.\n\n$ sudo grep -ir ^umask /home | grep -v '.bash_history'\n\nIf any local interactive user initialization files are found to have a umask statement that has a value less restrictive than \"077\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230384"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230384",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00228",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "deckerr: default umask 022 less restrictive than '077'.",
          "finding_details": "##!/usr/bin/env bash\nshopt -s nullglob\n\nsys_umask=$(awk 'BEGIN{IGNORECASE=1} /^[[:space:]]*UMASK[[:space:]]+/ {print $2; exit}' /etc/login.defs)\nif [[ -z $sys_umask ]]; then\n  for f in /etc/profile /etc/bashrc; do\n    [[ -f $f ]] || continue\n    sys_umask=$(grep -i '^[[:space:]]*umask' \"$f\" | awk '{print $2; exit}')\n    [[ -n $sys_umask ]] && break\n  done\nfi\nsys_umask=${sys_umask:-022}\n\nwhile IFS=: read -r username _ _ _ _ homedir shell; do\n  case \"$shell\" in\n    /sbin/nologin|/bin/sync|/sbin/shutdown|/sbin/halt|/usr/sbin/nologin|/bin/false|/bin/true) continue ;;\n  esac\n\n  echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n  echo \"#USERNAME:$username HOMEDIRECTORY:$homedir\"\n\n  found=0\n  for f in \"$homedir\"/.[^.]*; do\n    [[ -f $f ]] || continue\n    grep -H -i '^[[:space:]]*umask' \"$f\" 2>/dev/null \\\n      | grep -v '\\.bash_history' \\\n      | while IFS= read -r line; do\n          echo \"$line\"\n          found=1\n        done\n  done\n\n  if (( found == 0 )); then\n    echo \"DEFAULT UMASK: $sys_umask\"\n  fi\n\ndone < /etc/passwd\n \nChecking if the default 'umask' for all interactive users is '077':\nUser: deckerr :: Home Directory: /home/deckerr\n\u274c Default umask 022 less restrictive than '077'\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "995e7cff-2bd8-4154-a810-953cc025d325",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230476",
          "group_id_src": "V-230476",
          "rule_id": "SV-230476r958752",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230476r958752_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030660",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records, when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.",
          "fix_text": "Allocate enough storage capacity for at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nIf audit records are stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, resize the partition with sufficient space to contain one week of audit records.\n\nIf audit records are not stored on a partition made specifically for audit records, a new partition with sufficient space will need be to be created.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records, when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "To ensure RHEL 8 systems have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, RHEL 8 needs to be able to allocate audit record storage capacity.\n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of RHEL 8.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 allocates audit record storage capacity to store at least one week of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nDetermine to which partition the audit records are being written with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nCheck the size of the partition to which audit records are written (with the example being /var/log/audit/) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo df -h /var/log/audit/\n/dev/sda2 24G 10.4G 13.6G 43% /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit records are not written to a partition made specifically for audit records (/var/log/audit is a separate partition), determine the amount of space being used by other files in the partition with the following command:\n\n$ sudo du -sh [audit_partition]\n1.8G /var/log/audit\n\nIf the audit record partition is not allocated for sufficient storage capacity, this is a finding.\n\nNote: The partition size needed to capture a week of audit records is based on the activity level of the system and the total storage capacity available. Typically 10.0 GB of storage space for audit records should be sufficient.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230476"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001849"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230476",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000341-GPOS-00132",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d\"=\" -f2 | xargs -I file dirname file |xargs -I dir df -h dir\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d\"=\" -f2 | xargs -I file dirname file |xargs -I dir du -sh dir\n\nDetrmining the partition audit records are written to:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log File: /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\ud83d\udd0d Log File Directory: /var/log/audit\n\nChecking the size of the partition where audit records are written:\n\ud83d\udd0d Partition used for Audit Records: /\n\ud83d\udd0d Partition Size: 48G\n\ud83d\udd0d Partition Used Space: 6.5G\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9a8d4bed-5c50-4701-8e8c-a12eccced114",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-279933",
          "group_id_src": "V-279933",
          "rule_id": "SV-279933r1156352",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-279933r1156352_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010015",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must have the crypto-policies package installed.",
          "fix_text": "Install the crypto-policies package (if the package is not already installed) with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf -y install crypto-policies",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must have the crypto-policies package installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Centralized cryptographic policies simplify applying secure ciphers across an operating system and the applications that run on that operating system. Use of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of using encryption to protect data.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176, SRG-OS-000393-GPOS-00173, SRG-OS-000394-GPOS-00174",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 crypto-policies package is installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo dnf list --installed crypto-policies\n\nUpdating Subscription Management repositories.\nInstalled Packages\ncrypto-policies.noarch                     20230731-1.git3177e06.el8                      @rhel-8-for-x86_64-baseos-rpms\n\nIf the crypto-policies package is not installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-279933"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002450"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-279933",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000396-GPOS-00176",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The crypto-policies package is installed as required.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ndnf list --installed crypto-policies || echo 'crypto-policies package not installed'\n\n\u2705 crypto-policies package installed\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9af7f9c4-a2a9-4b1e-b6e5-77dd6d89b2ff",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230344",
          "group_id_src": "V-230344",
          "rule_id": "SV-230344r1017156",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230344r1017156_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020022",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must include root when automatically locking an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to include root when locking an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts occur in 15 minutes.\n\nAdd/Modify the appropriate sections of the \"/etc/pam.d/system-auth\" and \"/etc/pam.d/password-auth\" files to match the following lines:\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nThe \"sssd\" service must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the \"sssd\" service, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sssd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must include root when automatically locking an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nRHEL 8 can utilize the \"pam_faillock.so\" for this purpose. Note that manual changes to the listed files may be overwritten by the \"authselect\" program.\n\nFrom \"Pam_Faillock\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module. Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Check that the system includes the root account when locking an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes with the following commands:\n\nIf the system is RHEL version 8.2 or newer, this check is not applicable.\n\nNote: If the System Administrator demonstrates the use of an approved centralized account management method that locks an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts within a period of 15 minutes, this requirement is not applicable.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" option is missing from the \"preauth\" line with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, this is a finding.\n\n$ sudo grep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth\n\nauth required pam_faillock.so preauth dir=/var/log/faillock silent audit deny=3 even_deny_root fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0\nauth required pam_faillock.so authfail dir=/var/log/faillock unlock_time=0\naccount required pam_faillock.so\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" option is missing from the \"preauth\" line with the \"pam_faillock.so\" module, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230344"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230344",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The RHEL version is '8.10', per DISA this check is 'Not Applicable'\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/password-auth | grep -w preauth\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep pam_faillock.so /etc/pam.d/system-auth | grep -w preauth\n\nChecking the RHEL version:\n\ud83d\udd36 RHEL version is '8.10'\nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9b335b7a-7308-4099-a8f1-7bc96b0d9d56",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230363",
          "group_id_src": "V-230363",
          "rule_id": "SV-230363r1017175",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230363r1017175_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020170",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must require the change of at least 8 characters when passwords are changed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed by setting the \"difok\" option.\n\nAdd the following line to \"/etc/security/pwquality.conf\" (or modify the line to have the required value):\n\ndifok = 8\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above value.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must require the change of at least 8 characters when passwords are changed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determines how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes \"pwquality\" as a mechanism to enforce password complexity. The \"difok\" option sets the number of characters in a password that must not be present in the old password.",
          "check_content": "Verify the value of the \"difok\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r difok /etc/security/pwquality.conf*\n\n/etc/security/pwquality.conf:difok = 8\n\nIf the value of \"difok\" is set to less than \"8\" or is commented out, this is a finding.\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230363"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-004066",
            "CCI-000195"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230363",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000072-GPOS-00040",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'difok' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*difok' /etc/security/pwquality.conf* 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value for 'difok':\n\u274c The 'difok' setting does not exist in any 'pwquality.conf' file in '/etc/security'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9b552199-d659-4af6-a2d8-f76795f79cdc",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230398",
          "group_id_src": "V-230398",
          "rule_id": "SV-230398r1017204",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230398r1017204_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030090",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must be group-owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit log to be owned by root by configuring the log group in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file:\n\nlog_group = root",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit logs must be group-owned by root to prevent unauthorized read access.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit RHEL 8 activity.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit logs are group-owned by \"root\". First determine where the audit logs are stored with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nlog_file = /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nUsing the location of the audit log file, determine if the audit log is group-owned by \"root\" using the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -al /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nrw------- 2 root root 23 Jun 11 11:56 /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nIf the audit log is not group-owned by \"root\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230398"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230398",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The group owner of '/var/log/audit/audit.log' is 'root'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nstat -c \"%G\" /var/log/audit/audit.log 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -iw log_file /etc/audit/auditd.conf | cut -d= -f2 | xargs stat -c \"%G\" 2>/dev/null\n\nDetermining the audit log location:\n\ud83d\udd0d Log Location: /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nChecking the group owner of '/var/log/audit/audit.log':\n\u2705 Group Owner = root\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9c1b5d9d-d1c6-4447-a91e-92d1a311c5ee",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230409",
          "group_id_src": "V-230409",
          "rule_id": "SV-230409r1017215",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230409r1017215_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030171",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/sudoers.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/sudoers\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/sudoers.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, CCI-002884, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/sudoers\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/sudoers /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230409"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230409",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/sudoers' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/sudoers /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep /etc/sudoers\n\nChecking for '/etc/sudoers' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/sudoers' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "9c69cebf-78b2-4c26-941e-bcc0fa07de2e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230346",
          "group_id_src": "V-230346",
          "rule_id": "SV-230346r1069306",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230346r1069306_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020024",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must limit the number of concurrent sessions to ten for all accounts and/or account types.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to limit the number of concurrent sessions to \"10\" for all accounts and/or account types.\n\nAdd the following line to the top of the /etc/security/limits.conf or in a \".conf\" file defined in /etc/security/limits.d/:\n\n* hard maxlogins 10",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must limit the number of concurrent sessions to ten for all accounts and/or account types.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Operating system management includes the ability to control the number of users and user sessions that utilize an operating system. Limiting the number of allowed users and sessions per user is helpful in reducing the risks related to DoS attacks.\n\nThis requirement addresses concurrent sessions for information system accounts and does not address concurrent sessions by single users via multiple system accounts. The maximum number of concurrent sessions should be defined based on mission needs and the operational environment for each system.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system limits the number of concurrent sessions to \"10\" for all accounts and/or account types by issuing the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r -s '^[^#].*maxlogins' /etc/security/limits.conf /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/security/limits.d/maxlogins.conf:* hard maxlogins 10\n\nThis can be set as a global domain (with the * wildcard) but may be set differently for multiple domains.\n\nIf the \"maxlogins\" item is missing, commented out, or the value is set greater than \"10\" and is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement for all domains that have the \"maxlogins\" item assigned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230346"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000054"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230346",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000027-GPOS-00008",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No uncommented 'maxlogins' entries found in /etc/security/limits.conf or /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf. Expected: 'hard maxlogins 10'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -rH -s '^[^#].*maxlogins' /etc/security/limits.conf /etc/security/limits.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking that the OS limits the number of concurrent sessions to '10':\n\u274c No output\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a006703c-606e-4e08-9fc2-21abdd78a443",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244547",
          "group_id_src": "V-244547",
          "rule_id": "SV-244547r1014811",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244547r1014811_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040139",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must have the USBGuard installed.",
          "fix_text": "Install the USBGuard package with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install usbguard.x86_64",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must have the USBGuard installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without authenticating devices, unidentified or unknown devices may be introduced, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\nPeripherals include, but are not limited to, such devices as flash drives, external storage, and printers.\nA new feature that RHEL 8 provides is the USBGuard software framework. The USBguard-daemon is the main component of the USBGuard software framework. It runs as a service in the background and enforces the USB device authorization policy for all USB devices. The policy is defined by a set of rules using a rule language described in the usbguard-rules.conf file. The policy and the authorization state of USB devices can be modified during runtime using the usbguard tool.\n\nThe System Administrator (SA) must work with the site Information System Security Officer (ISSO) to determine a list of authorized peripherals and establish rules within the USBGuard software framework to allow only authorized devices.",
          "check_content": "Verify USBGuard is installed on the operating system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed usbguard\n\nInstalled Packages\nusbguard.x86_64                   0.7.8-7.el8             @ol8_appstream\n\nIf the USBGuard package is not installed, ask the SA to indicate how unauthorized peripherals are being blocked.\nIf there is no evidence that unauthorized peripherals are being blocked before establishing a connection, this is a finding.\n\nIf the system is a virtual machine with no virtual or physical USB peripherals attached, this is not a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244547"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001958"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244547",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000378-GPOS-00163",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'usbguard' package is not installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed usbguard\n\nChecking if the 'usbguard' package is installed:\n\u274c The 'usbguard' package is not installed.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a0f864a8-fba9-416d-b561-eec0e2799ff0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244538",
          "group_id_src": "V-244538",
          "rule_id": "SV-244538r1069324",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244538r1069324_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020081",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent non-privileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/session/idle-delay\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the session idle-delay setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.\n\nImplementing session settings will have little value if a user is able to manipulate these settings from the defaults prescribed in the other requirements of this implementation guide.\n\nLocking these settings from non-privileged users is crucial to maintaining a protected baseline.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010, SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\nsystem-db:local\n\nCheck that graphical settings are locked from non-privileged user modification with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n$ sudo grep -i idle /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/session/idle-delay\n\nIf the command does not return at least the example result, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244538"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000057"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244538",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-delay' was not found in any of the 'system-db' directories identified in '/etc/dconf/profile/user'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep gnome-shell\ngrep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user | cut -d: -f2 | xargs -I DIR sh -c 'echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; echo \"Directory: /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks\"; grep -iH idle-delay /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks/*' 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if the system has a GUI installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system has a GUI installed:\n   xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking if 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n   chrome-gnome-shell.x86_64                          42.1-1.el8                                                  @appstream\ngnome-shell.x86_64                                 3.32.2-58.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-apps-menu.noarch             3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-common.noarch                3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-desktop-icons.noarch         3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-horizontal-workspaces.noarch 3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-launch-new-instance.noarch   3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-places-menu.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-window-list.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n\nChecking the 'idle-delay' setting is protected for 'Gnome Shell':\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-delay' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/site.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-delay' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/distro.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/idle-delay' not found in any files\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a208c5ca-a64d-4c6e-9ebf-2cfa0a88eecf",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230345",
          "group_id_src": "V-230345",
          "rule_id": "SV-230345r1017157",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230345r1017157_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020023",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must include root when automatically locking an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to include root when locking an account after three unsuccessful logon attempts occur in 15 minutes.\n\nAdd/Modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\neven_deny_root",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must include root when automatically locking an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Note: This check applies to RHEL versions 8.2 or newer, if the system is RHEL version 8.0 or 8.1, this check is not applicable.\n\nVerify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur:\n\n$ sudo grep even_deny_root /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\neven_deny_root\n\nIf the \"even_deny_root\" option is not set, is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230345"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230345",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All 'even_deny_root' options in '/etc/security/faillock.conf' are commented out",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep even_deny_root /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nChecking the RHEL version:\n\ud83d\udd0d RHEL version is '8.10'\n\nChecking that '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file is configured to log user name information when unsuccessful logon attempts occur:\n\u274c # even_deny_root\n\u274c # This option implies the `even_deny_root` option.\n\u274c # the root account (the options `even_deny_root>` and\n\u274c All 'even_deny_root' options in '/etc/security/faillock.conf' are commented out\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a321b54a-e2b4-4036-b7ba-6ac898bfcac1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230231",
          "group_id_src": "V-230231",
          "rule_id": "SV-230231r1017050",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230231r1017050_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010110",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must encrypt all stored passwords with a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to encrypt all stored passwords.\n\nEdit/Modify the following line in the \"/etc/login.defs\" file and set \"[ENCRYPT_METHOD]\" to SHA512.\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must encrypt all stored passwords with a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised.\n\nUnapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified and therefore cannot be relied upon to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DoD data may be compromised.\n\nFIPS 140-2 is the current standard for validating that mechanisms used to access cryptographic modules utilize authentication that meets DoD requirements.",
          "check_content": "Verify that the shadow password suite configuration is set to encrypt password with a FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithm.\n\nCheck the hashing algorithm that is being used to hash passwords with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i crypt /etc/login.defs\n\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nIf \"ENCRYPT_METHOD\" does not equal SHA512 or greater, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230231"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000196",
            "CCI-004062"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230231",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'ENCRYPT_METHOD' line in the '/etc/login.defs' file is set to 'SHA512'.\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512",
          "finding_details": "#grep -Ei '^[[:space:]]*encrypt_method' /etc/login.defs\n\nChecking the hashing algorithm being used to hash passwords:\n\u2705 The 'ENCRYPT_METHOD' line in the '/etc/login.defs' file is set to 'SHA512'.\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a385ab84-6384-418d-aa7f-e343694f5c34",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230538",
          "group_id_src": "V-230538",
          "rule_id": "SV-230538r1017300",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230538r1017300_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040240",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv6 source-routed packets.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not accept IPv6 source-routed packets.\n\nNote: If IPv6 is disabled on the system, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\n\nnet.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230538"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230538",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route' setting.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl -a 2>/dev/null | grep 'net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6'\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if IPv6 is disabled on the system:\n\ud83d\udd0d IPv6 is not disabled\n\nChecking the 'net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route' setting using 'sysctl':\n\u2705 net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0\n\nChecking for the 'net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route' setting in configuration files:\n\u274c No configuration files were found with the 'net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_source_route' setting\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a42b1a3e-bd2d-4b79-973b-88db30598b39",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244546",
          "group_id_src": "V-244546",
          "rule_id": "SV-244546r1017349",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244546r1017349_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040137",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 fapolicy module must be configured to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception application whitelisting policy with \"fapolicyd\".\n\nWith the \"fapolicyd\" installed and enabled, configure the daemon to function in permissive mode until the whitelist is built correctly to avoid system lockout. Do this by editing the \"/etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.conf\" file with the following line:\n\npermissive = 1\n\nFor RHEL 8.4 systems and older:\nBuild the whitelist in the \"/etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.rules\" file ensuring the last rule is \"deny perm=any all : all\".\n\nFor RHEL 8.5 systems and newer:\nBuild the whitelist in a file within the \"/etc/fapolicyd/rules.d\" directory ensuring the last rule is \"deny perm=any all : all\".\n\nOnce it is determined the whitelist is built correctly, set the fapolicyd to enforcing mode by editing the \"permissive\" line in the /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.conf file.\n\npermissive = 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 fapolicy module must be configured to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nUtilizing a whitelist provides a configuration management method for allowing the execution of only authorized software. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities. Verification of whitelisted software occurs prior to execution or at system startup.\n\nUser home directories/folders may contain information of a sensitive nature. Non-privileged users should coordinate any sharing of information with an SA through shared resources.\n\nRHEL 8 ships with many optional packages. One such package is a file access policy daemon called \"fapolicyd\". \"fapolicyd\" is a userspace daemon that determines access rights to files based on attributes of the process and file. It can be used to either blacklist or whitelist processes or file access.\n\nProceed with caution with enforcing the use of this daemon. Improper configuration may render the system non-functional. The \"fapolicyd\" API is not namespace aware and can cause issues when launching or running containers.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154, SRG-OS-000370-GPOS-00155, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00232",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 \"fapolicyd\" employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy.\n\nCheck that \"fapolicyd\" is in enforcement mode with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep permissive /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.conf\n\npermissive = 0\n\nCheck that fapolicyd employs a deny-all policy on system mounts with the following commands:\n\nFor RHEL 8.4 systems and older:\n$ sudo tail /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.rules\n\nFor RHEL 8.5 systems and newer:\n$ sudo tail /etc/fapolicyd/compiled.rules\n\nallow exe=/usr/bin/python3.7 : ftype=text/x-python\ndeny_audit perm=any pattern=ld_so : all\ndeny perm=any all : all\n\nIf fapolicyd is not running in enforcement mode with a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244546"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244546",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The Red Hat version is '8.10'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep permissive /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.conf\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -v '^$' /etc/fapolicyd/fapolicyd.rules | tail -n 1\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -v '^$' /etc/fapolicyd/compiled.rules | tail -n 1\n\nChecking the version of Red Hat:\n\ud83d\udd0d The Red Hat version is '8.10'\n\nChecking 'fapolicyd' enforcement mode:\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a4326287-22fb-4645-a360-a17c89a156d2",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-251706",
          "group_id_src": "V-251706",
          "rule_id": "SV-251706r1017359",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-251706r1017359_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010121",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 operating system must not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords.",
          "fix_text": "Configure all accounts on the system to have a password or lock the account with the following commands:\n\nPerform a password reset:\n$ sudo passwd [username]\nLock an account:\n$ sudo passwd -l [username]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 operating system must not have accounts configured with blank or null passwords.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.",
          "check_content": "Check the \"/etc/shadow\" file for blank passwords with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '!$2 {print $1}' /etc/shadow\n\nIf the command returns any results, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-251706"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-251706",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No accounts were found with blank passwords in the '/etc/shadow' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nawk -F: '!$2 {print $1}' /etc/shadow\n\nChecking for accounts with blank passwords:\n\u2705 No accounts were found with blank passwords in the '/etc/shadow' file.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a4a36cd5-1390-4da7-8742-c7c72a1668d6",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244532",
          "group_id_src": "V-244532",
          "rule_id": "SV-244532r1101906",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244532r1101906_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010741",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories are group-owned by a group of which the home directory owner is a member.",
          "fix_text": "Change the group of a local interactive user's files and directories to a group that the interactive user is a member. To change the group owner of a local interactive user's files and directories, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user smithj, who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\" and is a member of the users group.\n\n$ sudo chgrp smithj /home/smithj/<file or directory>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured so that all files and directories contained in local interactive user home directories are group-owned by a group of which the home directory owner is a member.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If a local interactive user's files are group-owned by a group of which the user is not a member, unintended users may be able to access them.",
          "check_content": "Verify all files and directories in a local interactive user home directory are group-owned by a group that the user is a member.\n\nCheck the group owner of all files and directories in a local interactive user's home directory with the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\".\n\n$ sudo ls -lLR /<home directory>/<users home directory>/\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj  18 Mar  5 17:06 file1\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj smithj 193 Mar  5 17:06 file2\n-rw-r--r-- 1 smithj sa        231 Mar  5 17:06 file3\n\nIf any files are found with a group owner different from the home directory user private group, check to see if the user is a member of that group with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep smithj /etc/group\nsa:x:100:juan,shelley,bob,smithj\nsmithj:x:521:smithj\n\nIf any files or directories are group owned by a group that the directory owner is not a member of verify that it is documented with the information system security officer (ISSO). If it is not, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244532"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244532",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The user 'root' has the following files or directories in their home directory('/root') group-owned by a group they are not a member of:\n/root/rocky-execute.zip",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/passwd\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/group\n#!/bin/bash\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n        if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n                group_name=$(getent group $groupid | cut -d: -f1)\n                echo \"#USERNAME:$username HOMEDIRECTROY:$homedir PRIMARYGROUPID:$groupid PRIMARYGROUPNAME:$group_name\"\n\t\t\t\tfind $homedir ! -group $group_name -exec stat -c \"%G %g %n\" {} \\; 2>/dev/null\n        fi\ndone < $FILENAME\n\nChecking user's home directory for files or directories group-owned by a group the user is not a member of:\n***USER NAME: root***HOME DIR: /root***\n\u274c deckerr 1000 /root/rocky-execute.zip\n\n\n***USER NAME: deckerr***HOME DIR: /home/deckerr***\n\u2705 No files or directories found\n\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a4e5c836-c2c6-4cde-a1dc-b83c9a857d39",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230556",
          "group_id_src": "V-230556",
          "rule_id": "SV-230556r1017318",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230556r1017318_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040341",
          "rule_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the SSH daemon to prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.\n\nEdit the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment or add the line for the \"X11UseLocalhost\" keyword and set its value to \"yes\" (this file may be named differently or be in a different location if using a version of SSH that is provided by a third-party vendor):\n\nX11UseLocalhost yes",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "The RHEL 8 SSH daemon must prevent remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "When X11 forwarding is enabled, there may be additional exposure to the server and client displays if the sshd proxy display is configured to listen on the wildcard address.  By default, sshd binds the forwarding server to the loopback address and sets the hostname part of the DIPSLAY environment variable to localhost.  This prevents remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.",
          "check_content": "Verify the SSH daemon prevents remote hosts from connecting to the proxy display.\n\nCheck the SSH X11UseLocalhost setting with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*x11uselocalhost'\n\nX11UseLocalhost yes\n\nIf the \"X11UseLocalhost\" keyword is set to \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230556"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230556",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'X11UseLocalhost' keyword is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'X11UseLocalhost' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 x11uselocalhost yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a68efba6-7d89-4f97-8d65-71746622c104",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230432",
          "group_id_src": "V-230432",
          "rule_id": "SV-230432r1017233",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230432r1017233_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030316",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of setsebool in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"setsebool\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setsebool -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of setsebool in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise. The \"setsebool\" command sets the current state of a particular SELinux boolean or a list of booleans to a given value.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of \"setsebool\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"setsebool\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/setsebool -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230432"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230432",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setsebool' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"path=/usr/sbin/setsebool\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setsebool' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'setsebool' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a7002a37-3ccf-477d-834c-e619cb68b703",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-237643",
          "group_id_src": "V-237643",
          "rule_id": "SV-237643r1050789",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-237643r1050789_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010384",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must require re-authentication when using the \"sudo\" command.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"sudo\" command to require re-authentication.\nEdit the /etc/sudoers file:\n$ sudo visudo\n\nAdd or modify the following line:\nDefaults timestamp_timeout=[value]\nNote: The \"[value]\" must be a number that is greater than or equal to \"0\".\n\nRemove any duplicate or conflicting lines from /etc/sudoers and /etc/sudoers.d/ files.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must require re-authentication when using the \"sudo\" command.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without re-authentication, users may access resources or perform tasks for which they do not have authorization.\n\nWhen operating systems provide the capability to escalate a functional capability, it is critical the organization requires the user to re-authenticate when using the \"sudo\" command.\n\nIf the value is set to an integer less than 0, the user's time stamp will not expire and the user will not have to re-authenticate for privileged actions until the user's session is terminated.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system requires re-authentication when using the \"sudo\" command to elevate privileges.\n\n$ sudo grep -ir 'timestamp_timeout' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d\n/etc/sudoers:Defaults timestamp_timeout=0\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.\n\nIf \"timestamp_timeout\" is set to a negative number, is commented out, or no results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-237643"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002038",
            "CCI-004895"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-237643",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000373-GPOS-00156",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'timestamp_timeout' setting was not found in '/etc/sudoers' or any file in '/etc/sudoers.d'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -ir 'timestamp_timeout' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the 'timestamp_timeout' setting:\n\u274c The 'timestamp_timeout' setting was not found in '/etc/sudoers' or any file in '/etc/sudoers.d'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a725b174-f5cf-44e7-ac74-d98704f37efb",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230410",
          "group_id_src": "V-230410",
          "rule_id": "SV-230410r1017216",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230410r1017216_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030172",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/sudoers.d/.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/sudoers.d/\".\n\nAdd or update the following file system rule to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\":\n\n-w /etc/sudoers.d/ -p wa -k identity\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect /etc/sudoers.d/.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000004-GPOS-00004, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000470-GPOS-00214, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000239-GPOS-00089, SRG-OS-000240-GPOS-00090, SRG-OS-000241-GPOS-00091, SRG-OS-000303-GPOS-00120, SRG-OS-000304-GPOS-00121, CCI-002884, SRG-OS-000466-GPOS-00210, SRG-OS-000476-GPOS-00221",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events that affect \"/etc/sudoers.d/\".\n\nCheck the auditing rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep /etc/sudoers.d/ /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-w /etc/sudoers.d/ -p wa -k identity\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230410"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230410",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers.d/' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/etc/sudoers.d/' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep /etc/sudoers.d /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep '/etc/sudoers.d'\n\nChecking for '/etc/sudoers.d/' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers.d/' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/etc/sudoers.d/' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/etc/sudoers.d/' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a793de9f-0bd7-4075-b35d-bf19ced03f18",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230232",
          "group_id_src": "V-230232",
          "rule_id": "SV-230232r1017051",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230232r1017051_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010120",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must employ FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithms for all stored passwords.",
          "fix_text": "Lock all interactive user accounts not using SHA-512 hashing until the passwords can be regenerated with SHA-512.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must employ FIPS 140-2 approved cryptographic hashing algorithms for all stored passwords.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The system must use a strong hashing algorithm to store the password.\n\nPasswords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read (i.e., clear text) and easily compromised.",
          "check_content": "Confirm that the interactive user account passwords are using a strong password hash with the following command:\n\n$ sudo cut -d: -f2 /etc/shadow\n\n$6$kcOnRq/5$NUEYPuyL.wghQwWssXRcLRFiiru7f5JPV6GaJhNC2aK5F3PZpE/BCCtwrxRc/AInKMNX3CdMw11m9STiql12f/\n\nPassword hashes \"!\" or \"*\" indicate inactive accounts not available for logon and are not evaluated. If any interactive user password hash does not begin with \"$6$\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230232"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000196",
            "CCI-004062"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230232",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000073-GPOS-00041",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All interactive user account passwords are using a strong password hash.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\necho \"Interactive Users:\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n         if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                 echo \"$username\"\n         fi\ndone < $FILENAME\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/shadow\n\nChecking if interactive user account passwords are using a strong password hash:\n\u2705 The user: 'root' has a password that starts with '$6$'.\n\u2705 The user: 'deckerr' has a password that starts with '$6$'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a7a5154c-c4c9-4a27-855b-beb201499e6e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230354",
          "group_id_src": "V-230354",
          "rule_id": "SV-230354r1069323",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230354r1069323_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020080",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the session lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to prevent a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nCreate a database to contain the system-wide screensaver settings (if it does not already exist) with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so if the system is using another database in \"/etc/dconf/profile/user\", the file should be created under the appropriate subdirectory.\n\n$ sudo touch /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/session\n\nAdd the following setting to prevent non-privileged users from modifying it:\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay\n\nRun the following command to update the database:\n\n$ sudo dconf update",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent a user from overriding the session lock-delay setting for the graphical user interface.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "A session time-out lock is a temporary action taken when a user stops work and moves away from the immediate physical vicinity of the information system but does not log out because of the temporary nature of the absence. Rather than relying on the user to manually lock their operating system session prior to vacating the vicinity, operating systems need to be able to identify when a user's session has idled and take action to initiate the session lock.\n\nThe session lock is implemented at the point where session activity can be determined and/or controlled.\n\nImplementing session settings will have little value if a user is able to manipulate these settings from the defaults prescribed in the other requirements of this implementation guide.\n\nLocking these settings from non-privileged users is crucial to maintaining a protected baseline.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010, SRG-OS-000031-GPOS-00012, SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system prevents a user from overriding settings for graphical user interfaces.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nDetermine which profile the system database is using with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user\n\nsystem-db:local\n\nCheck that graphical settings are locked from non-privileged user modification with the following command:\n\nNote: The example below is using the database \"local\" for the system, so the path is \"/etc/dconf/db/local.d\". This path must be modified if a database other than \"local\" is being used.\n\n$ sudo grep -i lock-delay /etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks/*\n\n/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay\n\nIf the command does not return at least the example result, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230354"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000057"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230354",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000029-GPOS-00010",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay' was not found in any of the 'system-db' directories identified in '/etc/dconf/profile/user'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed |grep gnome-shell\ngrep system-db /etc/dconf/profile/user | cut -d: -f2 | xargs -I DIR sh -c 'echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"; echo \"Directory: /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks\"; grep -iH lock-delay /etc/dconf/db/DIR.d/locks/*' 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking if the system has a GUI installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system has a GUI installed:\n   xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking if 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d The 'Gnome Shell' is installed:\n   chrome-gnome-shell.x86_64                          42.1-1.el8                                                  @appstream\ngnome-shell.x86_64                                 3.32.2-58.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-apps-menu.noarch             3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-common.noarch                3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-desktop-icons.noarch         3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-horizontal-workspaces.noarch 3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-launch-new-instance.noarch   3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-places-menu.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\ngnome-shell-extension-window-list.noarch           3.32.1-49.el8_10                                            @appstream\n\nChecking the 'lock-delay' setting is protected for 'Gnome Shell':\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/local.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/site.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay' not found in any files\n   Searching in '/etc/dconf/db/distro.d/locks:\n   \u274c '/org/gnome/desktop/screensaver/lock-delay' not found in any files\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a88dc523-c482-40b6-afd7-04bf6402fa6c",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230300",
          "group_id_src": "V-230300",
          "rule_id": "SV-230300r1017110",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230300r1017110_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010571",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot directory.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"nosuid\" option on the /boot directory.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent files with the setuid and setgid bit set from being executed on the /boot directory.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system not to execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "For systems that use UEFI, this is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify the /boot directory is mounted with the \"nosuid\" option with the following command:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep '\\s/boot\\s'\n\n/dev/sda1 on /boot type xfs (rw,nosuid,relatime,seclabe,attr2,inode64,noquota)\n\nIf the /boot file system does not have the \"nosuid\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230300"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230300",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The '/boot' directory is not being mounted with the 'nosuid' setting",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nls /sys/firmware/efi\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nmount | grep '\\s/boot\\s'\n\nChecking if the system is using UEFI:\n\ud83d\udd0d The system is not using UEFI\n\nChecking if the '/boot' directory is mounted with 'nosuid' option:\n\u274c /dev/vda1 on /boot type ext4 (rw,relatime,seclabel)\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "a8dd254b-4b32-4c13-8444-d961456de49a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-254520",
          "group_id_src": "V-254520",
          "rule_id": "SV-254520r1069331",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-254520r1069331_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040400",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions, including disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to prevent nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions, including disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.\n\nUse the following command to map a new user to the \"sysadm_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -a -s sysadm_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map an existing user to the \"sysadm_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -m -s sysadm_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map a new user to the \"staff_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -a -s staff_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map an existing user to the \"staff_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -m -s staff_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map a new user to the \"user_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo  semanage login -a -s user_u <username>\n\nUse the following command to map an existing user to the \"user_u\" role:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -m -s user_u <username>\n\nNote: SELinux confined users mapped to sysadm_u are not allowed to log in to the system over SSH, by default. If this is a required function, it can be configured by setting the ssh_sysadm_login SELinux boolean to \"on\" with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo setsebool -P ssh_sysadm_login on\n\nThis must be documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions, including disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Preventing nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions mitigates the risk that unauthorized individuals or processes may gain unnecessary access to information or privileges.\n\nPrivileged functions include, for example, establishing accounts, performing system integrity checks, or administering cryptographic key management activities. Nonprivileged users are individuals who do not possess appropriate authorizations. Circumventing intrusion detection and prevention mechanisms or malicious code protection mechanisms are examples of privileged functions that require protection from nonprivileged users.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system prevents nonprivileged users from executing privileged functions, including disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.\n\nObtain a list of authorized users (other than system administrator and guest accounts) for the system.\n\nCheck the list against the system by using the following command:\n\n     $ sudo semanage login -l | more\n\n     Login Name    SELinux User    MLS/MCS Range    Service\n\n     __default__   user_u                 s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     root                   unconfined_u  s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     system_u        system_u           s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n     joe                     staff_u                s0-s0:c0.c1023        *\n\nAll administrators must be mapped to the \"sysadm_u\", \"staff_u\", or an appropriately tailored confined role as defined by the organization.\n\nAll authorized nonadministrative users must be mapped to the \"user_u\" role.\n\nIf they are not mapped in this way, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-254520"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002235"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-254520",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000324-GPOS-00125",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following users are not mapped to a SELinux Role:\ndeckerr",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#!/bin/bash\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n        if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n                echo \"$username\"\n        fi\ndone < $FILENAME\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsemanage user -l\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsemanage login -l\n\nChecking if interactive users are mapped to SELinux User role:\n\u274c deckerr  __default__\nNone\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "aa24972a-2c6c-499f-821c-697b1da59c03",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230486",
          "group_id_src": "V-230486",
          "rule_id": "SV-230486r1017270",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230486r1017270_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030742",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable network management of the chrony daemon.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system disable network management of the chrony daemon by adding or modifying the following line in the \"/etc/chrony.conf\" file.\n\ncmdport 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable network management of the chrony daemon.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nNot exposing the management interface of the chrony daemon on the network diminishes the attack space.\n\nRHEL 8 utilizes the \"timedatectl\" command to view the status of the \"systemd-timesyncd.service\". The \"timedatectl\" status will display the local time, UTC, and the offset from UTC.\n\nNote that USNO offers authenticated NTP service to DOD and U.S. Government agencies operating on the NIPR and SIPR networks. Visit https://www.usno.navy.mil/USNO/time/ntp/DOD-customers for more information.",
          "check_content": "Note: If the system is approved and documented by the information system security officer (ISSO) to function as an NTP time server, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nVerify RHEL 8 disables network management of the chrony daemon with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w 'cmdport' /etc/chrony.conf\ncmdport 0\n\nIf the \"cmdport\" option is not set to \"0\", is commented out or missing, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230486"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230486",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'cmdport' option does not exist in '/etc/chrony.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w 'cmdport' /etc/chrony.conf\n\nChecking 'cmdport' value in '/etc/chrony.conf':\n\u274c The 'cmdport' option does not exist\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "aa973786-4627-4126-936e-394dfdc330b1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230499",
          "group_id_src": "V-230499",
          "rule_id": "SV-230499r1069315",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230499r1069315_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040026",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable IEEE 1394 (FireWire) Support.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to disable the ability to use the firewire-core kernel module.\n\nAdd or update the following lines in the file \"/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf\":\n\n     install firewire-core /bin/false\n     blacklist firewire-core\n\nReboot the system for the settings to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable IEEE 1394 (FireWire) Support.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nThe IEEE 1394 (FireWire) is a serial bus standard for high-speed real-time communication. Disabling FireWire protects the system against exploitation of any flaws in its implementation.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system disables the ability to load the firewire-core kernel module and ensure that the firewire-core kernel module is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r firewire-core /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\"\n\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:install firewire-core /bin/false\n/etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf:blacklist firewire-core\n\nIf the command does not return any output, or the line is commented out, and use of the firewire-core protocol is not documented with the Information System Security Officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230499"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000381"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230499",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'install firewire-core kernel module /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\nThe 'firewire-core kernel module blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r firewire-core /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"install\" 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r firewire-core /etc/modprobe.d/* | grep \"blacklist\" 2>/dev/null\n\n\nChecking if firewire-core kernel module is disabled:\n\u274c The 'install firewire-core kernel module /bin/true' setting was not found in any files in '/etc/modprobe.d/' directory\n\nChecking if the firewire-core kernel module blacklist entry exists:\n\u274c The 'firewire-core kernel module blacklist' entry is missing from any config file in '/etc/modprobe.d/'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "ab229314-4315-4417-9813-166df0775ab3",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230322",
          "group_id_src": "V-230322",
          "rule_id": "SV-230322r1017133",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230322r1017133_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010740",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directories must be group-owned by the home directory owner\u2019s primary group.",
          "fix_text": "Change the group owner of a local interactive user\u2019s home directory to the group found in \"/etc/passwd\". To change the group owner of a local interactive user\u2019s home directory, use the following command:\n\nNote: The example will be for the user \"smithj\", who has a home directory of \"/home/smithj\", and has a primary group of users.\n\n     $ sudo chgrp users /home/smithj",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 local interactive user home directories must be group-owned by the home directory owner\u2019s primary group.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If the Group Identifier (GID) of a local interactive user\u2019s home directory is not the same as the primary GID of the user, this would allow unauthorized access to the user\u2019s files, and users that share the same group may not be able to access files that they legitimately should.",
          "check_content": "Verify the assigned home directory of all local interactive users is group-owned by that user\u2019s primary GID with the following command:\n\nNote: This may miss local interactive users that have been assigned a privileged UID. Evidence of interactive use may be obtained from a number of log files containing system logon information. The returned directory \"/home/smithj\" is used as an example.\n\n     $ sudo ls -ld $(awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $6}' /etc/passwd)\n\n     drwxr-x--- 2 smithj admin 4096 Jun 5 12:41 smithj\n\nCheck the user's primary group with the following command:\n\n     $ sudo grep $(grep smithj /etc/passwd | awk -F: '{print $4}') /etc/group\n\n     admin:x:250:smithj,jonesj,jacksons\n\nIf the user home directory referenced in \"/etc/passwd\" is not group-owned by that user\u2019s primary GID, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230322"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230322",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "All user home directories referenced in '/etc/passwd' are group-owned by that user\u2019s primary Group ID",
          "finding_details": "#while IFS=: read -r username _ _ _ _ home_dir shell; do\n    if [[ \"$shell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$shell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$shell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$shell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$shell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$shell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$shell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" ]]; then\n        group_owner=$(stat -c '%g' \"$home_dir\")\n        primary_group=$(id -g \"$username\")\n\n        echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\n        echo \"$username:$home_dir:$group_owner:$primary_group\"\n    fi\ndone < /etc/passwd\n\nChecking that the home directory of interactive users is group-owned by that user\u2019s primary GID:\n\u2705 Username: root\n   Home Directory: /root\n   Home Directory Group ID: 0\n   User's Primary Group ID: 0\n\n\u2705 Username: deckerr\n   Home Directory: /home/deckerr\n   Home Directory Group ID: 1000\n   User's Primary Group ID: 1000\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "ad27e65a-a20c-42cc-ae90-6bdc5bb81bff",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230526",
          "group_id_src": "V-230526",
          "rule_id": "SV-230526r958908",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230526r958908_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040160",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 networked systems must have and implement SSH to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted and received information, as well as information during preparation for transmission.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the SSH service to automatically start after reboot with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl enable sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 networked systems must have and implement SSH to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted and received information, as well as information during preparation for transmission.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered.\n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification.\n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189, SRG-OS-000426-GPOS-00190",
          "check_content": "Verify SSH is loaded and active with the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl status sshd\n\nsshd.service - OpenSSH server daemon\nLoaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/sshd.service; enabled)\nActive: active (running) since Tue 2015-11-17 15:17:22 EST; 4 weeks 0 days ago\nMain PID: 1348 (sshd)\nCGroup: /system.slice/sshd.service\n1053 /usr/sbin/sshd -D\n\nIf \"sshd\" does not show a status of \"active\" and \"running\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230526"
          ],
          "ccis": [
