          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'GSSAPIAuthentication' keyword is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration, but should be set to something other than 'yes':\ngssapiauthentication yes",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'GSSAPIAuthentication' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u274c gssapiauthentication yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c4d63c5d-0e86-4678-ae2b-7521b4a3acba",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230402",
          "group_id_src": "V-230402",
          "rule_id": "SV-230402r1017208",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230402r1017208_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030121",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 audit system must protect auditing rules from unauthorized change.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to set the audit rules to be immutable by adding the following line to \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\"\n\n-e 2\n\nNote: Once set, the system must be rebooted for auditing to be changed.  It is recommended to add this option as the last step in securing the system.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 audit system must protect auditing rules from unauthorized change.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unauthorized disclosure of audit records can reveal system and configuration data to attackers, thus compromising its confidentiality.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, audit reports) needed to successfully audit RHEL 8 system activity.\n\nIn immutable mode, unauthorized users cannot execute changes to the audit system to potentially hide malicious activity and then put the audit rules back.  A system reboot would be noticeable and a system administrator could then investigate the unauthorized changes.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027, SRG-OS-000058-GPOS-00028, SRG-OS-000059-GPOS-00029",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit system prevents unauthorized changes with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"^\\s*[^#]\" /etc/audit/audit.rules | tail -1\n\n-e 2\n\nIf the audit system is not set to be immutable by adding the \"-e 2\" option to the \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230402"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000162"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230402",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000057-GPOS-00027",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The last line in '/etc/audit/audit.rules' is not '-e 2'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\nChecking that the audit system prevents unauthorized changes:\n\u274c --backlog_wait_time 60000\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c659965a-bc80-441e-a171-2ad342d23d57",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230378",
          "group_id_src": "V-230378",
          "rule_id": "SV-230378r1017189",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230378r1017189_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020310",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed console logon attempt.\n\nModify the \"/etc/login.defs\" file to set the \"FAIL_DELAY\" parameter to \"4\" or greater:\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must enforce a delay of at least four seconds between logon prompts following a failed logon attempt.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Configuring the operating system to implement organization-wide security implementation guides and security checklists verifies compliance with federal standards and establishes a common security baseline across the DoD that reflects the most restrictive security posture consistent with operational requirements.\n\nConfiguration settings are the set of parameters that can be changed in hardware, software, or firmware components of the system that affect the security posture and/or functionality of the system. Security-related parameters are those parameters impacting the security state of the system, including the parameters required to satisfy other security control requirements. Security-related parameters include, for example, registry settings; account, file, and directory permission settings; and settings for functions, ports, protocols, services, and remote connections.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system enforces a delay of at least four seconds between console logon prompts following a failed logon attempt with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i fail_delay /etc/login.defs\n\nFAIL_DELAY 4\n\nIf the value of \"FAIL_DELAY\" is not set to \"4\" or greater, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230378"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230378",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00226",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'FAIL_DELAY' setting does not exist in '/etc/login.defs'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Ei '^[[:space:]]*fail_delay' /etc/login.defs\n\nChecking the value for 'FAIL_DELAY':\n\u274c The 'FAIL_DELAY' setting does not exist in '/etc/login.defs'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c6857e2e-932d-4685-9698-82b3e69e07d6",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230337",
          "group_id_src": "V-230337",
          "rule_id": "SV-230337r1134885",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230337r1134885_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020015",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to lock an account until released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur in 15 minutes.\n\nAdd/Modify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file to match the following line:\n\nunlock_time = 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful logon attempts occur during a 15-minute time period.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-force attacks, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.\n\nIn RHEL 8.2 the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file was incorporated to centralize the configuration of the pam_faillock.so module.  Also introduced is a \"local_users_only\" option that will only track failed user authentication attempts for local users in /etc/passwd and ignore centralized (AD, IdM, LDAP, etc.) users to allow the centralized platform to solely manage user lockout.\n\nFrom \"faillock.conf\" man pages: Note that the default directory that \"pam_faillock\" uses is usually cleared on system boot so the access will be reenabled after system reboot. If that is undesirable a different tally directory must be set with the \"dir\" option.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005, SRG-OS-000329-GPOS-00128",
          "check_content": "Verify the \"/etc/security/faillock.conf\" file is configured to lock an account until released by an administrator after three unsuccessful logon attempts:\n\n$ sudo grep 'unlock_time =' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nunlock_time = 0\n\nIf the \"unlock_time\" option is not set to \"0\", or is missing or commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230337"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000044"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230337",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000021-GPOS-00005",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'unlock_time' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ncat /etc/redhat-release\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\ngrep -E '^[[:space:]]*unlock_time[[:space:]]*=' /etc/security/faillock.conf\n\nChecking the version of RHEL:\n\ud83d\udd0d The RHEL version is '8.10'. \nRocky Linux release 8.10 (Green Obsidian)\n\nChecking the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file is configured to lock an account until released by an administrator after 3unsuccessful logon attempts:\n\u274c The 'unlock_time' option does not exist in the '/etc/security/faillock.conf' file.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c6ab3307-7f69-409b-93de-d46f90fe8a9a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244549",
          "group_id_src": "V-244549",
          "rule_id": "SV-244549r958908",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244549r958908_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040159",
          "rule_title": "All RHEL 8 networked systems must have SSH installed.",
          "fix_text": "Install SSH packages onto the host with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install openssh-server.x86_64",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "All RHEL 8 networked systems must have SSH installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered.\n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of information system components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification.\n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187, SRG-OS-000424-GPOS-00188, SRG-OS-000425-GPOS-00189, SRG-OS-000426-GPOS-00190",
          "check_content": "Verify SSH is installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed openssh-server\n\nopenssh-server.x86_64                 8.0p1-5.el8          @anaconda\n\nIf the \"SSH server\" package is not installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244549"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-002418"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244549",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000423-GPOS-00187",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'openssh-server' package (openssh-server.x86_64                  8.0p1-27.el8_10                   @baseos) is installed.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed openssh-server\n\nChecking if the 'openssh-server' package is installed:\n\u2705 The 'openssh-server' package ('openssh-server.x86_64                  8.0p1-27.el8_10                   @baseos') is installed.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c7544b30-01cd-441a-b09b-36f75dae40d1",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-251711",
          "group_id_src": "V-251711",
          "rule_id": "SV-251711r1017365",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-251711r1017365_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010379",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must specify the default \"include\" directory for the /etc/sudoers file.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the /etc/sudoers file to only include the /etc/sudoers.d directory.\n\nEdit the /etc/sudoers file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo visudo\n\nAdd or modify the following line:\n#includedir /etc/sudoers.d",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must specify the default \"include\" directory for the /etc/sudoers file.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"sudo\" command allows authorized users to run programs (including shells) as other users, system users, and root. The \"/etc/sudoers\" file is used to configure authorized \"sudo\" users as well as the programs they are allowed to run. Some configuration options in the \"/etc/sudoers\" file allow configured users to run programs without re-authenticating. Use of these configuration options makes it easier for one compromised account to be used to compromise other accounts.\n\nIt is possible to include other sudoers files from within the sudoers file currently being parsed using the #include and #includedir directives. When sudo reaches this line it will suspend processing of the current file (/etc/sudoers) and switch to the specified file/directory. Once the end of the included file(s) is reached, the rest of /etc/sudoers will be processed. Files that are included may themselves include other files. A hard limit of 128 nested include files is enforced to prevent include file loops.",
          "check_content": "Note: If the \"include\" and \"includedir\" directives are not present in the /etc/sudoers file, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nVerify the operating system specifies only the default \"include\" directory for the /etc/sudoers file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep include /etc/sudoers\n\n#includedir /etc/sudoers.d\n\nIf the results are not \"/etc/sudoers.d\" or additional files or directories are specified, this is a finding.\n\nVerify the operating system does not have nested \"include\" files or directories within the /etc/sudoers.d directory with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -r include /etc/sudoers.d\n\nIf results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-251711"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-251711",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'includedir' directive in '/etc/sudoers' points to '/etc/sudoers.d'\nNo additional 'includes' were found in '/etc/sudoers.d/'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep includedir /etc/sudoers\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -r include /etc/sudoers.d 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking 'includedir' in '/etc/sudoers':\n\u2705 #includedir /etc/sudoers.d\n\nChecking for additional 'includes' in '/etc/sudoers.d/':\n\u2705 No additional 'includes' were found in '/etc/sudoers.d/'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c83b3171-8e6d-4ccd-a70d-e861502c0f5d",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230222",
          "group_id_src": "V-230222",
          "rule_id": "SV-230222r1017041",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230222r1017041_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010010",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 vendor packaged system security patches and updates must be installed and up to date.",
          "fix_text": "Install the operating system patches or updated packages available from Red Hat within 30 days or sooner as local policy dictates.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 vendor packaged system security patches and updates must be installed and up to date.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Timely patching is critical for maintaining the operational availability, confidentiality, and integrity of information technology (IT) systems. However, failure to keep operating system and application software patched is a common mistake made by IT professionals. New patches are released daily, and it is often difficult for even experienced System Administrators to keep abreast of all the new patches. When new weaknesses in an operating system exist, patches are usually made available by the vendor to resolve the problems. If the most recent security patches and updates are not installed, unauthorized users may take advantage of weaknesses in the unpatched software. The lack of prompt attention to patching could result in a system compromise.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system security patches and updates are installed and up to date. Updates are required to be applied with a frequency determined by the site or Program Management Office (PMO).\n\nObtain the list of available package security updates from Red Hat. The URL for updates is https://rhn.redhat.com/errata/. It is important to note that updates provided by Red Hat may not be present on the system if the underlying packages are not installed.\n\nCheck that the available package security updates have been installed on the system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum history list | more\n\nLoaded plugins: langpacks, product-id, subscription-manager\nID | Command line | Date and time | Action(s) | Altered\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n70 | install aide | 2020-03-05 10:58 | Install | 1\n69 | update -y | 2020-03-04 14:34 | Update | 18 EE\n68 | install vlc | 2020-02-21 17:12 | Install | 21\n67 | update -y | 2020-02-21 17:04 | Update | 7 EE\n\nIf package updates have not been performed on the system within the timeframe the site/program documentation requires, this is a finding.\n\nTypical update frequency may be overridden by Information Assurance Vulnerability Alert (IAVA) notifications from CYBERCOM.\n\nIf the operating system is in non-compliance with the Information Assurance Vulnerability Management (IAVM) process, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230222"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230222",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_reviewed",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Package updates were last accomplished on  2026-03-27 21:31",
          "finding_details": "#yum history list\n\n\ud83d\udd36 Found most recent update with yum/dnf ID 3 on  2026-03-27 21:31 \n  If the number of days since package updates were applied is within\n  site/program documentation requirements, mark this as 'Not A Finding',\n  otherwise this should be marked a 'Finding'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "c8c1929a-2717-48d4-8b77-44e4fb1e9c71",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230446",
          "group_id_src": "V-230446",
          "rule_id": "SV-230446r1017245",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230446r1017245_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030390",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the delete_module command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"delete_module\" command by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the delete_module command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"delete_module\" command is used to unload a kernel module.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record when successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"delete_module\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"delete_module\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S delete_module -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k module_chng\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
