          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040290",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying.",
          "fix_text": "If \"postfix\" is installed, modify the \"/etc/postfix/main.cf\" file to restrict client connections to the local network with the following command:\n\n$ sudo postconf -e 'smtpd_client_restrictions = permit_mynetworks,reject'",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If unrestricted mail relaying is permitted, unauthorized senders could use this host as a mail relay for the purpose of sending spam or other unauthorized activity.",
          "check_content": "Verify the system is configured to prevent unrestricted mail relaying.\n\nDetermine if \"postfix\" is installed with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed postfix\n\npostfix.x86_64  2:3.3.1-9.el8\n\nIf postfix is not installed, this is Not Applicable.\n\nIf postfix is installed, determine if it is configured to reject connections from unknown or untrusted networks with the following command:\n\n$ sudo postconf -n smtpd_client_restrictions\n\nsmtpd_client_restrictions = permit_mynetworks, reject\n\nIf the \"smtpd_client_restrictions\" parameter contains any entries other than \"permit_mynetworks\" and \"reject\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230550"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230550",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'postfix' (Error: No matching Packages to list) is installed.\nThe 'postconf' command returned unexpected results.\nxylok-cmd-temp.sh: line 5: postconf: command not found",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed postfix\necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\npostconf -n smtpd_client_restrictions\n\nChecking if 'postfix' is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d 'postfix' (Error: No matching Packages to list) is installed.\n\nChecking 'postfix' is configured to reject connections from unknown or untrusted networks:\n\u274c The 'postconf' command returned unexpected results.\nxylok-cmd-temp.sh: line 5: postconf: command not found\nxylok-cmd-temp.sh: line 5: postconf: command not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d134b61e-af30-4119-8593-4b92c4d6bdd4",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230439",
          "group_id_src": "V-230439",
          "rule_id": "SV-230439r1017243",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230439r1017243_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030361",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"rename\", \"unlink\", \"rmdir\", \"renameat\", and \"unlinkat\" system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the rename, unlink, rmdir, renameat, and unlinkat system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"rename\" system call will rename the specified files by replacing the first occurrence of expression in their name by replacement.\n\nThe \"unlink\" system call deletes a name from the filesystem. If that name was the last link to a file and no processes have the file open, the file is deleted and the space it was using is made available for reuse.\nThe \"rmdir\" system call removes empty directories.\nThe \"renameat\" system call renames a file, moving it between directories if required.\nThe \"unlinkat\" system call operates in exactly the same way as either \"unlink\" or \"rmdir\" except for the differences described in the manual page.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. Performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"rename\", \"unlink\", \"rmdir\", \"renameat\", and \"unlinkat\" system calls by using the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep 'rename\\|unlink\\|rmdir' /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S rename,unlink,rmdir,renameat,unlinkat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k delete\n\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"rename\", \"unlink\", \"rmdir\", \"renameat\", and \"unlinkat\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230439"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230439",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'rename' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'rename' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'unlink' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'unlink' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'rmdir' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'rmdir' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'renameat' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'renameat' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'unlinkat' does not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'unlinkat' does not exist.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"rename\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"rename\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"unlink\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"unlink\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"rmdir\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"rmdir\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"renameat\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"renameat\" | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"unlinkat\" | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w \"unlinkat\" | grep b64\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'rename':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'rename' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'rename' does not exist.\nChecking audit records are generated for 'unlink':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'unlink' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'unlink' does not exist.\nChecking audit records are generated for 'rmdir':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'rmdir' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'rmdir' does not exist.\nChecking audit records are generated for 'renameat':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'renameat' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'renameat' does not exist.\nChecking audit records are generated for 'unlinkat':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rule for 'unlinkat' does not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rule for 'unlinkat' does not exist.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d170a94b-9519-44bd-b3d4-8540f89c6e2f",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230296",
          "group_id_src": "V-230296",
          "rule_id": "SV-230296r1069322",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230296r1069322_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010550",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not permit direct logons to the root account using remote access via SSH.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to stop users from logging on remotely as the \"root\" user via SSH.\n\nEdit the appropriate \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment or add the line for the \"PermitRootLogin\" keyword and set its value to \"no\":\n\nPermitRootLogin no\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not permit direct logons to the root account using remote access via SSH.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Even though the communications channel may be encrypted, an additional layer of security is gained by extending the policy of not logging on directly as root. In addition, logging on with a user-specific account provides individual accountability of actions performed on the system.",
          "check_content": "Verify remote access using SSH prevents users from logging on directly as \"root\".\n\nCheck that SSH prevents users from logging on directly as \"root\" with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permitrootlogin'\n\nPermitRootLogin no\n\nIf the \"PermitRootLogin\" keyword is set to any value other than \"no\", is missing, or is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230296"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000770",
            "CCI-004045"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230296",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000109-GPOS-00056",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'PermitRootLogin' is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration, but should be set to 'no':\npermitrootlogin yes",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'PermitRootLogin' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u274c permitrootlogin yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d1862534-f737-40b9-917a-2342b203ea13",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230380",
          "group_id_src": "V-230380",
          "rule_id": "SV-230380r1069308",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230380r1069308_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020330",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the following line in \"etc/ssh/sshd_config\" to prevent logons with empty passwords.\n\nPermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nThe SSH daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect. To restart the SSH daemon, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd.service",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not allow accounts configured with blank or null passwords.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If an account has an empty password, anyone could log on and run commands with the privileges of that account. Accounts with empty passwords should never be used in operational environments.",
          "check_content": "To verify that null passwords cannot be used, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*permitemptypasswords'\n\n/etc/ssh/sshd_config:PermitEmptyPasswords no\n\nIf \"PermitEmptyPasswords\" is set to \"yes\", this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230380"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230380",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'PermitEmptyPasswords' keyword is set to 'no' in the sshd effective configuration",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'PermitEmptyPasswords' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u2705 permitemptypasswords no\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d18a49c1-62ce-4440-8b4d-d453203cb3ef",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230516",
          "group_id_src": "V-230516",
          "rule_id": "SV-230516r958804",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230516r958804_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040128",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log with the noexec option.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the system so that /var/log is mounted with the \"noexec\" option by adding /modifying the /etc/fstab with the following line:\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log /var/log xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must mount /var/log with the noexec option.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs that are authorized to execute on organizational information systems is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nThe \"noexec\" mount option causes the system to not execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nodev\" mount option causes the system to not interpret character or block special devices. Executing character or block special devices from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.\n\nThe \"nosuid\" mount option causes the system to not execute \"setuid\" and \"setgid\" files with owner privileges. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved \"setuid\" and \"setguid\" files. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify \"/var/log\" is mounted with the \"noexec\" option:\n\n$ sudo mount | grep /var/log\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log on /var/log type xfs (rw,nodev,nosuid,noexec,seclabel)\n\nVerify that the \"noexec\" option is configured for /var/log:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log\n\n/dev/mapper/rhel-var-log /var/log xfs defaults,nodev,nosuid,noexec 0 0\n\nIf results are returned and the \"noexec\" option is missing, or if /var/log is mounted without the \"noexec\" option, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230516"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001764"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230516",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000368-GPOS-00154",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "'/var/log' is not mounted on the system.\n'/var/log' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nmount | grep /var/log\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/fstab | grep /var/log\n\nChecking if '/var/log' is mounted with 'noexec' option:\n\u274c '/var/log' is not mounted on the system.\n\n\nChecking that the 'noexec' is configured for '/var/log':\n\u274c '/var/log' is not configured in '/etc/fstab'.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d359a6f7-5ac4-4449-9849-240a6a97f177",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230480",
          "group_id_src": "V-230480",
          "rule_id": "SV-230480r958754",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230480r958754_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030700",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"overflow_action\" option:\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must take appropriate action when the internal event queue is full.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in information systems with limited audit storage capacity.\n\nRHEL 8 installation media provides \"rsyslogd\".  \"rsyslogd\" is a system utility providing support for message logging.  Support for both internet and UNIX domain sockets enables this utility to support both local and remote logging.  Couple this utility with \"gnutls\" (which is a secure communications library implementing the SSL, TLS and DTLS protocols), and you have a method to securely encrypt and off-load auditing.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133, SRG-OS-000479-GPOS-00224",
          "check_content": "Verify the audit system is configured to take an appropriate action when the internal event queue is full:\n\n$ sudo grep -i overflow_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\noverflow_action = syslog\n\nIf the value of the \"overflow_action\" option is not set to \"syslog\", \"single\", \"halt\", or the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the audit logs are off-loaded to a different system or media.\n\nIf there is no evidence that the transfer of the audit logs being off-loaded to another system or media takes appropriate action if the internal event queue becomes full, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230480"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001851"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230480",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'overflow_action' setting is set to 'SYSLOG' in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i overflow_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking the 'overflow_action' setting in '/etc/audit/auditd.conf:\n\u2705 overflow_action = SYSLOG\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d577a6ad-391a-4bcb-a89d-fe0b08bf4bea",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230221",
          "group_id_src": "V-230221",
          "rule_id": "SV-230221r1017040",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230221r1017040_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010000",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must be a vendor-supported release.",
          "fix_text": "Upgrade to a supported version of RHEL 8.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must be a vendor-supported release.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "An operating system release is considered \"supported\" if the vendor continues to provide security patches for the product. With an unsupported release, it will not be possible to resolve security issues discovered in the system software.\n\nRed Hat offers the Extended Update Support (EUS) add-on to a Red Hat Enterprise Linux subscription, for a fee, for those customers who wish to standardize on a specific minor release for an extended period. The RHEL 8 minor releases eligible for EUS are 8.1, 8.2, 8.4, 8.6, and 8.8. Each RHEL 8 EUS stream is available for 24 months from the availability of the minor release. RHEL 8.10 will be the final minor release overall. For more details on the Red Hat Enterprise Linux Life Cycle  visit https://access.redhat.com/support/policy/updates/errata/.\nNote: The life-cycle time spans and dates are subject to adjustment.",
          "check_content": "Verify the version of the operating system is vendor supported.\n\nNote: The lifecycle time spans and dates are subject to adjustment.\n\nCheck the version of the operating system with the following command:\n\n$ sudo cat /etc/redhat-release\n\nRed Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 8.6 (Ootpa)\n\nCurrent End of Extended Update Support for RHEL 8.1 is 30 November 2021.\n\nCurrent End of Extended Update Support for RHEL 8.2 is 30 April 2022.\n\nCurrent End of Extended Update Support for RHEL 8.4 is 31 May 2023.\n\nCurrent End of Maintenance Support for RHEL 8.5 is 31 May 2022.\n\nCurrent End of Extended Update Support for RHEL 8.6 is 31 May 2024.\n\nCurrent End of Maintenance Support for RHEL 8.7 is 31 May 2023.\n\nCurrent End of Extended Update Support for RHEL 8.8 is 31 May 2025.\n\nCurrent End of Maintenance Support for RHEL 8.9 is 31 May 2024.\n\nCurrent End of Maintenance Support for RHEL 8.10 is 31 May 2029.\n\nIf the release is not supported by the vendor, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230221"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230221",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "This system is running RHEL 8.10 and the Extended Update Support has not ended for this version.",
          "finding_details": "#cat /etc/redhat-release\n\nScan Date: 2026-03-28 04:09:31\n\nChecking the system's version of RHEL:\n\u2705 This system is running RHEL 8.10 and the Extended Update Support has not ended for this version.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d6f485d4-819f-43f7-a3dc-a703a6d10110",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230555",
          "group_id_src": "V-230555",
          "rule_id": "SV-230555r1017317",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230555r1017317_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040340",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 remote X connections for interactive users must be disabled unless to fulfill documented and validated mission requirements.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the \"/etc/ssh/sshd_config\" file to uncomment or add the line for the \"X11Forwarding\" keyword and set its value to \"no\" (this file may be named differently or be in a different location if using a version of SSH that is provided by a third-party vendor):\n\nX11Forwarding no\n\nThe SSH service must be restarted for changes to take effect:\n\n$ sudo systemctl restart sshd",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 remote X connections for interactive users must be disabled unless to fulfill documented and validated mission requirements.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The security risk of using X11 forwarding is that the client's X11 display server may be exposed to attack when the SSH client requests forwarding.  A system administrator may have a stance in which they want to protect clients that may expose themselves to attack by unwittingly requesting X11 forwarding, which can warrant a \"no\" setting.\n\nX11 forwarding should be enabled with caution. Users with the ability to bypass file permissions on the remote host (for the user's X11 authorization database) can access the local X11 display through the forwarded connection. An attacker may then be able to perform activities such as keystroke monitoring if the ForwardX11Trusted option is also enabled.\n\nIf X11 services are not required for the system's intended function, they should be disabled or restricted as appropriate to the system\u2019s needs.",
          "check_content": "Verify X11Forwarding is disabled with the following command:\n\n$ sudo /usr/sbin/sshd -dd 2>&1 | awk '/filename/ {print $4}' | tr -d '\\r' | tr '\\n' ' ' | xargs sudo grep -iH '^\\s*x11forwarding'\n\nX11Forwarding no\n\nIf the \"X11Forwarding\" keyword is set to \"yes\" and is not documented with the  information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement or is missing, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230555"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230555",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'X11Forwarding' keyword is set to 'yes' in the sshd effective configuration, but should be set to something other than 'yes':\nx11forwarding yes",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsshd -T 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking for the 'X11Forwarding' keyword in the sshd effective configuration:\n\u274c x11forwarding yes\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d77008b7-1aeb-4fbb-bda4-d84c9d690412",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230243",
          "group_id_src": "V-230243",
          "rule_id": "SV-230243r1137695",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230243r1137695_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010190",
          "rule_title": "A sticky bit must be set on all RHEL 8 public directories to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.",
          "fix_text": "Configure all world-writable directories to have the sticky bit set to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.\n\nSet the sticky bit on all world-writable directories using the command, replace \"[World-Writable Directory]\" with any directory path missing the sticky bit:\n\n$ sudo chmod 1777 [World-Writable Directory]",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "A sticky bit must be set on all RHEL 8 public directories to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transferred via shared system resources.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Preventing unauthorized information transfers mitigates the risk of information, including encrypted representations of information, produced by the actions of prior users/roles (or the actions of processes acting on behalf of prior users/roles) from being available to any current users/roles (or current processes) that obtain access to shared system resources (e.g., registers, main memory, hard disks) after those resources have been released back to information systems. The control of information in shared resources is also commonly referred to as object reuse and residual information protection.\n\nThis requirement generally applies to the design of an information technology product, but it can also apply to the configuration of particular information system components that are, or use, such products. This can be verified by acceptance/validation processes in DoD or other government agencies.\n\nThere may be shared resources with configurable protections (e.g., files in storage) that may be assessed on specific information system components.",
          "check_content": "Verify that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set.\n\nCheck to see that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set by running the following command:\n\n$ sudo find / -type d \\( -perm -0002 -a ! -perm -1000 \\) 2>/dev/null -exec ls -ald {} \\;\n\ndrwxrwxrwx. 14 root root 4096 Sep 13 15:13 /tmp\n\nIf any of the returned directories are world-writable and do not have the sticky bit set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230243"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001090"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230243",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000138-GPOS-00069",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_a_finding",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No world-writable directories were found without the sticky bit set",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nfind $(df --local -P | awk 'NR>1 {print $6}') -xdev -type d \\( -perm -0002 -a ! -perm -1000 \\) -exec stat -c \"Dir: %n :: Permissions: %A\" {} \\; 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking that all world-writable directories have the sticky bit set:\n\u2705 No world-writable directories were found without the sticky bit set\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d8385261-893a-4c92-ad2d-d2c38b3cee15",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244552",
          "group_id_src": "V-244552",
          "rule_id": "SV-244552r1017352",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244552r1017352_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-040249",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nAdd or edit the following line in a system configuration file, in the \"/etc/sysctl.d/\" directory:\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route=0\n\nRemove any configurations that conflict with the above from the following locations:\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\nLoad settings from all system configuration files with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not forward IPv4 source-routed packets by default.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Source-routed packets allow the source of the packet to suggest that routers forward the packet along a different path than configured on the router, which can be used to bypass network security measures. This requirement applies only to the forwarding of source-routed traffic, such as when forwarding is enabled and the system is functioning as a router.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographic order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 does not accept IPv4 source-routed packets by default.\n\nCheck the value of the accept source route variable with the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route\n\nnet.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"0\", a line is not returned, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.\n\nCheck that the configuration files are present to enable this network parameter.\n\n$ sudo grep -r net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n\n/etc/sysctl.d/99-sysctl.conf: net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0\n\nIf \"net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route\" is not set to \"0\", is missing or commented out, this is a finding.\n\nIf conflicting results are returned, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244552"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244552",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' variable is set to '1' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '0'\nThe 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' variable was not found in any config files",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route 2>/dev/null\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -Er '^[[:space:]]*net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' variable:\n\u274c net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 1\n\nChecking config files to enable 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' variable:\n\u274c The 'net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route' variable was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d8937c20-6199-484d-91ce-7ea2cdeae3d4",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-244543",
          "group_id_src": "V-244543",
          "rule_id": "SV-244543r971542",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-244543r971542_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030731",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume 75 percent utilization.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to initiate an action to notify the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity by adding/modifying the following line in the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file.\n\nspace_left_action = email\n\nNote: Option names and values in the auditd.conf file are case insensitive.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must notify the System Administrator (SA) and Information System Security Officer (ISSO) (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume 75 percent utilization.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75 percent utilization, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 notifies the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum audit record storage capacity with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -w space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nspace_left_action = email\n\nIf the value of the \"space_left_action\" is not set to \"email\", or if the line is commented out, ask the System Administrator to indicate how the system is providing real-time alerts to the SA and ISSO.\n\nIf there is no evidence that real-time alerts are configured on the system, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-244543"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001855"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-244543",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000343-GPOS-00134",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'space_left_action' setting is set to 'SYSLOG' in the '/etc/audit/auditd.conf' file, but should be set to 'email'.\nspace_left_action = SYSLOG",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w space_left_action /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking that the OS notifies the SA and ISSO when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of the repository maximum:\n\u274c space_left_action = SYSLOG\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d8adaa2b-42bc-46b5-ae8a-7199e1ae82c7",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230431",
          "group_id_src": "V-230431",
          "rule_id": "SV-230431r1017232",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230431r1017232_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030315",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of userhelper in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful uses of the \"userhelper\" by adding or updating the following rule in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/userhelper -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of userhelper in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Reconstruction of harmful events or forensic analysis is not possible if audit records do not contain enough information.\n\nAt a minimum, the organization must audit the full-text recording of privileged commands. The organization must maintain audit trails in sufficient detail to reconstruct events to determine the cause and impact of compromise. The \"userhelper\" command is not intended to be run interactively.  \"Userhelper\" provides a basic interface to change a user's password, gecos information, and shell.  The main difference between this program and its traditional equivalents (passwd, chfn, chsh) is that prompts are written to standard out to make it easy for a graphical user interface wrapper to interface to it as a child process.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of \"userhelper\" by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w \"userhelper\" /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/sbin/userhelper -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-unix-update\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230431"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230431",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'userhelper' command.",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nauditctl -l | grep \"/usr/sbin/userhelper\"\n\nChecking if an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'userhelper' command:\n\u274c No audit rule exists for generating an event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the 'userhelper' command.\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d95ba9e0-2159-45fb-a86b-b97df812501a",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230379",
          "group_id_src": "V-230379",
          "rule_id": "SV-230379r1017190",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230379r1017190_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-020320",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must not have unnecessary accounts.",
          "fix_text": "Remove unauthorized local interactive user accounts with the following command where <unauthorized_user> is the unauthorized account:\n\n$ sudo userdel <unauthorized_user>",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must not have unnecessary accounts.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Accounts providing no operational purpose provide additional opportunities for system compromise. Unnecessary accounts include user accounts for individuals not requiring access to the system and application accounts for applications not installed on the system.",
          "check_content": "Verify that there are no unauthorized interactive user accounts with the following command:\n\n$ less /etc/passwd\n\nroot:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n...\ngames:x:12:100:games:/usr/games:/sbin/nologin\nscsaustin:x:1001:1001:scsaustin:/home/scsaustin:/bin/bash\ndjohnson:x:1002:1002:djohnson:/home/djohnson:/bin/bash\n\nInteractive user account, generally will have a user identifier (UID) of 1000 or greater, a home directory in a specific partition, and an interactive shell.\n\nObtain the list of interactive user accounts authorized to be on the system from the system administrator or information system security officer (ISSO) and compare it to the list of local interactive user accounts on the system.\n\nIf there are unauthorized local user accounts on the system, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230379"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230379",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The following 'known' unnecessary users were found:\ngames\nftp",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\n\nChecking for 'known' unnecessary users:\n\ud83d\udd0d root\n\ud83d\udd0d bin\n\ud83d\udd0d daemon\n\ud83d\udd0d adm\n\ud83d\udd0d lp\n\ud83d\udd0d sync\n\ud83d\udd0d shutdown\n\ud83d\udd0d halt\n\ud83d\udd0d mail\n\ud83d\udd0d operator\n\u274c games\n\u274c ftp\n\ud83d\udd0d nobody\n\ud83d\udd0d dbus\n\ud83d\udd0d systemd-coredump\n\ud83d\udd0d systemd-resolve\n\ud83d\udd0d tss\n\ud83d\udd0d polkitd\n\ud83d\udd0d sssd\n\ud83d\udd0d sshd\n\ud83d\udd0d deckerr\n\ud83d\udd0d unbound\n\ud83d\udd0d rtkit\n\ud83d\udd0d pipewire\n\ud83d\udd0d colord\n\ud83d\udd0d dnsmasq\n\ud83d\udd0d rpc\n\ud83d\udd0d chrony\n\ud83d\udd0d clevis\n\ud83d\udd0d usbmuxd\n\ud83d\udd0d saslauth\n\ud83d\udd0d gluster\n\ud83d\udd0d libstoragemgmt\n\ud83d\udd0d qemu\n\ud83d\udd0d geoclue\n\ud83d\udd0d cockpit-ws\n\ud83d\udd0d cockpit-wsinstance\n\ud83d\udd0d rpcuser\n\ud83d\udd0d pulse\n\ud83d\udd0d setroubleshoot\n\ud83d\udd0d flatpak\n\ud83d\udd0d gdm\n\ud83d\udd0d gnome-initial-setup\n\ud83d\udd0d avahi\n\ud83d\udd0d tcpdump\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d95c8901-5f7a-4156-b604-085fd149586e",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230449",
          "group_id_src": "V-230449",
          "rule_id": "SV-230449r1017249",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230449r1017249_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030420",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"truncate\", \"ftruncate\", \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", and \"open_by_handle_at\" system calls by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the truncate, ftruncate, creat, open, openat, and open_by_handle_at system calls in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"truncate\" and \"ftruncate\" functions are used to truncate a file to a specified length.\n\nThe \"creat\" system call is used to open and possibly create a file or device.\nThe \"open\" system call opens a file specified by a pathname. If the specified file does not exist, it may optionally be created by \"open\".\nThe \"openat\" system call opens a file specified by a relative pathname.\nThe \"name_to_handle_at\" and \"open_by_handle_at\" system calls split the functionality of \"openat\" into two parts: \"name_to_handle_at\" returns an opaque handle that corresponds to a specified file; \"open_by_handle_at\" opens the file corresponding to a handle returned by a previous call to \"name_to_handle_at\" and returns an open file descriptor.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nThe system call rules are loaded into a matching engine that intercepts each syscall made by all programs on the system. Therefore, it is very important to use syscall rules only when absolutely necessary since these affect performance. The more rules, the bigger the performance hit. The performance can be helped, however, by combining syscalls into one rule whenever possible.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215, SRG-OS-000064-GPOS-00033",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 generates an audit record upon successful/unsuccessful attempts to use the \"truncate\", \"ftruncate\", \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", and \"open_by_handle_at\" system calls by using the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep 'open\\|truncate\\|creat' /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\n-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S truncate,ftruncate,creat,open,openat,open_by_handle_at -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k perm_access\n\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EPERM\", this is a finding.\nIf the output does not produce rules containing \"-F exit=-EACCES\", this is a finding.\nIf the command does not return an audit rule for \"truncate\", \"ftruncate\", \"creat\", \"open\", \"openat\", and \"open_by_handle_at\" or any of the lines returned are commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230449"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230449",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'truncate' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'truncate' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'ftruncate' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'ftruncate' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'creat' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'creat' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'open' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'open' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'openat' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'openat' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'open_by_handle_at' do not exist.\nThe 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'open_by_handle_at' do not exist.",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'truncate' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'truncate' | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'ftruncate' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'ftruncate' | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'creat' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'creat' | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'open' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'open' | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'openat' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'openat' | grep b64\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'open_by_handle_at' | grep b32\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w 'open_by_handle_at' | grep b64\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'truncate':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'truncate' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'truncate' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'ftruncate':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'ftruncate' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'ftruncate' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'creat':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'creat' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'creat' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'open':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'open' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'open' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'openat':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'openat' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'openat' do not exist.\n\n\nChecking audit records are generated for 'open_by_handle_at':\n\u274c The 'arch=b32' audit rules for 'open_by_handle_at' do not exist.\n\u274c The 'arch=b64' audit rules for 'open_by_handle_at' do not exist.\n\n\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d99923c0-37b3-4710-9f82-0cf4aafbc961",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230238",
          "group_id_src": "V-230238",
          "rule_id": "SV-230238r1017057",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230238r1017057_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010161",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent system daemons from using Kerberos for authentication.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to prevent system daemons from using Kerberos for authentication.\n\nRemove any files with the .keytab extension from the operating system.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent system daemons from using Kerberos for authentication.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Unapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified and therefore cannot be relied upon to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DoD data may be compromised.\n\nRHEL 8 systems utilizing encryption are required to use FIPS-compliant mechanisms for authenticating to cryptographic modules.\n\nThe key derivation function (KDF) in Kerberos is not FIPS compatible.  Ensuring the system does not have any keytab files present prevents system daemons from using Kerberos for authentication.  A keytab is a file containing pairs of Kerberos principals and encrypted keys.\n\nFIPS 140-2 is the current standard for validating that mechanisms used to access cryptographic modules utilize authentication that meets DoD requirements. This allows for Security Levels 1, 2, 3, or 4 for use on a general-purpose computing system.",
          "check_content": "Verify that RHEL 8 prevents system daemons from using Kerberos for authentication.\n\nIf the system is a server utilizing krb5-server-1.17-18.el8.x86_64 or newer, this requirement is not applicable.\nIf the system is a workstation utilizing krb5-workstation-1.17-18.el8.x86_64 or newer, this requirement is not applicable.\n\nCheck if there are available keytabs with the following command:\n\n$ sudo ls -al /etc/*.keytab\n\nIf this command produces any file(s), this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230238"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000803"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230238",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000120-GPOS-00061",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "not_applicable",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "Neither the 'krb5-server' or the 'krb5-workstation' package is installed, per DISA this check is 'Not Applicable'",
          "finding_details": "#echo \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nyum list installed | grep -E 'krb5-server|krb5-workstation' \necho \"***XYLOK ICS***\"\nstat -c \"%n\" /etc/*.keytab\n\nChecking version of Kerberos installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d Neither the 'krb5-server' or the 'krb5-workstation' package is installed\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d9b1d10c-6012-4e62-9ecb-c53c4ec605f8",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230311",
          "group_id_src": "V-230311",
          "rule_id": "SV-230311r1155408",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230311r1155408_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010671",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the kernel.core_pattern.",
          "fix_text": "Configure RHEL 8 to restrict usage of ptrace to descendant processes by adding the following line to a dropfile in the \"/etc/sysctl.d\" directory:\n\nCreate a dropfile if it does not already exist:\n$ sudo vi /etc/sysctl.d/99-disable-coredump.conf\n\nAdd the following to the file:\nkernel.core_pattern = |/bin/false\n\nThe system configuration files need to be reloaded for the changes to take effect. To reload the contents of the files, run the following command:\n\n$ sudo sysctl --system",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must disable the kernel.core_pattern.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore, may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nThe sysctl --system command will load settings from all system configuration files. All configuration files are sorted by their filename in lexicographical order, regardless of which of the directories they reside in. If multiple files specify the same option, the entry in the file with the lexicographically latest name will take precedence. Files are read from directories in the following list from top to bottom. Once a file of a given filename is loaded, any file of the same name in subsequent directories is ignored.\n/etc/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/run/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf\n/etc/sysctl.conf",
          "check_content": "Verify RHEL 8 disables storing core dumps with the following commands:\n\n$ sudo sysctl kernel.core_pattern\n\nkernel.core_pattern = |/bin/false\n\nIf the returned line does not have a value of \"|/bin/false\", or a line is not returned and the need for core dumps is not documented with the information system security officer (ISSO) as an operational requirement, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230311"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230311",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'kernel.core_pattern' variable is set to '|/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump %P %u %g %s %t %c %h %e' returned by the 'sysctl' command, but should be set to '|/bin/false'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nsysctl kernel.core_pattern\n#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#grep -Er '^[[:space:]]*kernel.core_pattern' /run/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/local/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /usr/lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /lib/sysctl.d/*.conf /etc/sysctl.conf /etc/sysctl.d/*.conf 2>/dev/null\n\nChecking the value of the 'kernel.core_pattern' variable:\n\u274c kernel.core_pattern = |/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump %P %u %g %s %t %c %h %e\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "d9d79cc3-2bab-4f52-bc3c-6530c1470d70",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230302",
          "group_id_src": "V-230302",
          "rule_id": "SV-230302r1017112",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230302r1017112_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010590",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the \"/etc/fstab\" to use the \"noexec\" option on file systems that contain user home directories for interactive users.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must prevent code from being executed on file systems that contain user home directories.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "The \"noexec\" mount option causes the system not to execute binary files. This option must be used for mounting any file system not containing approved binary files, as they may be incompatible. Executing files from untrusted file systems increases the opportunity for unprivileged users to attain unauthorized administrative access.",
          "check_content": "Verify file systems that contain user home directories are mounted with the \"noexec\" option.\n\nNote: If a separate file system has not been created for the user home directories (user home directories are mounted under \"/\"), this is automatically a finding as the \"noexec\" option cannot be used on the \"/\" system.\n\nFind the file system(s) that contain the user home directories with the following command:\n\n$ sudo awk -F: '($3>=1000)&&($7 !~ /nologin/){print $1,$3,$6}' /etc/passwd\n\nsmithj:1001: /home/smithj\nrobinst:1002: /home/robinst\n\nCheck the file systems that are mounted at boot time with the following command:\n\n$ sudo more /etc/fstab\n\nUUID=a411dc99-f2a1-4c87-9e05-184977be8539 /home ext4 rw,relatime,discard,data=ordered,nosuid,nodev,noexec 0 2\n\nIf a file system found in \"/etc/fstab\" refers to the user home directory file system and it does not have the \"noexec\" option set, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230302"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230302",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "No entry for '/home' exists in '/etc/fstab'The Home Directory('/home') for user('deckerr') does not have an entry in '/etc/fstab'",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i \"HOME=\" /etc/default/useradd | grep -v \"^#\" |cut -d\"=\" -f2\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\n#Checking the default useradd home directory\ngrep -i \"HOME=\" /etc/default/useradd | grep -v \"^#\" |cut -d\"=\" -f2|xargs -I i grep i /etc/fstab\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ncat /etc/passwd\n#!/bin/bash\nFILENAME=\"/etc/passwd\"\nwhile IFS=: read -r username password userid groupid comment homedir cmdshell\ndo\n        if [[ \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/nologin\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/halt\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/sync\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/sbin/shutdown\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/false\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/bin/true\" && \"$cmdshell\" != \"/usr/sbin/nologin\" && \"$username\" != \"root\" ]]; then\n                echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\n                echo \"#USERNAME:$username\"\n                echo \"$homedir\" | xargs -I HOMEDIR dirname HOMEDIR\n                echo \"$homedir\" | xargs -I HOMEDIR dirname HOMEDIR | xargs -I DIR grep DIR /etc/fstab\n        fi\ndone < $FILENAME\n\nDetermining the default home directory in '/etc/default/useradd':\n/home\n\nChecking the default Home Directory('/home') for 'noexec' option:\n\u274c No entry for '/home' exists in '/etc/fstab'\n\nChecking existing interactive user home directories for an enty in '/etc/fstab':\n\u274c The Home Directory('/home') for user('deckerr') does not have an entry in '/etc/fstab'\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "da35de2c-1fb7-48b3-b605-2e2f29b01649",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230329",
          "group_id_src": "V-230329",
          "rule_id": "SV-230329r1017140",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230329r1017140_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "high",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010820",
          "rule_title": "Unattended or automatic logon via the RHEL 8 graphical user interface must not be allowed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nAdd or edit the line for the \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" parameter in the [daemon] section of the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file to \"false\":\n\n[daemon]\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Unattended or automatic logon via the RHEL 8 graphical user interface must not be allowed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Failure to restrict system access to authenticated users negatively impacts operating system security.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system does not allow an unattended or automatic logon to the system via a graphical user interface.\n\nNote: This requirement assumes the use of the RHEL 8 default graphical user interface, Gnome Shell. If the system does not have any graphical user interface installed, this requirement is Not Applicable.\n\nCheck for the value of the \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" in the \"/etc/gdm/custom.conf\" file with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep -i automaticloginenable /etc/gdm/custom.conf\n\nAutomaticLoginEnable=false\n\nIf the value of \"AutomaticLoginEnable\" is not set to \"false\", this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230329"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000366"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230329",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00229",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\nyum list installed |grep xorg-x11-server-Xorg\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -i automaticloginenable /etc/gdm/custom.conf\n\nChecking if a GUI is installed:\n\ud83d\udd0d xorg-x11-server-Xorg.x86_64                        1.20.11-27.el8_10                                           @appstream\n\nChecking the 'AutomaticLoginEnable' setting in '/etc/gdm/custom.conf':\n\u274c The 'AutomaticLoginEnable' setting was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "da6e1d9c-fab5-4d3e-8b34-e93b99a3c288",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230423",
          "group_id_src": "V-230423",
          "rule_id": "SV-230423r1017224",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230423r1017224_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030300",
          "rule_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the mount command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the audit system to generate an audit event for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"mount\" command by adding or updating the following rules in the \"/etc/audit/rules.d/audit.rules\" file:\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/mount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for the changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "Successful/unsuccessful uses of the mount command in RHEL 8 must generate an audit record.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter). The \"mount\" command is used to mount a filesystem.\n\nWhen a user logs on, the AUID is set to the UID of the account that is being authenticated. Daemons are not user sessions and have the loginuid set to \"-1\". The AUID representation is an unsigned 32-bit integer, which equals \"4294967295\". The audit system interprets \"-1\", \"4294967295\", and \"unset\" in the same way.\n\nSatisfies: SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000037-GPOS-00015, SRG-OS-000042-GPOS-00020, SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031, SRG-OS-000392-GPOS-00172, SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206, SRG-OS-000471-GPOS-00215",
          "check_content": "Verify that an audit event is generated for any successful/unsuccessful use of the \"mount\" command by performing the following command to check the file system rules in \"/etc/audit/audit.rules\":\n\n$ sudo grep -w /usr/bin/mount /etc/audit/audit.rules\n\n-a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/mount -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=unset -k privileged-mount\n\nIf the command does not return a line, or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230423"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-000169"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230423",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The audit rule for '/usr/bin/mount' was not found in '/etc/audit/audit.rules'\nThe audit rule for '/usr/bin/mount' was not found in the running audit rules",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep -w /usr/bin/mount /etc/audit/audit.rules\necho '***XYLOK ICS***'\nauditctl -l | grep -w /usr/bin/mount\n\nChecking for '/usr/bin/mount' in '/etc/audit/audit.rules':\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/mount' was not found\n\nChecking 'auditctl' for the '/usr/bin/mount' audit rule:\n\u274c The audit rule for '/usr/bin/mount' was not found\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "db64fd9b-e8af-426e-bdee-92e18b23c3e9",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230394",
          "group_id_src": "V-230394",
          "rule_id": "SV-230394r958754",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230394r958754_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "medium",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-030062",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.",
          "fix_text": "Edit the /etc/audit/auditd.conf file and add or update the \"name_format\" option:\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nThe audit daemon must be restarted for changes to take effect.",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must label all off-loaded audit logs before sending them to the central log server.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without establishing what type of events occurred, the source of events, where events occurred, and the outcome of events, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack.\n\nAudit record content that may be necessary to satisfy this requirement includes, for example, time stamps, source and destination addresses, user/process identifiers, event descriptions, success/fail indications, filenames involved, and access control or flow control rules invoked.\n\nEnriched logging is needed to determine who, what, and when events occur on a system.  Without this, determining root cause of an event will be much more difficult.\n\nWhen audit logs are not labeled before they are sent to a central log server, the audit data will not be able to be analyzed and tied back to the correct system.",
          "check_content": "Verify the RHEL 8 Audit Daemon is configured to label all off-loaded audit logs, with the following command:\n\n$ sudo grep \"name_format\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nname_format = hostname\n\nIf the \"name_format\" option is not \"hostname\", \"fqd\", or \"numeric\", or the line is commented out, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
            "V-230394"
          ],
          "ccis": [
            "CCI-001851"
          ],
          "group_tree": [
            {
              "id": "V-230394",
              "title": "SRG-OS-000342-GPOS-00133",
              "description": "<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"
            }
          ],
          "createdAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "updatedAt": "2026-03-28T04:09:31Z",
          "status": "open",
          "overrides": {},
          "comments": "The 'name_format' setting is set to 'NONE' in the '/etc/audit/auditd.conf' file, but should be set to 'hostname', 'fqd', or 'numeric'.\nname_format = NONE",
          "finding_details": "#echo '***XYLOK ICS***'\ngrep \"name_format\" /etc/audit/auditd.conf\n\nChecking that the Audit Daemon is configured to label all off-loaded audit logs:\n\u274c name_format = NONE\n\n\nXylok post-processing completed with no errors.\n"
        },
        {
          "uuid": "dbad517e-bd55-44dd-a535-fda82fea43c0",
          "stig_uuid": "e27566b5-e7a8-44d8-8939-9d31f0f583f8",
          "group_id": "V-230241",
          "group_id_src": "V-230241",
          "rule_id": "SV-230241r1017060",
          "rule_id_src": "SV-230241r1017060_rule",
          "target_key": null,
          "stig_ref": null,
          "weight": "10.0",
          "classification": "Unclassified",
          "severity": "low",
          "rule_version": "RHEL-08-010171",
          "rule_title": "RHEL 8 must have policycoreutils package installed.",
          "fix_text": "Configure the operating system to have the policycoreutils package installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum install policycoreutils",
          "reference_identifier": null,
          "group_title": "RHEL 8 must have policycoreutils package installed.",
          "false_positives": "",
          "false_negatives": "",
          "discussion": "Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the information system responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nPolicycoreutils contains the policy core utilities that are required for basic operation of an SELinux-enabled system. These utilities include load_policy to load SELinux policies, setfile to label filesystems, newrole to switch roles, and run_init to run /etc/init.d scripts in the proper context.",
          "check_content": "Verify the operating system has the policycoreutils package installed with the following command:\n\n$ sudo yum list installed policycoreutils\n\npolicycoreutils.x86_64                                              2.9-3.el8                                                  @anaconda\n\nIf the policycoreutils package is not installed, this is a finding.",
          "documentable": "",
          "mitigations": "",
          "potential_impacts": "",
          "third_party_tools": "Xylok",
          "mitigation_control": "",
          "responsibility": "",
          "security_override_guidance": "",
          "ia_controls": "",
          "check_content_ref": null,
          "legacy_ids": [
